<HEAD>Snowbirds Member Drunk In Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf to CORRECT spelling of colonel's name.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RECTOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A member of the Canadian Snowbirds precision military flying team was drunk when he crashed his car and died on the day he was to perform at an air show, authorities said Monday. Capt. <PERSON> Wesley </PERSON> <PERSON> MacKay </PERSON>, 28, of <LOCATION> Camrose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alberta </LOCATION>, had an alcohol concentration of 0.191 percent in his blood, said <PERSON> Skip </PERSON> <PERSON> Rusciewicz </PERSON>, deputy coroner for <LOCATION> Westmoreland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> law recognizes 0.10 as the level of intoxication. The crash occurred on a private road around 1 a.m. Saturday, police said. The Snowbirds were to perform 14 hours later. The pilots are not allowed to consume alcohol within eight hours of a flight, said Col. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Thibault </PERSON>, commander of Canadian Forces Base in Moose Jaw. Two other team members were injured in the crash.
