<HEAD>FAA Chief Says Air Safety Improving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Aviation safety is improving, and technology and training programs are now in place to prevent most major air disasters, the director of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. `` I reject any notion from anybody that would assert that aviation safety is somehow declining,'' <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said during a visit to the <ORGANIZATION> Mike </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monroney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Near-collision reports are down 67 percent from last year; pilot errors are down 63 percent and controller errors are down 18 percent, <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said. Also down are aviation-related fatalities and delays, he said. `` Aviation safety is improving. That does not mean aviation safety can not continue to improve. We have a lot of work to do. But we should never be caught in the trap of assuming that accident rates reflect aviation safety,'' he said, explaining that as air travel increases, the number of accidents also would increase. Technological advancements in such things as radar, combined with improved pilot training programs have reduced the danger of wind shear to air travelers, <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said. `` Wind shear has been with us since the dawn of aviation. But just now, we have the technology and the training that can recognize these microburst conditions,'' he said. He referred to sudden shifts in wind direction and speed caused when a mass of cooled air rushes downward out of a thunderstorm, a condition that can especially endanger planes taking off and landing. Just last week, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> announced that airplanes themselves will now be required to carry equipment that can detect wind shear, and to display steering commands so pilots can escape the conditions, <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said. In addition, he said all airlines are now training pilots in simulators to recognize conditions of wind shear and to escape from them safely. He said the 1985 crash of a <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> flight in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> that killed 137 people probably could have been prevented if such measures had been in place at the time.
</TEXT>
