<HEAD>China's First Consumer Cooperative Formed In Beijing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A neighborhood trying to buck bureaucracy, middlemen and rising inflation has created <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s first consumer food cooperative in 30 years. The Tiantan Residential Area Consumer Cooperative in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> opened in April and already has 9,000 members who paid 5 yuan -LRB- $ 1.30 -RRB- a share for access to fresh and sometimes cheaper vegetables, milk, eggs, matches, food oils and other consumer goods. `` Our only purpose is to serve the people,'' said the co-op's general manager, <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> <PERSON> Jingson </PERSON> It is run entirely by people living near the landmark Temple of Heaven in southern <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Consumer cooperatives existed in the early years after the Communist government came to power in 1949, but were taken over by the state in 1957, `` when our economy became more developed,'' <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> said. The idea has been revived three decades later as <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> goes through the painful process of ending price controls and letting the value of most food products be determined by market forces. Prices for many vegetables and other food items have doubled in the past year amid an overall inflation rate of around 20 percent. The reluctance of farmers to grow low-profit crops, difficulties in transport and widespread profiteering in scarce commodities have added to the price spiral, the most serious problem facing the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> economy today. The Tiantan Neighborhood <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> decided to start the co-op, <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> said, mainly to `` eliminate all kinds of troubles happening between producers and consumers.'' The cooperative has signed contracts with several farm villages outside <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> for supply and delivery of cucumbers, milk, sesame oil and other items, which are stocked in some of the 40 shops now run by the cooperative. Most of the 100 people working for the cooperative are retired from regular jobs or unemployed, <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> <PERSON> Xuyuan </PERSON>, 69, said she came out of retirement to run a little corner shop that sells soft drinks, canned goods and fresh foods because `` I wanted something to do.'' Now, she says she works up to 12 hours a day and takes home a wage pegged to the shop's sales and averaging about 100 yuan -LRB- $ 27 -RRB- a month, on a par with a factory worker's salary. Shoppers, she said, are `` quite satisfied, they've got no quarrels'' with the cooperative products. <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> said the little groceries barely break even, but the cooperative is earning good profits from several larger retail stores. He said shareholders should receive dividends larger than interest rates on bank savings deposits. He added that as <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> switches to a commodity-based economy, the government permits consumers to have various shopping options. The co-op, he said, will be a `` little brother'' to state-owned food shops and will not hurt the free markets that now supply urban residents with much of their better-quality if more expensive food. Although elimination of middlemen will mean better prices for co-op members, <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> said, prices will generally be pegged to those in state stores but that holding the line on price rises will be tough. He expressed confidence, however, that the co-op could provide good service at reasonable prices, `` and make things a little easier for our residents.''
</TEXT>
