<SECOND>PM-Botha-10 Years,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>Enthusiasm Scarce As Botha Marks 10 Years In Power</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> completes 10 years in power Wednesday, pressing ahead with policies that have disenchanted blacks and whites across <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s political spectrum. Not interested in charming his way to popularity, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> has presented himself as a stern, dedicated patriot leading his country on a precarious path between outright racism and black majority rule. Lately, his balancing act has won little praise. Growing numbers of right-wing whites feel he has gone too far in extending power to blacks, while white liberals and a solid core of blacks believe he has fallen woefully short. The criticisms, and increasingly frequent calls for new leadership, sometimes rankle <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, but he is unapologetic. `` My attitude is that I am doing what I believe to be right and in the interests of the country,'' he recently told a television interviewer who sought an assessment of 10 turbulent years. In his early years in power, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> had a broad mandate from whites for his twin goals of maintaining stability while moving away from rigid apartheid. The Sunday Times, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s largest newspaper and a critic of the government, commented this month, `` Mr. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s place in history is assured. It required courage to lead his people out of the cul-de-sac of apartheid, even if the final destination of their new course remains uncharted.'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, 72, became head of the white-minority government on Sept. 28, 1978, when <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> members elected him prime minister over more moderate and more conservative rivals. He had been in the Cabinet since 1961 and became defense minister in 1966. His first speech as prime minister stressed a theme that remains dear to him _ the paramount importance of national security in the face of a purported communist-led `` total onslaught.'' A year later, in one of his most quoted remarks, he sounded a different theme, telling whites: `` We must adapt, otherwise we will die.'' In 1984, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> helped push through a new constitution that brought Asians and people of mixed race into the previously all-white <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, but continued to exclude blacks. One result was black anger that ignited two years of nationwide political violence. The constitution abolished the post of prime minister, and <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> became president. His critics say he has steadily increased the power of the executive branch since then while weakening <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. Since 1984, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> has been credited with the repeal of several of apartheid's most hurtful laws, including those that banned interracial marriages and required blacks to have a permit to be in whites-only areas. These reforms, along with promises of limited power-sharing with blacks, triggered a wave of defections by <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s fellow Afrikaners from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to the extreme-right <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Botha </ORGANIZATION>'s anniversary comes as the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> verges on losing support of a majority of whites for the first time since it gained power 40 years ago. The party won 55 percent of the vote in whites-only general elections in May 1987, while 26 percent went to the <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and 19 percent to liberal candidates. The Conservatives are believed to have gained strength since then and could outpoll the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in nationwide local elections Oct. 26. Many liberals believe <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> has gone as far as he is willing to go toward substantive reform. The president has declared that some aspects of apartheid are non-negotiable _ he rejects equal voting rights for blacks and insists that whites retain segregated neighborhoods and schools. `` We are forever told that President <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s government has chosen the path fo reform and should be given a chance,'' wrote black newspaper editor <PERSON> Khulu </PERSON> <PERSON> Sibiya </PERSON>. `` What chance, when they move one step forward and three backwards?'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, whose government has detained thousands of black activists during a 27-month-old state of emergency, says most blacks view him favorably. Opinion polls suggest otherwise. This month, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> held his first summit meetings in black <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. He visited <LOCATION> Malawi </LOCATION>, a longtime friend of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, a longtime adversary. Some critics say <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> is more willing to take chances in the international arena than at home. `` One has to say that P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> lacks imagination,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Soal </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> member for the anti-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` He has failed to deal creatively with black political aspirations.'' Even some of <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s own Cabinet ministers feel he should step down, said Soal. `` Is there someone with the guts to tell him?''
</TEXT>
