<HEAD>Despot Ne Win May Still Be Calling The Shots In Burma</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ne Win, who resigned two months ago after 26 years of despotic rule, is widely believed to still be the top man in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> orchestrating moves to put down the anti-government uprising. Many Western diplomats and <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> believe <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON> has been calling the shots since he stepped down July 23 as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> that has ruled the country for a quarter century. `` I would say the almost universal perception and opinion among Burmese is that Ne Win is still the government of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>,'' a Rangoon-based diplomat said. Ne Win, 77, has remained out of public sight since he resigned, and there is no indisputable evidence he remains the most powerful figure. But observers characterize the men who have led the government since he stepped down as long-time associates of Ne Win who dare not make any major move without his assent. Diplomats said military commander Gen. Saw <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> visited Ne Win at his home in the plush northern <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> suburbs around scenic <LOCATION> Inya </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> before launching a coup Sept. 18 that began a harsh crackdown on pro-democracy protesters. The Rangoon-based diplomat said `` a number of -LRB- other -RRB- meetings have been held at critical times'' between Ne Win and top officials. <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON>, who became head of the party and state to succeed Ne Win in July, was a military leader known for his ruthlessness and long-time political association with Ne Win. When protests against <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON>'s authoritarian rule increased in August, he was replaced by civilian <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>, who served as Ne Win's legal adviser and wrote a flattering book about him called `` <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> and General Ne Win.'' <PERSON> Tzang </PERSON> <PERSON> Yawnghwe </PERSON>, an author and son of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s first president, described <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> as `` one of the few Burmese intellectuals who sincerely and deeply admired Gen. Ne Win.'' <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> was removed from power by <PERSON> Saw </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> when promises to hold the first multiparty elections since 1960 failed to end massive anti-government street demonstrations and a crippling general strike. <PERSON> Saw </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>, who was promoted to armed forces commander in 1985, is regarded as a hardliner who during most of his 39-year army career has loyally followed orders from Ne Win. Ne Win `` did n't raise up a generation of leaders but raised a generation of followers to do his bidding,'' a Bangkok-based diplomat observed. Another diplomat said the three successors are generally viewed as `` absolutely beholden'' to the charismatic Ne Win, whose unquestioned supremacy over the capable, well-organized 186,000-man military since his 1962 coup is seen as the key to his lasting power. The opposition so far has been unable to draw into its fold the rank-and-file soldiers and their officers, who in the past week shot and killed largely unarmed, peaceful demonstrators and broke up dozens of protest centers throughout the nation. `` What striking about it is the ruthlessness of his -LRB- Ne Win's -RRB- tactics,'' the Bangkok-based diplomat said. Japanese <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> expert <PERSON> Minoru </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiryu </PERSON> suggests, however, that events of recent weeks do not follow a `` Ne Win scenario,'' since the coup leaders abolished virtually all the state organizations built up by the military strongman. Ne Win first came to prominence as one of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s `` Thirty Comrades'' who played a key role in the fight for independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. He ended <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s shaky post-independence experiment with democracy by leading the 1962 coup. Ne Win quickly vowed to lead his country on a neutralist, egalitarian and moralistic `` Burmese road to socialism.'' But inefficiency, corruption and black marketeering soon spread throughout the system and <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>, rich in natural resources and once the world's largest exporter of rice, is now one of the world's poorest nations The failure to oust Ne Win and his cronies despite the popular uprising has led to `` certainly a tremendous mood of depression and disillusionment in the country,'' the Rangoon-based diplomat said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Biers </PERSON> is the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> news editor in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and is assisting in coverage of the <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> crisis.
