<SECOND>PM-Money Talks, Bjt,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Political Millions Dash Proxmire's Illusions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An illusion has been dashed for <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, who won his last <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> election in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> by shaking scores of thousands of hands and spending $ 145. <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> since 1957, won that election in 1982 with 64 percent of the vote and without spending a dime on television commercials. But in the scramble to succeed him _ a scuffle that began when he announced earlier this year that he would not seek re-election _ a new reality of the American political process emerged. <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> has found that money does in fact talk. The senator predicted the result earlier this year even before <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>'s voters picked free-spending millionaire businessman <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, who never has held public office, as the Democratic senatorial nominee over a list of veteran politicians. <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> described to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> the way he had established a victorious and enduring political career by shaking hands and ringing doorbells. He also correctly described what can happen when all that hard work comes up against big money. `` Meet just as many voters as you can _ day after day, month after month, year after year,'' <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> said in a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> speech. `` The numbers are critical,'' he said. `` They add up. You can literally meet hundreds every day. By campaigning on main streets and shopping malls for seven or eight hours a day you can hit a couple of thousand. `` Go out to baseball and football games, state fairs, busy summer festivals ... and you can meet as many as a thousand an hour _ literally. `` Keep that up year after year and you build remarkable long-term support,'' he said. `` When you run statewide a few times ... an astonishing number remember you. Many of the hundred-thousand people you met in your 1952 campaign for governor still remember meeting you when they vote in 1982. `` With every election that passes you have more of those beautiful voters in the bank.'' It was a `` magic'' that never failed him. But it was not a road that <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, a relatively unknown face, chose to follow. According to <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> got his name recognition with money, not by meeting voters one after the other. `` All that magic can blow away like a puff of smoke in a hurricane when your opponent turns up with $ 2 million or $ 3 million to buy television time and the good judgment of the experts to tell him precisely how to build on it,'' he said. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>'s Republican opponent, <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Engeleiter </PERSON>, minority leader of the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, also is mounting an extensive and expensive television campaign but is expected to be outspent by <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>, who had pumped $ 4 million into his campaign by the end of August. <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> said that as a result of <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>'s heavy spending in the Democratic primary campaign, `` the three Democratic candidates, qualified by years of service in public office and with long campaigning, were left far behind in the dust.'' <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>'s conclusion: `` Building constituent support one on one, serving well in public office, can help build a political career, but there is no substitute for money, and lots of it, wisely spent in buying the most seasoned and shrewd media advice and the television time to ring that bell. `` The candidate who has come from nowhere has been a smashing success in business,'' <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> said. `` He may, if elected, serve the country and our state as an excellent senator.'' `` But as a retiring senator who followed the other painstaking route of years of one-to-one hard campaigning work,'' <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> said, `` I am disillusioned _ and more than a little jealous.''
