<FIRST>r a PM-Shuttle-Marshall     09-27 0877</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle-Marshall,0901</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alabama Center Recovers From Challenger, But Warns Space Is Still
Dangerous</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 No matter the care taken and the tests conducted, eventually there will be another space accident and the <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> probably will once again be the target of the nation's anger and anguish. That, says <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, director of <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, is a truth engineers learn to live with at the <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> center that designs and develops the most dangerous parts of a space machine. `` Ours are the two high-risk elements _ the shuttle main engine and the shuttle solid rocket,'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said in an interview at the facility in the forested hills of northern <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. `` In 9 chances out of 10, when there is a catastrophic failure, it will rest with those two elements.'' `` When a mission goes good, the focus is going to be on the operations end,'' he said. `` When things go amiss, the attention is going to be right here ... It's not an unfair thing. We're big boys and we know that's the job we've got.'' A presidential commission concluded that the explosion that destroyed Challenger and killed its seven crew members on Jan. 28, 1986, was caused by a flawed solid rocket booster that blowtorched against the external tank. <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> engineers became personal targets of blame. Their judgment was ridiculed, their diligence belittled and their competence questioned. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulloy </PERSON>, who headed the solid rocket booster program at <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION>, received hate mail and endured the collapse of a 23-year career at <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>, director at <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, resigned, with parting, bitter shots at the press. Ten other managers also left, retiring or seeking jobs in private industry. None of the more than 3,400 workers at <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> escaped the stain. `` It was devastating,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Erwin </PERSON>, an engineer who analyzes stresses on the spacecraft. `` Everybody was pretty low. There was not so much a sense of guilt as of loss. There was also the sense of professional embarrassment. Something had gone terribly wrong and <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> was responsible.'' The drumbeat of blame, recalled <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, an organic chemist and materials expert, seemed to last forever. `` All the nails were driven in place and we were just hanging there and they were still beating on us,'' he said. `` Eventually it got to be too much ... We had accepted the responsibility. What we had to do then was make it right.'' That involved the most massive effort at reevaluation, repair and redesign ever attempted by <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>. Teams of engineers at <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> dissected every piece of hardware developed at the <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> center. Every design was reexamined. Every test was checked over and new ones were ordered where needed. Work days stretched from 10 to 12 to 14 hours, and, for many, weekends were forgotten. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said more tests were made on the main engines and on the solid rocket boosters than were conducted before the shuttle first flew in 1981. The goal was not to find out if the equipment was just `` good enough,'' but to demonstrate that it was better than it had to be. The full-scale solid rocket engine, with a new design for the flawed joint, was fired five times at a test site in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> by its manufacturer, <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. There were hundreds of other firings using sub-scale models or partial propellant loads. In one full-scale test, flaws were intentionally introduced to see if the new rocket had a margin of safety. It was a test never before attempted in the solid rocket industry. `` A lot of people inside and outside the agency did n't like that test because they thought it was pushing the engine too far,'' said <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>. If it had failed, it could have caused a long delay in shuttle flights. But <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> and the <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> engineers insisted because, he said, they `` believed in our design and wanted to go out on the test stand and prove it.'' The new rocket engine passed the test with margin to spare. Before Challenger, engineers recalled, dissent against consensus technical views was discouraged. Public differences of opinion were rare and quickly silenced. `` You were part of a team and it seemed a betrayal to take a contrary view,'' said one engineer. Challenger changed that. `` The accident strengthened the hand of the engineers in the trenches,'' said <PERSON> Erwin </PERSON>. `` Before, if you objected to something the manager could say you were overcautious because we had never had an accident. Now if a manager wants to yield to schedule pressures, we tell him that he's on his own.'' The new openness has resulted in conflicts unknown before Challenger. In one case, some experts believed a material in a solid rocket part needed one more test and refused to approve its use despite pressure from a manager. At conferences, it has become common for engineers to stand up and object to positions taken by their own managers. `` You admire a guy who has the courage to take a position different from the crowd,'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said. `` But that does n't mean it's a democracy. You're not going to launch with a democracy. You've got to have certain people in the system who make decisions and go.''
</TEXT>
