<FIRST>r a PM-Shuttle-MortonThiokol     09-27 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle-Morton Thiokol,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>Discovery Launch Marks Milestone On Morton Thiokol's Long Road
Back</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Thiokol </PERSON>, maker of the rocket booster that caused Challenger's destruction, hopes a successful launch for Discovery will begin an awakening from a 32-month-long corporate nightmare. It will be the `` final demonstration to our customer <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> and the country that solid rocket motors are going to be a reliable contributor to future shuttle successes,'' said <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, vice president and assistant general manager of space operations at <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Wasatch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>. Less easily dispatched are the specters of an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> investigation, lawsuits by frustrated former employees and a plague of rocket fuel-related accidents, including an MX missile motor fire that killed five employees last December. The presidential commission that investigated the Jan. 28, 1986, shuttle disaster found that an O-ring seal on the right booster rocket had stiffened in freezing pre-launch temperatures, allowing superheated gas to escape and trigger an explosion. Worse, the commission learned that several <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> engineers had argued the night before that just such a disaster could occur, but were overruled by superiors who told <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> the launch should proceed. In the relentless glare of the postmortem, <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Thiokol </PERSON> embarked on an exhaustive booster redesign that kept some 3,000 workers busy on the field joints as well as the case-to-nozzle motor joint, the nozzle assembly and hundreds of smaller components. `` It's been a very difficult period,'' said <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>. `` I do n't think any company is ever prepared for the kind of intense scrutiny that you get following a tragedy like Challenger. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> engineer who had argued against the Challenger launch, was made vice president of engineering for space operations _ overseer of the booster redesign. His guiding principle in the $ 500 million effort has been redundancy: multiple seals, bolts and clamps to contain the 1.1 million pounds of solid fuel that burn in just two minutes. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> has borne the redesign cost and <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> agreed to reap no profit. Engineers have conducted five $ 20 million full-scale test-firings of the redesigned boosters, as well as hundreds of sub-scale and component tests. A sixth full-scale test is planned for December. With 8,000 employees and an annual payroll of $ 220 million, <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>'s largest private employer. The Chicago-based company also produces munitions, salt and specialty chemicals, and manufactures first-stage motors for the MX, Trident 2 and Midgetman strategic missiles and propulsion systems for tactical missiles. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, a company vice president, said aerospace profits _ which account for more than a quarter of the company's overall profits _ fell from $ 96 million in fiscal 1986 to $ 73 million in 1987, then rose to $ 80.8 million in 1988. Even as <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Thiokol </PERSON> struggled to recover from Challenger, accidents further begrimed its public image. On Dec. 29, 1987, five men were killed when 108,000 pounds of fuel in an MX missile segment exploded, destroying a $ 6.2 million building at the complex 75 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The state cited <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> for six safety violations. Just last week, the company acknowledged that an old model of a nozzle inlet ring had been used in a motor test-fired in August. Analysis proved new versions had been placed in Discovery's boosters <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Thiokol </PERSON> also has been sued by former employees, among them <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON>, another engineer who protested the Challenger launch and later resigned. His lawsuits, seeking $ 3 billion, were recently dismissed. In mid-September, two former consultants, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Agee </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Laine </PERSON>, filed suit contending they were fired for attempting to bring redesign problems to light. Their suits also claim the company violated racketeering laws by filing false reports on its contractual obligations with <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Agee </PERSON> said on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>' `` West 57th'' Saturday that the entire booster system was unsafe and that he `` would n't even want to be around when they assemble the boosters and stack them prior to launch.'' Discovery's boosters, of course, have long been in place, assembly on a second set is nearly complete and a third set is being shipped to the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION>. And <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Malone </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the Kennedy Space Center, expressed confidence in the redesign and testing the boosters have undergone. <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Thiokol </PERSON> also is the subject of an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> inquiry into allegations by <PERSON> Agee </PERSON>, a contract engineer who worked undercover for the agency during his 4 -LCB- - month tenure as a safety analyst <PERSON> Agee </PERSON> alleged that, among other things, the company had concealed hazards from <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>.
