<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> have been negotiating plans for a `` white pride day'' rally at Independence Hall in November, a park official says. The park service expects to approve an application for a permit to hold the rally at the hall, where the Declaration of Independence and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Constitution were signed, Chief Ranger <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Burn </PERSON> said Monday. The application has not been filed yet, but will be soon, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Fogel </PERSON>, a Klan official who lives in <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lion </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>. For the past two weeks, the <ORGANIZATION> KKK </ORGANIZATION> and the park service have been discussing police protection, parking and other concerns associated with the rally scheduled for Nov. 5 at the hall, <PERSON> Burn </PERSON> said Burn said the application probably would be approved because `` under the First Amendment and the regulations we operate under, there's not much room for denying -LRB- it -RRB-.'' <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, an executive board member of the Philadlephia branch of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advancement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colored </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION>, agreed the Constitution gives the <ORGANIZATION> KKK </ORGANIZATION> the right to rally. But, she said, `` It is sad to see that people who have accepted violence as a way of life toward people who are not their race or creed can imbue others with their hatred. `` I do hope there will be so