<HEAD>Interest Up on Short-Term Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates on short-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities rose in the latest auction. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 7.0 billion in three-month bills at an average discount rate of 7.23 percent on Monday, up from 7.17 percent last week. Another $ 7.0 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 7.48 percent, up from 7.34 percent last week. The rates were the highest since three-month bills sold for 7.26 percent on Sept. 6 and six-month bills averaged 7.50 percent on Aug. 29. The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 7.47 percent for three-month bills with a $ 10,000 bill selling for $ 9,817.20 and 7.88 percent for six-month bills selling for $ 9,621.80. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that the average yield for one-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, rose to 8.07 percent last week after averaging 8.01 percent the week before.
