<HEAD>`Suds,' A New Musical, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Those great pop songs of the early 1960s will survive `` Suds,'' a numbing regurgitation of many of the musical hits of the era when the Beatles were changing the sound of popular music. There are some terrific musical memories including `` Respect,'' `` Dedicated to the One I Love,'' `` The Loco-Motion,'' `` Do <PERSON> Wah </PERSON> <PERSON> Diddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Diddy </PERSON>,'' `` You Don ` t Have to Say You Love Me,'' `` You Ca n't Hurry Love'' and nearly 40 other Top 10 tunes crammed into the show What sinks `` Suds'' is not the songs but the dippy story that authors <PERSON> Melinda </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilb </PERSON>, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunderson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> have inflicted on these golden oldies. It's dumb without being fun. They have set their musical in a Laundromat where <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON>, the world's oldest looking teen-ager, is celebrating her birthday _ alone and depressed. <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON>'s cat, Fluffy, has been run over by a Corvair, her pen pal boyfriend has dropped her because he found someone with better handwriting and she discovers she owes $ 10,000 to the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> for some relative's back taxes. <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> tries to end it all by wrapping pedal pushers around her neck, throwing them into a <ORGANIZATION> Maytag </ORGANIZATION> and agitating herself to death. She's stopped by two guardian angels, one named <PERSON> Dee </PERSON> <PERSON> Dee </PERSON> who looks like <PERSON> Marlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> on a bad day and the other, <PERSON> Marge </PERSON>, whose red bouffant hairdo confirms she has cornered the market on hairspray. The duo counsel the girl, trying to cheer her up and persuade her to get on with her life. It's these therapeutic sessions that take the form of musical interludes, usually three or four hit numbers stitched together. Occasionally, they take off, like a funny version of `` Secret Agent Man,'' done with style by <PERSON> Gunderson </PERSON>, who plays all the men and even one woman in the show. More often, you grow impatient with the dialogue, waiting for the story to end and the music to begin again. The cast is competent but not distinguished. The women _ <PERSON> Christine </PERSON> <PERSON> Sevec </PERSON>, <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosher </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gilb </PERSON> _ belt out the songs with gusto if not any particular style. `` Suds,'' which opened last weekend, is the first attraction at Stage Left, a cabaret theater in the Criterion Center. The Center is an impressive theater complex located in Times Square and also contains a more formal theater which will open later in the year. The playing area has good sightlines and comfortable seating. Now all it needs is a show.
