 Things have turned nasty in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> race where Democratic incumbent <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> opponent already has called his rival a liar, a coward and a crummy boss <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, a two-term <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> veteran, is known to most of the world as a professorial type who writes a lot of books, taught at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> and served as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. But Republican <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> is hoping to expose another side of <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> using an aggressive campaign with sharp personal attacks, and, in the process, salvage an underfunded and underpublicized effort to unseat <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>. It's a long shot gamble. <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> claims, is an arrogant and overrated senator who was `` chicken'' to debate him, condones `` safe sodomy'' for homosexuals, lies to the press, is too abrasive to keep employees on his staff and too lazy to do his official duties in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` What kind of a man is this <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>?'' <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> asked last month. `` He's on the record as one who would lie, if he thought he could get away with it.'' <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, 61, has tried to appear above the fray in the face of <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON>'s charges. When asked about being called a liar, <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> said only, `` I heard that. That's OK. I've been called worse things than that.'' <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON>, 56, a wealthy <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> 