e <ORGANIZATION> Marist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opinion </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Poughkeepsie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, showed him with a 63-21 percent lead over <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> among 601 likely voters. Financially, <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> has little hope of matching <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> in spending. The most recent contribution filing with the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> showed <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON>'s campaign $ 40,000 in debt while <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> had $ 1.9 million in the bank. Since starting his campaign May 9, <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> has been on the road almost constantly, appearing at county fairs, political picnics and local television and radio stations. He has logged about 27,000 miles by car. In that time, the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> candidate has tried to prove that <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>'s intellectual bent has n't paid dividends for New Yorkers since the former <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> professor won election to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1976. <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> says <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> has exercised `` benign neglect'' toward New Yorkers as senator. <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> says `` I plead guilty'' about his enthusiasm for writing and lecturing, but insists that one of his senatorial duties is to articulate the issues. And, <PERSON> O'Donnell </PERSON> says <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> has been responsible for delivering about $ 5 billion in federal aid to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in his second term alone. <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> has also tried to make political hay by pointing out that <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> has missed more than 400 ro