<HEAD>$206 Million Farm Research Bill Gets House Approval</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An agricultural research bill to provide $ 206 million for programs ranging from alternative crops to fish farming is headed for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> after winning approval in the House. `` The land is the only thing that can produce new wealth for this vast economic empire we call the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and it begins with research,'' Agriculture Chairman E. `` Kika'' de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said Monday as the bill received <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approval on a voice vote. Research grants to develop new types of crop production would be authorized by the bill. The measure also would establish a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alternative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> within the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. A non-profit <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercialization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> also would be created that would use loans, loan guarantees, interest subsidies and other means to spur product commercialization. Under the measure, $ 20 million a year through fiscal year 2000 would be authorized for development of new agricultural products, $ 15 million to commercialize products and up to $ 600,000 to enhance marketing of existing ones. The bill's overall price tag was estimated by the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> at $ 206 million over five years. With perhaps three weeks to go before lawmakers adjourn, however, the future of the measure is clouded. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has offered no guarantees that it will get to the measure. The bill would establish grants for research into statistical methods of measuring chemicals and microorganisms in food products and means of preventing contamination. Also under the measure, an office of groundwater policy determination would be established within the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. That provision was included at the urging of Republican Rep. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Grandy </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, where concern is growing over findings of pesticide contamination in groundwater. The bill would provide $ 3 million in each of three years for research into aquaculture, or fish farming. It also would reauthorize federal research aid for examination and development of crops used in so-called critical materials. The measure would set the program at an $ 8 million level for each of the next two years. Most money under that program would go to research into guayule _ a plant grown in the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> that produces a natural rubber that can be used for high-performance aircraft tires. The bill would enable farmers to plant so-called alternative crops in 1989 and 1990 without losing their base acreage listed with the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>. The base acreage is used to calculate the size of the federal payments they get for producing wheat, feed grains, cotton and rice. Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved on a voice vote a separate measure to establish a 25-member Commission on the Improvement of the Federal Crop Insurance Program. Ten of the 21 voting members would come from the insurance industry and 10 from among agricultural producers with the manager of the corporation also serving on the panel. The four non-voting members would come from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The goal of the panel would be to recommend changes in the program, which has lost more than $ 1 billion since 1980 when a major overhaul was approved.
