<SECOND>PM-Wages,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Number Of Low-Wage Jobs Is Rising</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Minimum Wage Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of working Americans with wages below the poverty level for a family of four increased by more than 1 million last year, according to a new <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> report. The report, prepared by the Democratic staff of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> from <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> data, concluded that both high-paying and low-paying jobs have grown at the expense of a shrinking middle class over the past eight years. Fueling the debate over the quality of 16 million new jobs since President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> took office, the report was immediately criticized by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republicans </ORGANIZATION> as `` misleading and inaccurate.'' `` Sixty-four percent of American jobs paid middle level wages -LRB- defined as those between $ 11,611 and $ 46,444 in 1987 dollars -RRB- in 1979,'' said the report, released Monday. `` Between the peak of the business cycle in 1979 and the latest year of the current expansion in 1987, only 38 percent of the increase in employment was in middle wage jobs,'' it added. As a result, according to the data, the share of middle-wage earners declined from 64 percent to 61.3 percent between 1979 and 1987. Those earning a poverty wage climbed from 32.4 percent to 34.2 percent and those with high wages -LRB- more than $ 46,444 -RRB- rose from 3.7 percent to 4.5 percent of the working population. The committee's chairman, retiring Sen. <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., said a comparison of the 1987 data from the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>'s Current Population Survey released earlier this month with 1986 data shows a worsening of the trend According to the data, 40.45 million workers were paid a full-time equivalent of less than $ 11,611 last year, compared with 39.38 million in 1986. Meanwhile, the number of Americans with jobs exceeding $ 46,444 fell from 5.4 million in 1986 to 5.32 million last year. `` The sad truth,'' <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> said, `` is that jobs paying below the poverty level are growing faster than any other kind. And jobs that provide a middle-class standard of living are a shrinking part of our job landscape.'' Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the committee's ranking Republican and former chairman, called the report `` opportunistic, political, misleading and inaccurate'' and predicted that it eventually will be discredited. `` Most of the new jobs created during the expansion have been in occupations that pay well _ in technical and managerial fields, the kind of jobs we want for our kids,'' he said. `` Only 8 percent of the jobs generated by this expansion pay under $ 7,000 annually.'' The only group going against the trend was women, according to the report. Middle-wage and high-wage jobs among them increased by 1.2 percentage points and 0.5 percentage points to 55.4 percent and 1.8 percent, respectively, over the past eight years. The share of women in the workforce with low-paying jobs, meanwhile, fell from 44.6 percent in 1979 to 42.9 percent last year. Men fared the worst, with the middle-income share falling from 72.1 percent in 1979 to 66.6 percent last year. The share of low-wage earners among men climbed from 22.3 percent to 26.5 percent over the same period while the proportion of high-wage earners rose from 5.6 percent to 6.9 percent. Among blacks and other minorities, the share of low-income workers and high-income earners increased by 1.2 percentage points and 0.6 percentage points to 41.7 percent and 2.3 percent respectively. The proportion of middle-income minority workers declined from 57.8 percent to 56 percent over the eight years.
</TEXT>
