 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has already turned his closing statement from the first presidential debate into a tag line for two campaign commercials that begin airing tonight. `` The best <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is not behind us, the best <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is yet to come,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> says in both 30-second spots. One, called `` Opportunity,'' includes only the closing lines from his Sunday night debate with <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Wake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C </LOCATION>. The other, `` Our Concern,'' focuses on his pitch for universal health insurance, but also mentions college opportunity and includes the closing line. The length of the run has not been determined, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Lorraine </PERSON> <PERSON> Voles </PERSON> said Monday. `` We have an opportunity, working together, to build that future, to build a better <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, to build a best <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said at the close of the debate in a passage also frequently found in his stump speeches. `` Because the best <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> does n't hide; we compete,'' he continued. `` The best <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> does n't waste; we invest. The best <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> does n't leave some of its citizens behind; we bring everyone along. And the best <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is not behind us. The best <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is yet to come.'' The health care pitch focuses on the Democratic nominee's promise to seek legislation requiring most employers to provide health insurance to their workers `` I think it's time that when you got a job in this country that it came with health insurance,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> says in the debate footage. The passage from the closing statement was chosen for an ad because it focuses on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' effort to win broad support among middle class voters _ a segment <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has characterized as victims of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> recovery. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aides had planned to use at least one segment from the debate, and likely the closing statement, for a new ad and then also decided to make a second ad with the health care material, campaign aides said.
