<HEAD>Government Analysts Say Food Aid To Poor Nations May Fall Further</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Food aid to needy countries has dropped and could fall further because of rising commodity prices, according to <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> analysts. The Food and <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> agency, estimates that aid in the form of cereal grain shipments in the 12 months ended June 30 was about 10.5 million metric tons, down 14 percent from 12.2 million tons a year earlier. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Nightingale </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> provided 65 percent of last year's 10.5 million tons and `` was followed distantly'' by the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> with 15 percent; <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, 10 percent; and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, each with about 3 percent. For the fourth consecutive year, he said, the 1974 <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> goal of 10 million tons of food aid was exceeded last year. `` However, given no significant increases in the major donors' 1988-89 food-aid budgets, and higher commodity prices, the volume of food aid may fall in 1988-89, and achievement of the 10-million-ton-goal is doubtful,'' <PERSON> Nightingale </PERSON> said The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid program under Food for Peace, or P.L. 480 as it is also known, was increased nearly 5 percent for the fiscal year ending Sept. 30 to nearly $ 1.5 billion. Nightingale, writing in the October issue of Agricultural Outlook magazine, said about two-thirds of the volume under Food for Peace was wheat and wheat products, while feed grains and vegetable oils made up about 5 percent each. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, dairy products, pulses and other products made up the remainder. <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> accounted for nearly half the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allocations in 1987-88; <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, about a third, and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, about a fifth. <PERSON> Nightingale </PERSON> said the dollar amount of the 1988-89 allocations under Food for Peace has not been decided but that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has requested about $ 1.4 billion, which effectively would roll back the 5 percent increase of 1987-88. The 1988-89 money for Food for Peace is included in <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> appropriation bills currently being negotiated by a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference committee. <PERSON> Nightingale </PERSON> said that with few exceptions crop prospects in developing countries `` look good this season'' and that food supplies are up relative to current consumption. `` However, greater assistance is needed this year to rebuild stocks that were drawn down heavily last year,'' he said. Grains are the mainstay of food aid, with cereals making up 75 percent of the diet in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and 50 percent to 70 percent in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Nightingale </ORGANIZATION> said. Although these regions produce a large share of the world's cereal crops, much that enters world trade is grown in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, where drought has reduced supplies this year. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> monitors 55 countries for signs of food shortfall. Newly available information on the food-aid share of some countries' food imports `` indicates greater dependence on aid than previously thought,'' <PERSON> Nightingale </PERSON> said. Some countries have allocated less foreign exchange to food imports than thought earlier, he said. And because prices are up, the estimated amount of commercial imports will be only 6.5 million tons, compared with 11.7 million in 1987-88.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says three food stamp projects using plastic magnetic strip cards instead of paper coupons will be conducted in parts of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. Assistant Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bode </PERSON> said Monday that nearly 30,000 food stamp households in the three states will use the cards to see if the system will be easier for people to use and to help reduce lost or stolen coupons. The projects are scheduled to begin within the next 8 to 12 months and run for at least three years, he said. An evaluation will be made to see if the electronic system might be used nationally. Bode said the $ 1.3 million project will operate by running the plastic cards through a computer terminal at grocery checkout counters. The cost of the food will be automatically deducted from the family's total monthly food stamp allotment. In addition, he said, some of the food stamp recipients will be able to use the same plastic cards for other public benefits, such as Aid for Families With Dependent Children. Bode said <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> will get $ 580,853 from <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> to design its projects, which will be tested in <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION>, with services to 6,500 households. <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> will receive $ 385,309 to test kits system in <LOCATION> Ramsey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> among 13,000 households, and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> will get $ 379 for its test in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION> among 10,150 households. Nationally, nearly 19 million people are getting food stamp benefits, based on family size and adjusted household incomes. The program costs about $ 12.6 billion a year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some penjing trees from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> are out of federal quarantine and will be dedicated at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> National Arboretum on Sept. 30, says the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Penjing trees are dwarf versions of forest species and are the result of a 1,200-year-old art, says arboretum director <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Cathey </PERSON>. The specimens, a gift to the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people, are 20 to 100 years old and are only three feet high. <PERSON> Cathey </PERSON> said Monday that the penjing trees will be dedicated and opened to public display on Sept. 30. The trees were donated by penjing experts <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yee-sun </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lui </PERSON> Shu-ying on June 25, 1986, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. All specimens have been held in quarantine at the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> plant introduction station in <LOCATION> Glenn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, to guard against the introduction of pests and diseases.
