<HEAD>First Lady Attends Met Opera Opening</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Luciano </PERSON> <PERSON> Pavarotti </PERSON>'s singing was ravishing and his co-stars were in sterling voice for the Metropolitan Opera's opening night performance of `` Il Trovatore'' Monday, but the production lacked excitement, at times resembling a concert more than an opera The staging of the <LOCATION> Fabrizio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Melano </LOCATION> production, which was new last November, works against excitement. The set is a high staircase extending across the stage. Most of the time, the singers take turns standing alone on the stairs. The stage is kept dark, with a changing backdrop of dark and white clouds. Of the three stars, <PERSON> Sherrill </PERSON> <PERSON> Milnes </PERSON> took vocal honors in the first two acts, his voice strong and warm from the first note, while <PERSON> Pavarotti </PERSON> and <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> Marton </PERSON> held back for the last two acts. <PERSON> Pavarotti </PERSON>, as <PERSON> Manrico </PERSON>, was tender with the <LOCATION> Leonora </LOCATION>, sung by <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> Marton </PERSON>, and with <PERSON> Azucena </PERSON>, sung by <PERSON> Fiorenza </PERSON> <PERSON> Cossotto </PERSON>. When there was reason for <ORGANIZATION> Manrico </ORGANIZATION> to be firm, <PERSON> Pavarotti </PERSON>'s tones became stalwart. He also acted effectively, using spare but telling gestures. In 1976, <PERSON> Pavarotti </PERSON> sang at the Met's opening night in this same opera. It was his first Met venture into heavier roles than the light, clear bel canto parts he had been singing. One heard strain in his voice as he repeatedly sang <PERSON> Manrico </PERSON> that season. Now, the role sounds natural and totally unstrained. Miss <PERSON> Marton </PERSON> was singing <PERSON> Leonora </PERSON> at the Met for the first time. Her voice is closer to being shrill than soft and sweet, but she has the volume, flexibility and stamina for the part. The last-act duet with <PERSON> Milnes </PERSON>