<HEAD>Engineer Who Tried To Stop Challenger Launch Still Rebuilding Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's taken <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> 32 months to recover from Challenger and get ready to try again. It may take <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> even longer. <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON>, then one of the chief engineers for rocket manufacturer <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION>, warned his bosses on Jan. 27, 1986, that a flawed rocket booster design could fail if Challenger was launched from the <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in freezing temperatures. His concerns were ridiculed by <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials, then rejected by <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Thiokol </PERSON> managers. The space shuttle blew up the next day, exactly as <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> feared. He believes that despite a costly redesign and testing effort, the rocket engines still have potentially disastrous weak spots. `` To me, it's just another disaster waiting to happen,'' said the 50-year-old engineer. Discovery is scheduled to lift off Thursday on the first manned <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space mission since Challenger. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which has reviewed the booster redesign and testing, say the new rocket engine is not perfect, but is much safer than the one that failed with Challenger. Challenger was destroyed when pressurized flame leaked from a joint between segments in one of the shuttles's pair of solid-fuel rocket boosters, touching off an explosion that killed all seven astronauts. In testimony before the <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> which investigated the accident, <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> revealed that <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Thiokol </PERSON> knew the rocket engines had leaked on past launches and were working toward a solution even while continuing shuttle flights. Afterward, <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> said, he was shunned by fellow workers and neighbors, and <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Thiokol </PERSON> put him on the sidelines while work started on a redesign of the rocket joint. `` When I realized what was happening, it absolutely destroyed me,'' <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> said in a recent telephone interview. `` It destroyed my career, my life, everything else. I'm just now getting back to the point where I think I'll be able to work as an engineer again.'' A doctor said <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> was suffering from traumatic stress syndrome, and the engineer took medical leave from <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION>. Later, <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> named the company in a series of lawsuits that sought recovery of $ 2.07 billion for himself and the federal government. The last of the suits was dismissed earlier this month by a judge. In the past year, <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> has toured the country, speaking before engineering groups and attacking what he believes is a `` business as usual'' attitude in <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> and at <LOCATION> Morton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Thiokol </LOCATION>. His theme is simple: Engineers have the obligation to report shoddy work or design when they find it because people's safety is at stake. But, says <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON>, the life of a whistleblower is often unpleasant and could be personally disastrous. `` They -LRB- whistleblowers -RRB- should know that if they do speak out against their organization they will pay some sort of a price,'' he said. <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> has received major awards from the American Association for the Advancement of Science and the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> for his efforts to stop the Challenger launch and to make changes in the shuttle rocket design. `` The very fact that some people are interested in what I stand for has been very encouraging,'' he said. But <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> said he is still looking for work, and added sadly, `` It's not the easiest thing to do to get a new job at 50 years old even under normal conditions.'' His home near the Morton Thiokol plant in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> is up for sale. <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON> and his wife hope to move to <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>. Wherever he goes, said <PERSON> Boisjoly </PERSON>, he's going to avoid watching shuttle launches on television. `` I just do n't want to go through that hell again,'' he said.
