<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More rain fell today in flooded parts of the northern state of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, hampering operations to rescue at least 200,000 people marooned by rising waters, an official said. Fifty air force helicopters were deployed to lift people to safer areas, but the operations were disrupted by rains, said J.F. <PERSON> Ribeiro </PERSON>, adviser to the state governor. <PERSON> Ribeiro </PERSON> said at least 138 people have died in the flooding, mainly from drownings, in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> since it began Wednesday. He said the inundation had claimed at least 200 lives in the neighboring states of <LOCATION> Haryana </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Himachal </PERSON> <PERSON> Pradesh </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Jammu </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, the most populated of the four states, has borne the brunt of the floods. The state's road and rail links with the rest of the country were cut off, though airports were still functioning. The three major rivers in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Ravi </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Beas </PERSON> and Sutlej were all flowing above danger levels, <PERSON> Ribeiro </PERSON> said. He said six of the state's nine administrative districts had been affected. More than 1,500 villages in the six districts were inundated and waters have entered low-lying areas of <LOCATION> Ludhiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kapurthala </LOCATION> cities, he said. The floods were caused by heavy rains in northern <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> as the annual southwest monsoon draws to a close. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, authorities ordered the closure of a bridge over the adjacent <LOCATION> Jamuna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, which is also flowing above the danger mark. A government official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, told reporters Monday that Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> had appointed a crisis mana