<HEAD>Cool Autumn Air Chills Northern Plains, Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Cool autumn air chilled parts of the <LOCATION> northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> and the Northeast today and scattered showers dampened the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. A cold front pushed through the <LOCATION> central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> today, dropping early morning temperatures into the 30s and 40s in the northern Plains. Temperatures were in the 40s in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and the northern Appalachians because of a cool Canadian air mass centered over <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state. Readings dropped into the 30s in some parts of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. Thunderstorms dumped locally heavy rain on parts of the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Keys </LOCATION>, and thunderstorms also were scattered over northern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Further north, fog draped the southern and central Appalachians, reducing visibility to near zero in parts of southeast <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>. Showers ahead of an approaching cold front scattered light rain over the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>. Most other parts of the country enjoyed fair skies. Today's forecast called for showers across the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> and the northern Plateau region, and northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Showers and thunderstorms were expected in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Dakotas </LOCATION>. Clouds were expected in the upper <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION>, but skies were predicted to be mostly sunny elsewhere. Highs were forecast to be in the 50s and 60s across the country's northern tier from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and the northern Great Lakes to the <LOCATION> Pacific