<SECOND>PM-CDC-Hot Lab,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>CDC Unveils New `Hot Lab' For Studying World's Deadliest Viruses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> researchers soon will move into their new `` hot lab,'' a $ 20 million super-sealed laboratory with a 21st century feel, to study the world's deadliest viruses. <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> officials unveiled it Monday, showing off the secret-code passageways, air locks, decontamination equipment, containment cabinets and space suits that will be off-limits to all outsiders once deadly pathogens are brought in starting next month. The complex will be formally dedicated Oct. 28. For years, the center has studied what scientists call Level 4 pathogens: mircroorganisms or viruses with the most dangerous classification according to deadliness, availability of vaccine or treatment and risk of transmission in the laboratory. Such agents include Ebola hemorrhagic fever, Lassa fever and <LOCATION> Rift </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> fever, diseases rarely, if ever, seen in this country and much more hazardous in the lab than AIDS or rabies, said Dr. <PERSON> Olen </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kew </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Molecular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> at the center. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s first facility for the study of such pathogens, built in 1967, was in a large trailer. Two larger labs followed. The new facility, officially known as the Viral and Rickettsial Diseases Laboratory but called `` the hot lab'' by those who work there, will give <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> researchers more space and more modern technology than they've ever had before, said Dr. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiley </PERSON>, a microbiologist with the Office of Biosafety. `` After 10 years, the old Level 4 lab was beginning to show its age,'' <PERSON> Kiley </PERSON> said. `` This will very much contribute to our overall mission of controlling infectious disease ... around the world,'' said Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s Center for Infectious Diseases. The laboratory building, located at the federal health agency's compound near <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, spans more than 95,000 square feet and is actually two buildings in one _ a six-story facility containing 12 separate labs, and a three-story Level 4 facility with two separate state-of-the-art containment labs, connected by a central atrium The new labs also have intricate waste disposal facilities, to inactivate, then remove, any hazardous substances. Walls in the new Level 4 facility are poured concrete, 9 inches thick. Inside, the labs themselves, researchers will wear blue plastic space suits, connected to a safe air supply by red hoses which dangle from various points above them. To enter their lab, they will pass through a series of increasingly secure checkpoints _ from the card-key system which opens the outer corridor doors, to a secret-code control which opens inner doors, to heavy, submarine-style steel gasket doors opening into a special chemical shower and air lock. That, in turn, opens onto the lab. Getting in takes about five minutes; getting out takes about 20, as workers shower first in their space suits _ with a special disinfectant fluid _ then take showers themselves. `` We go out to lunch sometimes, but you do n't drink a lot of coffee in the morning,'' joked research microbiologist <PERSON> Luanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON>. `` It takes too long to get in and out.''
</TEXT>
