<HEAD>Judge Approves Settlement for Owners of Kodak Instant Cameras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some 3.4 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> owners of <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s discontinued instant cameras should get up to $ 70 in cash and coupons just in time for Christmas under a new settlement. `` I think both sides agree it's an excellent settlement,'' said <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, one of four attorneys who filed the class-action lawsuit against <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>, saying he was `` very, very pleased'' after Monday's decision. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>, which was forced to stop making instant cameras and film after a patent dispute, said the settlement is worth $ 150 million, but attorneys for camera owners pegged it at more than $ 200 million. The settlement approved by <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judge </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> applies to 39 <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> instant camera models, ranging from the Fiesta, the lowest-priced model, to the Kodamatic 980L, the most expensive. <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> said the cash and coupons would probably be mailed in late November, in time for Christmas shopping. Depending on the cost of their instant camera, owners will receive amounts ranging from $ 52 in cash and $ 18 in coupons to $ 19.50 in cash and $ 30.50 in coupons. The coupons, accompanied by proof of purchase, then can be sent to the company for a rebate. The coupons could also be used in purchasing Kodak products such as film, cameras or batteries. `` From <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>'s point of view, it's good and fair,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> attorney representing the <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, company. The lawsuit was filed against the company in January 1986, asking that it compensate owners for instant cameras that were virtually useless after a ruling against <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> in its legal battle with <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. A federal judge in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> infringed on <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s instant-camera patent when it entered the market in Instant photography was invented by Dr. <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Land </PERSON>, founder of <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>, and was first marketed in 1948. It enables users to view a photographic print shortly after taking a picture. Polaroid retained a monopoly in the instant photography field until 1976, when <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> entered the market with a competing system. Polaroid immediately filed a lawsuit, charging patent infringement. A federal judge in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> sided with <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> let stand lower court rulings when it refused to hear <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>'s appeal in October 1986.
