 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has concluded a rocket launching into the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> and normal navigation and air flights through the area can resume Wednesday, the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> announced today. The report did not say when the launching took place or what was the purpose of launching the `` carrier'' rocket. Western military experts in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> speculated that the launch either could be a test of new models of satellite booster rockets now being developed or, more likely, a <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> missile. On Sept. 8, <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> warned ships and planes to stay out of the target area, located about 112 miles off of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Zhejiang </LOCATION> province and with a radius of 35 nautical miles, between 10 a.m. and 5 p.m. from Sept. 14 to Oct. 3.
