 Twelve young friends from a <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> welfare hotel got a taste of TV stardom when they were invited to appear on the soap opera `` <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>'s Hope.'' An actress on the show, <PERSON> Ilene </PERSON> <PERSON> Kristen </PERSON>, invited the children to perform in an episode after she met them in July when she volunteered to teach acting, singing and fitness at the hotel. Paid union scale of $ 97 each, they performed Monday in an episode in which welfare hotel residents chase a drug dealer from their neighborhood. <PERSON> Antoine </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, 12, who lives with his family in an apartment now, had made such an impression on <PERSON> Kristen </PERSON> that he was given a primary role with several speaking lines. `` No, I'm confident, babe,'' he told her when asked if he wanted to rehearse. The episode is to air Oct. 6.
