<HEAD>Helmsleys' Tax Case Delayed; Billionaire's Health Problems
Revealed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The tax evasion trial of real estate magnate <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> and his hotel queen wife, <PERSON> Leona </PERSON>, has been delayed until early next year because of a legal appeal. The decision by U.S. District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> on Monday was unrelated to a defense lawyer's claim that the 79-year-old <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> suffers from `` acute memory difficulties.'' In a affidavit filed late last week, <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>'s attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wing </PERSON> wrote the judge that his client's memory problems `` render him unable to assist adequately in his own defense.'' After examinations by five neurologists and neuro-psychologists, all but one of `` concluded that Mr. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> has a significant memory disability,'' Wing said. Wing, who sought an indefinite delay of the businessman's trial, said, `` forcing him to stand trial in his present condition would effectively deprive him of his constitutional rights.'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, who has postponed the <ORGANIZATION> Helmsleys </ORGANIZATION>' trial twice before, delayed the case until Jan. 16 because of a legal appeal by Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> and a court scheduling conflict. The Helmsleys were indicted in April on state and federal charges that they allegedly disguised about $ 4 million in renovations to their <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, mansion as business expenses and took bogus tax deductions. The Helmsleys and two former aides have pleaded innocent to the 188-count state indictment and the 47-count federal indictment. State prosecutors have agreed to let the federal case go first. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>, 67, is appealing <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>'s denial of her bid to dismiss the federal indictment. She said she was granted immunity from prosecution for her grand jury testimony in an earlier state sales tax investigation. Prosecutors say court papers on the appeal could not be filed until Oct. 14. Also, one of the defense attorneys begins a previously scheduled trial on Nov. 21 before another judge. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said an unidentified doctor `` interviewed and examined'' <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> over the weekend and `` expressed some views to me'' over the telephone. The judge said he would not rule on the defense motion to sever <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> from the case until he sees the doctor's written report
