<HEAD>ACLU Official Accuses Bush of `McCarthyite Slander'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Eds: Top 8 grafs new with <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> official's comments; picks up pvs 3rd graf bgng, `` In terms.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> today accused Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> of `` McCarthyite slander'' against the organization during his nationally televised debate Sunday night with Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. The official, <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> Glasser </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s statement that the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> is involved in a lawsuit seeking to remove the tax exemption of the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> is wrong, as is a suggestion that the group favors allowing child pornography. `` That kind of slur, that kind of McCarthyite slander, in characterizing what the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> does, is outrageous and it does not characterize what the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> is about,'' <PERSON> Glasser </PERSON> said on `` CBS This Morning.'' He referred to the 1950s anti-communist campaign of Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, R-Wis., in which many people were tarred as Communist sympathizers without proof There is a court case challenging the Catholic church's tax exemption but the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> is not involved, <PERSON> Glasser </PERSON> said. He said his organization is on record favoring criminal penalties in cases of child pornography. `` The fact is that we are devoted to only one thing, and that is the non-partisan defense of the Bill of Rights,'' <PERSON> Glasser </PERSON> said. `` Sooner or later everybody needs the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION>. When your constitutional rights are threatened or violated, you'll come to the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Haley </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbour </PERSON> of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign responded: `` The <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> has a well-earned reputation as caring more about criminals' rights and prisoners' rights than they care about victims' rights.'' On Monday, <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorsen </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had `` totally twisted'' the group's positions Sunday night as he sought to portray <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as a liberal outside the American mainstream. `` In terms of our day-to-day work over many years, we have consistently acted in a non-partisan way on behalf of some of the most basic principles of the Constitution,'' <PERSON> Dorsen </PERSON> said. `` Our positions are mainstream positions.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has repeatedly attacked <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for being a `` card-carrying member'' of the civil liberties union. In Sunday's debate, he said: `` I do n't want my 10-year-old granddaughter to go into an X-rated movie. ... I do n't think they're right to try to take the tax exemption away from the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. I do n't want to see the kiddie pornography laws repealed. I do n't want to see ` Under God' come out from our currency. Now, these are all positions of the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> and I do n't agree with them. <PERSON> Dorsen </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> does not want 10-year-olds to see pornographic movies, but believes that the movie rating system amounts to illegal censorship. `` We believe that's a decision that should be made by each family,'' he said. He agreed that the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> opposes tax exemptions for churches on the basis that they amount to a government subsidy of religion. He stressed that the organization's position applies to all religious groups, not just the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Dorsen </PERSON> also took issue with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s `` kiddie pornography'' attack, saying, `` Our view is that the government can prosecute the makers of pornography -LRB- for -RRB- the improper use of children for this purpose. We do n't feel that the material itself can be censored.'' Finally, <PERSON> Dorsen </PERSON> said, the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> has never challenged the use of `` In God We Trust'' on currency, although he agreed that such use is contrary to the organization's principles. `` It's not part of the government's job to promote a religious belief, and the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has said that as far back as 1947,'' he said. But <PERSON> Dorsen </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> has never tried to have the words removed from currency. <PERSON> Dorsen </PERSON> also pointed out that the organization recently defended Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>, saying the government violated his Fifth Amendment rights when it prosecuted him for his role in the Iran-Contra affair. And, <PERSON> Dorsen </PERSON> said, the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> is about to file a brief in federal court in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on behalf of former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> Lyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON>, saying he is being improperly prosecuted for illegal lobbying.
