<HEAD>Navy Views Gulf Escort Operation As Qualified Success</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with first unescorted tanker sailing through
gulf, 46 killed since convoys began, details. EDITS to trim and
conform. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD USS VANDEGRIFT IN THE PERSIAN GULF (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sailing into the <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION> under a full moon, this <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> missile frigate tried to draw within 900 feet of the supertanker <PERSON> Townsend </PERSON>, a lumbering 294,739-ton behemoth more than 81 times its size. The purpose, explained the <PERSON> Vandegrift </PERSON>'s skipper, was to see if the little warship could snuggle close enough to the tanker so that together they would appear as one blip on radar screens in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s so-called `` Silkworm Alley. `` It's just something the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> wanted us to try,'' said Cmdr. <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Utegaard </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, as his ship struggling to maintain 17 knots in the churning wake of the <PERSON> Townsend </PERSON>'s 30-foot-wide propeller Utegaard could not know last Saturday that `` Operation Earnest Will'' mission No. 89 would mark the final time a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warship would escort a Kuwaiti oil tanker through the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. Today, the first U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tanker to sail without a close escort of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships left <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s main terminal, heading south through waters where peace has prevailed since the <LOCATION> Iran-Iraq </LOCATION> cease-fire began Aug. 20. Although traveling alone, the 81,283-ton oil products carrier <LOCATION> Surf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> would not be unprotected should trouble arise during its two-day, 550-mile passage through the gulf and <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military sources said. `` She's on her way, and will be under surveillance at all times,'' one source said, speaking on condition of anonymity. While the <PERSON> Vandegrift </PERSON> trailed the tanker at a distance, for the first time since the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> convoy escort policy began July 21, 1987, no warship was sailing directly behind it. However, mine fears remain high following reports that Italian mine-hunters had found an explosive in the <LOCATION> south </LOCATION> <LOCATION> central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> gulf </LOCATION> _ the third discovered in five days. The White House announced Monday the reduction of tension since the Iran-Iraq cease-fire had led President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to end the `` tight escort'' operation. Presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships will continue to be stationed in the gulf, prepared to assist any ship that might need help. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> now has 26 ships in the region. Right to the end, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> was looking for better ways to conduct an operation in which its ships had already sailed 50,000 miles escorting convoys through the embattled oil artery. The <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, Calif.-based <PERSON> Vandegrift </PERSON> was the <PERSON> Townsend </PERSON>'s lone escort for the voyage northward, and earlier had accompanied the 88th mission, a northbound convoy with the 401,382-ton <LOCATION> Bridgeton </LOCATION>, famous for hitting a mine during the first `` Earnest Will'' mission. The <LOCATION> Bridgeton </LOCATION>'s encounter with a 500-pound mine apparently laid by the Iranians pointed up what <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officers such as Utegaard say is `` still the single biggest threat in the gulf.'' Apart from the <LOCATION> Bridgeton </LOCATION>, no ship under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> escort encountered any difficulty with mines, missiles, aircraft or gunboat attacks. Last Oct. 16, however, an Iranian Silkworm missile attack severely damaged the 81,283-ton tanker <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Isle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmadi </PERSON> loading terminal and the ship's American master was badly wounded. The ship, like the <LOCATION> Bridgeton </LOCATION>, later returned to service. Forty-six Americans have died in the gulf since shortly before the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> began escorting ships. On May 17, 1987, an Iraqi fighter jet mistakenly fired two missiles into the frigate USS Stark, killing 37 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sailors. Nine Americans died in the gulf after the escorts began _ seven in helicopter crashes and two in the crash of a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> plane from a carrier support group in <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. The cruiser USS Vincennes shot down an Iranian jetliner in the gulf on July 3, killing all 290 people aboard, after crewmen mistook it for an attacking Iranian fighter jet. Although the ostensible purpose of `` Operation Earnest Will'' was to protect the 11 reflagged Kuwaiti tankers and underscore a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commitment to freedom of navigation, officials say it was motivated greatly by <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s concern about growing Soviet influence in the gulf. Some diplomats noted it was only after <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> agreed to lease three tankers to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and give them armed escort protection that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> moved firmly to reflag and escort part of <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s fleet. The escort missions proved formidable enough that other foreign ships became `` tag-alongs,' lining up ahead, behind or alongside the American convoys as they traveled the dangerous waters of <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> gulf </LOCATION> where Iranian raiders were most active. Some even painted their sterns with American names to dupe Iranian gunners into thinking they were part of the reflagged Kuwaiti fleet.
