is committed to a 50-state campaign and so are we, but we all understand what drives a schedule and we are working on it together to make the sound strategic decisions,'' said one of them. By that measure, most of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> states appear to have been de-emphasized. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has campaigned extensively in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and will return there this week, but he has visited <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, which has 21 electoral votes, only once in the past several weeks. He has visited <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> one time each, briefly, and has not been to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> made two stops in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> several weeks ago but has not returned. He has not visited <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> since the Democratic convention in July, although he is expected to do so in the next few weeks in an effort to keep the race competitive there. In contrast, he has been to <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> at least twice since the convention, and aides say those states, along with <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, are considered more competitive, as is <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>. Turning West, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> strategists concede they have little hope for carrying traditionally <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, as well as <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> in the farm belt, <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential nominee <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s home state of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aides say they will not outright concede any state but, with six weeks to go before the election, must make decisions on where best to allocate staff and money. If internal tracking shows a significant shift among voters in any of the states now being de-emphasized, the plan could again be revised, the aides said. `` We track this stuff very carefully and will be ready to respond if we see a new opportunity somewhere,'' said one aide involved in targeting decisions. `` By keeping it competitive, if we can, we keep the Republicans spending time and resources. You see where we are by looking at the schedule but that does n't mean we do n't keep targets of opportunity open.'' If paid staffers are relocated, the campaign will rely on volunteers to maintain a presence in all 50 states, that aide said. The current plan is to target two of the largest electoral prizes, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and the traditionally Democratic states in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> and industrial <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. The race in many of those states is very tight, another factor in decisions to reallocate resources, the aides said. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, which ranks second only to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in electoral votes, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> carry a total of 179 votes, and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> hopes to win most of them and offset any losses with victories in the border states. Desp