<HEAD>Reagan Says He Would Never Deny US Advisers in El Salvador Right
to Defend Selves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, asked about a firefight involving guerrillas and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military advisers in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, said today he would never deny the advisers `` the right to defend themselves.'' In the incident two weeks ago, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> advisers to the Salvadoran army found themselves in the middle of a rebel attack on an army headquarters, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said. Maj. <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman, said that the advisers `` fired in self defense'' and that none was injured. `` They were caught in the middle of a fire fight and their own lives were in jeopardy, so they fired in self defense,'' she said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, asked about the incident during a picture-taking session with <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> leaders in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, replied, `` I'll never send any of our people into danger without allowing them the right to defend themselves if they are attacked.'' The Washington Post and the <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> in editions today quoted a <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> memorandum as saying 16 Salvadoran soldiers and five guerrillas were killed in the assault at the <ORGANIZATION> Salvadoran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s 4th Brigade headquarters in <LOCATION> north </LOCATION> <LOCATION> central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. Here is how the memorandum described the action, according to the published reports: `` During the attack, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> personnel positioned themselves in a sandbagged and reinforced bunker position adjacent to the trainer quarters. From this position, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> personnel could observe guerrillas moving about surrounding high ground and firing their weapons at, or in the general direction of, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> personnel. `` Perceiving a direct threat to their safety, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> personnel engaged the guerrillas with their assigned personal weapons.'' It was not known specifically whether the three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldiers killed anyone. They reportedly returned fire with M-16 rifles. `` There are no indications of guerrilla casualties as a result of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> defensive fire,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> quoted Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, as writing in the memo. The encounter occurred Sept. 13, but word of it surfaced Monday because the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> referred to it in a report it is required to send to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> whenever a hostile action in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> involves an American, the spokeswoman said Monday. She said she had not seen the memo referred to in the published reports. The same Salvadoran army headquarters was the site of a fierce gun and mortar battle in late March 1987, resulting in the death of a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> sergeant. Army Sgt. <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Fronius </PERSON>, 27, an intelligence specialist who was advising the Salvadoran army, is the only soldier reported killed while on duty in the midst of combat during the eight years of civil war in the country. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military advisers arrived in the country in 1981. <PERSON> Fronius </PERSON> was one of two advisers assigned to the camp at the time