<HEAD>Soviet Foreign Minister Calls for World Space Organization</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS 16 grafs to update with Shevardnadze speech, quotes.
Picks up graf 11 pvs, `On Monday ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> today called on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to join <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in creating a <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, which would use a disputed Siberian radar base as its eye on the heavens. Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> suggested earlier this month that the Soviet radar base at <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, be turned over to an international agency for the peaceful exploration of space. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says the radar base violates the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty and must be demolished. Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said in his speech today to the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should join the Soviets in the space agency and donate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> radar units in <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said the latest Soviet diplomatic initiative was sincere, and that he wanted to make the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> a `` unique global center for ensuring universal and regional security, and the security of each country.'' The Western allies, which regard the Soviet proposal as a new organizational plan that would replace the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Charter, are reluctant to tinker with the existing structure of the world body. Last year, the Soviets were unable to win a majority of votes in the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> when they introduced the plan as a resolution. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> also said the U.S.-Soviet treaty to scrap all intermediate-range nuclear missiles should be supplemented by an agreement limiting the spread of military missile technology that `` could be worked out only under the auspices of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>.'' On conventional arms, the Soviet diplomat suggested the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> register all conventional arms sales and transfers. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> called for an expanded role for the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, suggesting periodic meetings of its foreign ministers and that it meet in areas of regional tensions. In the last 18 months, increased U.S.-Soviet cooperation has allowed the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to act unanimously on major issues including the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> peace plan in Resolution 598, and in denouncing the use of chemical weapons in the gulf war. Turning to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said `` the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords are not just an isolated local instance of a regional conflict settlement. ... They are a new promising beginning in world politics, attesting to a qualitative change in poltiical thinking.'' Under those U.N.-mediated accords, Soviet troops are to be out of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> by Feb. 15 in a withdrawal that began May 15. <PERSON> Shevardnaze </PERSON> also called on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other nations to join the Soviets in abolishing some planned or ongoing military programs and channel the funds toward setting up an international system of environmental security. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> also acknowledged President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s speech Monday in which the president noted U.S.-Soviet cooperation had contributed to breakthroughs in regional security. `` Here I can only agree with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s remrks yesterday about the beneficial impact of Soviet-American political dialogue on that process,'' he said. On Monday, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> delivered a mostly conciliatory, upbeat farewell speech before the world body he had in the past chastised for its alleged anti-Western attitudes. The president condemned the use of outlawed chemical weapons in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war and called for a new global ban on such warfare. He indirectly criticized <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s use of poison gas against its Kurdish minority and against Iranians. Kurdish rebels have long been fighting for a separate homeland in northern <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and sided with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> during the war. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> called on all nations to convene a conference that would consider ways to enforce the 1925 protocol barring chemical weapons in international conflicts. He also urged nations to cooperate in negotiating a verifiable global ban on chemical weapons at the Conference on Disarmament in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> praised the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> for negotiating a cease-fire in the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war and for opening talks to formalize a peace treaty. He said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet negotiators were making steady progress on an accord to halve the superpowers' long-range, or strategic, nuclear arsenals. While completion of the pact this year was `` highly doubtful,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, `` I can tell you a year from now is a possibility, more than a possibility.''
