<HEAD>Thompson Seeks More Control Over Chicago School Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> is asking the legislature for changes in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> school reform legislation that would, among other things, give him more power over a board that is to oversee the reform process. The governor says his proposed changes in the legislation would further the bill's goal of shifting power to the local school level. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> signed the legislation Monday in an amendatory veto, a procedure under <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> law in which a bill is sent back to the legislature for consideration of the governor's written changes or amendments. `` The legislation radically reforms the administrative structure in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> in terms of budgeting and planning,'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said in a statement. `` I believe that the changes suggested today will make this bill stronger and that a majority of people throughout the city and state agree with me.'' Some legislative supporters of the bill said they could accept <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s suggestions. But <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> Vaughn </PERSON> raised objections to changes that would affect some teachers' seniority rights, and some black lawmakers took issue with the proposed expansion of the governor's power. Perhaps the most significant change sought by <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> would increase his authority over the seven-member <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reform </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oversight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, a body created to ensure that the reform measures are put into place. The original bill called for four authority members to be appointed by the mayor of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and three by the governor. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s version would give the governor and the mayor three appointments each, with the seventh member to be chosen jointly. Among <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s other proposals for change: _ Allow the oversight authority to withhold funds if school officials do n't implement reforms properly _ Give principals more authority over `` remediation programs'' for teachers whose work is judged to be substandard _ Require local school councils to return to the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> any unspent funds at the end of a budget year, rather than carrying the money over into the next budget year _ Remove a requirement that teachers with seniority whose positions are eliminated get first preference for vacancies in other vacant teaching posts When lawmakers convene for their veto session in November, they may accept <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s changes by a majority vote or override him by a three-fifths vote and enact the bill as originally drafted. If they fail to do either, the bill is dead.
