<HEAD>NAACP's Alabama State President's Extortion Trial Under Way</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with today's prosecution
testimony. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `In opening...' ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARRY MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prosecution witnesses testified today that <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> president said it would cost about $ 10,000 for his efforts in helping secure early release of a convicted killer. A federal court jury of 10 whites and six blacks, including alternate jurors, began hearing testimony today in the extortion trial of <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, a Democratic state representative and head of the <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> branch of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Colored People. <PERSON> Woodson </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, the inmate's father, testified that he took out two loans totaling $ 4,600 and combined it with cash to pay Reed $ 10,000. He said he did so after meeting with <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> about the imprisoned <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON>, who is serving a 40-year sentence for murder in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. `` I explained my son's situation and asked if he could help me. He said he'd helped a lot of them and we'll see,'' <PERSON> Woodson </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Muncy </PERSON>, a partner in the <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> business where <PERSON> Woodson </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON> worked, testified that <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> told him he believed he would be able to help the inmate. `` He mentioned that in order to get some help, it would probably cost some money. The figure I remember is $ 10,000,'' said <PERSON> Muncy </PERSON>. <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, the senior black member of the <ORGANIZATION> Alabama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, is charged with accepting $ 10,000 in cash and between $ 5,000 and $ 10,000 in restaurant equipment from the <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON> family. <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION> operates two restaurants in <LOCATION> Macon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubina </PERSON> ruled Monday he would allow into evidence a tape of a conversation between <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, restaurant equipment salesman. In opening arguments Monday, defense attorney <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Baxley </PERSON> described <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON>, <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON>'s uncle, as a `` crook to beat all crooks and a con man to beat all con men.'' <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON>, who was convicted in 1980 to a 10-year sentence on a felony theft charge, testified Monday he recorded the conversation with <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> on Aug. 28, 1986, when <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> came to his business. <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> Special Agent <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Koenig </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, testified that the 27-minute tape was authentic. The tape was not played in court Monday. <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON> wanted back the money allegedly given <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> after the state <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pardons </ORGANIZATION> and Paroles revoked an order to move up his nephew's consideration for parole, prosecutors have said. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Broward </PERSON> <PERSON> Segrest </PERSON> told the jury that the five-count indictment of <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> described the payments <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON> made to <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> for his `` political influence'' in obtaining the early prison release of <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON>. <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>'s attorneys challenged allowing the tape recording into evidence because they said it first went to a state parole board member before it reached the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON> told the judge he gave the tape directly to the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. The trial is expected to last three days. `` If the truth prevails, I'll be a free man when I leave here,'' <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, 60, told reporters when he arrived at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in Mobile on Monday. The trial was moved to Mobile from <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> because of publicity surrounding <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>'s indictment. He also is scheduled to go to trial Nov. 7 in <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> on related state bribery charges.
