ON> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to infiltrate troops to U.S.-backed <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> have conducted three previous joint crash site excavations, most recently in May. The American team in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, which brought its own interpreters, are interviewing villagers who witnessed the incidents in which the men were lost and are seeking evidence such as local government reports and human remains. <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> said the seven are among 70 cases in which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says there is strong evidence the men survived and were taken under Vietnamese control. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says it can not prove any Americans are alive in <LOCATION> Indochina </LOCATION> but can not ignore that possibility. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> is investigating 119 reports of purported sightings of Americans, <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> said. The Americans drove to the Vietnamese villages Monday in jeeps flown in from <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> the day before. The search is planned for about 10 days. <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> said the two sides may later excavate plane crash sites found during the investigation. Previously, the only significant joint field activity was in late 1985, when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldiers and Vietnamese state workers dug up the wreckage of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> B-52 bomber just outside <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>. They found remains but none identified as missing Americans. Lt. Col. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>, leader of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> team in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, earlier expressed hope of several joint investigation operations in the coming months. `