<HEAD>EPA Restricts Use Of Tin-Based Marine Paints</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has ordered drastic curtailments of highly toxic tin-based marine paints, banning unsupervised use by pleasure boat owners, the agency said Tuesday. The regulations carry out a new law requiring a five-fold reduction in the release rate of the active ingredient in the paints, tributyl tin or <ORGANIZATION> TBT </ORGANIZATION> compounds, from most hulls. The law bans use of the paints on non-aluminum hulls of vessels of less than 25 meters or 82 feet in deck length, and requires a long-term daily average release rate of 4 micrograms per square centimeter -LRB- about 0.1 thousandths of an ounce per square foot -RRB- or less on other hulls. Existing paints can release <ORGANIZATION> TBT </ORGANIZATION> at about 20 micrograms per square centimeter. The paints may be sold from inventories until Dec. 16 and be used until next June 16. Sold since the 1960s, the nine <ORGANIZATION> TBT </ORGANIZATION> compounds make the paint last much longer than other compounds needed to prevent the growth of barnacles and other organisms on hulls. But their extreme toxicity has led to oyster shell deformities in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> estimates that mussels and clams may be killed at concentrations as low as 20 parts per trillion _ a concentration reported for at least 30 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sites, primarily areas with heavy boating activity. As it proposed to do before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> stepped in, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said it is restricting sale of the paints to applicators certified under state pesticide programs. Use will be limited to those applicators or people working under the direct personal supervision of certified applicators. Formulators must revise labels to incorporate provisions of the new regulations and instructions for proper disposal. The law gives <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> authority to modify the release rate after it completes its studies, and the agency warned that its action in adopting the congressionally mandated rate in its regulations was not final and could be changed. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said it may have enough data next year to determine acceptable limits to human health of <ORGANIZATION> TBT </ORGANIZATION> ingested in drinking water and fish tissues. Data on additional ecological effects, worker exposure and environmental fate of the compounds are due from manufacturers over the next four years. About 1 million pounds of <ORGANIZATION> TBT </ORGANIZATION> compounds have been used in some 624,000 gallons of paint sold each year, of which about 4 percent has gone to paint docks, buoys and other gear. Copper-based paints, which require painting every year or two instead of the seven-year interval possible with <ORGANIZATION> TBT </ORGANIZATION>, are the chief alternative.
