<HEAD>Foreign Newspapers Comment on Bush-Dukakis Debate</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 This is one of a series of periodic reports compiled by <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> bureaus on how the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidential election campaign is viewed abroad.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Newspapers overseas are still commenting on Sunday's the first debate of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidential campaign between Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. Here is some of what they said:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DENMARK</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 _ Politiken -LRB- liberal -RRB- of <LOCATION> Copenhagen </LOCATION>: `` The debate was mostly to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' advantage because he is the least known of the candidates and the one who trailed in the polls since the Republican convention Even though <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> still leads, the election is still wide open.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NETHERLANDS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 _ De Telegraaf -LRB- conservative -RRB- of <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>: `` Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has emerged as the big winner of the first and most important television debate for the American presidential elections ... `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who as vice president had most to lose, overshadowed.. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> especially in the fields of foreign affairs and security. Although he did not deliver a knock-out blow, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> managed to push aside his opponent frequently.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SWEDEN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 _ <ORGANIZATION> Dagens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nyheter </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- liberal -RRB- of <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION>: `` To change the election wind, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> should have made something of an Olympic gold medal performance in his first long-awaited TV battle against <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s crown This he did not do.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ <ORGANIZATION> Svenska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dagbladet </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- center-right -RRB-: `` <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> got his best opportunity so far to remind the Americans of his opponent's not so honorable role in the Irangate scandal But do voters ever let themselves be influenced by scandals involving those who hold power?''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ Aftenposten -LRB- conservative -RRB- of <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION>: `` The debate hardly gave any firm clue about the final outcome when the voters go to the poll in six weeks `` As in most elections in democratic countries these days, it will be the big ` undecided' group which in the end decides whether <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> or <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> will move into The White House.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ <ORGANIZATION> Verdens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gang </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- independent -RRB- of <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION>: `` ... a draw Among those already decided, it is not likely that many voters went from <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> or the other. `` Today that is a bigger problem for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> than for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, because the <ORGANIZATION> democratic </ORGANIZATION> candidate was trailing in the opinion polls before the debate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ <ORGANIZATION> Arbeiderbladet </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- social democratic -RRB- of <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION>: `` This debate will hardly decide the election outcome <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made no major mistakes. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> demonstrated debate skill, but without giving the appearance of a great potential president.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRAZIL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 _ <PERSON> Rosental </PERSON> <PERSON> Calmon </PERSON> <PERSON> Alves </PERSON>, writing from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Jornal </LOCATION> do Brasil -LRB- independent -RRB- of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION>: `` Both <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> tried to appear tranquil and answered cautiously.. The lack of discussion of concrete themes in fact has been one of the most important characteristics of the current <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> electoral campaign.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FINLAND</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 _ <PERSON> Helsingin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanomat </PERSON> -LRB- independent -RRB- of <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION>: `` ... both scored a victory but the Democrats' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has to make a clearer win in the next TV debate if he wants to win the election.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ Ilta-Sanomat -LRB- independent -RRB- of <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION>: `` Many had felt <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who had done his homework and practiced with videos, would floor <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` But this did not happen, as <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who campaigned surprisingly calmly and relaxedly, managed to get in a few painful hooks right through the cold technocratic protection put up by <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>.''
