<HEAD>Debate Polls Call it a Draw; One Marks Rise in Dukakis Stature</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS throughout to show NY Times NOT part of CBS poll</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A national survey found `` major gains in stature'' for Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in the presidential debate, although that poll and three others rated the confrontation a tie overall. None of the surveys found much change in voter preferences as a result of Sunday's debate between <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, and most found relatively narrow movement in underlying opinions of the candidates. But <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> did better than expected at standing up under pressure and at appearing `` more presidential,'' a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> poll found, and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> lost ground in his rating on being able to handle the federal deficit. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, however, improved his ratings in the poll on holding down taxes, controlling crime and maintaining the national defense, and more viewers rated him as likable than had expected to before the debate. The outcome was rated even overall: Thirty-five percent of the 637 voters polled by the newspaper said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> won the debate, 34 percent picked <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and 29 percent called it a tie. Similarly, in a Gallup poll for <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION> 42 percent said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> did the better job and 41 percent said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did better; in a <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> poll 44 percent said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> won, 36 percent <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>; and in a <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> poll 42 percent said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> won, 39 percent <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. All the splits were within sampling error. The polls were conducted Sunday night by calling back voters who had been interviewed before the debate and said they intended to watch it. `` It's a wash,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugick </PERSON>, political pollster for the <ORGANIZATION> Gallup </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. `` What we found is that the debate simply reinforced the image that voters had of these men prior to the debate.'' As in pre-debate polls, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was rated higher on national defense _ 63-31 in the Gallup poll of 337 voters _ while <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> scored better on compassion, 51-33. The two were rated even on being able to create needed changes and on having the ideas to foster good economic conditions. Said <PERSON> Hugick </PERSON>: `` These guys are just even on a lot of things that seem to be critical to who's going to win.'' <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s poll, of 639 debate watchers, indicated a possible `` sliver of movement'' toward <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, said poll analyst <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>. When polled before the debate, the 639 favored <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in the election by 48-46; when called back after the debate, they favored <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> by 52-45. But the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> poll of 415 debate viewers found the possibility of incremental movement the other way. That group favored <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> by 49-44 before the debate and by 52-43 after it. In any case, `` Over 90 percent of each man's supporters stayed with him through the debate,'' said <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>. `` And that is the way these things go. Even if it's a knockout, the effect on the horse race is usually marginal.'' On the movement in <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' stature, the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> poll found that before the debate respondents were split on who would stand up better under pressure, with 36 percent picking <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to 35 percent for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. After the debate, 48 percent said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has stood up better, to 24 percent for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. And voters by 49 percent to 22 percent had expected <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to be `` more presidential.'' After the debate, the division was narrower: Forty-five percent said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had been more presidential, 29 percent said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. The Los Angeles Times' analysis called those results `` major gains in stature'' for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. Also, before the debate the newspaper poll found that 36 percent thought <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> could do better at handling the deficit; after the debate, that fell to 23 percent. Overall, though, the race was a tie: Forty-six percent favored <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for president, 46 percent <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. The horse race results applied just to debate watchers and not to the entire electorate. Also, the polls had relatively small sample sizes, and one-night surveys can be difficult to analyze because they measure visceral reaction to a single event. The margin of sampling error was five points in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> polls, six in Gallup's.
</TEXT>
