<HEAD>Emperor's Condition Shows No Improvement; Grandson Summoned Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> thanked the Japanese people on Tuesday for their outpouring of concern over his fragile health, but doctors expressed no optimism about his condition. Palace officials said physicians have failed to contain Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s internal bleeding, and the government said it has summoned the ailing 87-year-old monarch's grandson home from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kenji </PERSON> <PERSON> Maeda </PERSON>, head of general affairs for the Imperial Palace, quoted chief palace physician <PERSON> Akira </PERSON> <PERSON> Takagi </PERSON> as saying: `` The emperor's condition is stable but it's not improving either. It's an extremely difficult situation. <PERSON> Maeda </PERSON> said doctors found `` slight traces'' of blood in the emperor's bowel discharge Monday night, an indication of internal hemorrhaging. Chief Cabinet Secretary <PERSON> Keizo </PERSON> <PERSON> Obuchi </PERSON> told reporters that <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Aya </PERSON>, the 22-year-old younger son of Crown Prince <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON>, would return to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> shortly from his studies at <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Japanese officials have refused to confirm or deny media reports that the world's longest-reigning monarch is dying of cancer. Cabinet members have remained within calling distance and scheduled visits by the prime ministers of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> have been put on hold. More than 30,000 well-wishers called on the Imperial Palace in a chilling rain Tuesday to sign registries wishing for the emperor's recovery, the palace reported Nearly 600, ,000 people had signed their names to registries at the palace and at 11 locations around the country. Elderly Japanese, some wiping away tears, knelt in front of the 285-acre imperial residence in central <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> to pray for the monarch, who was considered a deity until the end of World War II. Informed of the public response to his illness, the emperor commented today: `` I thank everyone for their concern. Please express my gratitude,'' according to a palace official. `` All we can say is that the emperor has come through one week in stable condition,'' the agency quoted <PERSON> Akira </PERSON> <PERSON> Takagi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s chief physician, as saying <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> received another blood transfusion Tuesday. His slight fever of 98.2 was down from 99 Monday evening but still above his normal level of about 95.9. Although the emperor's body temperature and other vital readings appeared to have stabilized, doctors said they were using antibiotics to control fever and inflammation. News reports said the emperor was also suffering from jaundice and anemia. <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> has had no food in eight days and aside from two small ice cubes, has been unable to swallow water and is being fed intravenously.
</TEXT>
