^Eds: Top 8 grafs new with Quayle speech; picks up pvs 4th graf
bgng, Texas.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Previous NEW ORLEANS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE CHARLES, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> promised college students today that a new Republican administration will give them `` a drug-free and AIDS-free America.'' The <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential nominee, heading for important campaign appearances in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, appealed to 2,000 <ORGANIZATION> McNeese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> students as `` children of the 80s'' for support in the Nov. 8 elections. `` Let me tell you something, children of the 80s, the values of family, future and freedom will never change,'' said the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator, 41, the first baby boomer on a national party ticket. He promised if the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> ticket headed by Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is elected, `` we will do all that we must ... to give you a drug-free and AIDS-free America.'' He also promised every effort to provide better health care for Americans as each generation takes care of elderly citizens who are living longer than ever. `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and I are the leaders of tomorrow,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. `` We will lead this country forward into the decade of the 1990s. We will make the future better than the past.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> stood at <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s side Monday at a <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, rally in his first joint appearance with the vice president since the Republican National Convention in mid-August. He beamed as <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he had `` not only confidence but pride'' in his embattled running mate. From <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Charles </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> headed for to <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> and <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Paso </PERSON> on his first campaign foray into <ORGANIZATION> Lone </ORGANIZATION> <