<HEAD>Indian Rock Fans Await Amnesty Concert</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They've never seen <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> but do a fair imitation of moon-walking. For Indian fans of Western rock music, the Beatles are a cult, <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> is still alive, and <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON> is scintillating. Almost no major Western rockers have toured <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, but that has n't prevented thousands of Indians from being hooked on their music. The long wait for a top Western pop concert ends Friday when a rock-star-studded entourage including <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON>, Sting and <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> hits <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> as part of a worldwide <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> tour. `` This is the biggest show to reach <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Anil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gupta </PERSON>, an organizer of the concert. `` It's the first time music's mega-stars are playing in the region. It will be staged in <LOCATION> Jawaharlal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nehru </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stadium </LOCATION>, with 70,000 tickets on sale. `` I visualize it as more than a sellout,'' said <PERSON> Gupta </PERSON>. `` I have gotten inquiries for tickets from as far away as <LOCATION> Trivandrum </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Trivandrum </LOCATION>, on the southern tip of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, is 1,115 miles from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>. It is the first large Western music concert in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> since the groups <PERSON> Boney </PERSON> <PERSON> M </PERSON> and <PERSON> Osibisa </PERSON> performed in the early 1980s. But cassettes of Western artists sell by the hundreds every day in the shops of major <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> cities. Letters pour into the Western music section of the government-owned radio station, which runs at least three weekly request programs from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> and other big cities. `` I hear music from every house when I return home at night,'' says <PERSON> Rocque </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON>, a drummer and the leader of a band which plays in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> hotels and restaurants. `` It's mostly beat music played on loud stereos. But there's almost no Hindi music to be heard _ maybe because Hindi music nowadays is Western music for 11 bars at a time. Under international copyright laws, any duplication of at least 12 bars of existing music is an infringement. Hindi music is the term used to describe songs in films in the Hindi language. In earlier years, the films were mostly lyrical romances, and their soulful songs helped make a movie popular. But more recent films are more action-oriented, pulsing with a disco Hindi-language soundtrack whose rhythms are usually taken from Western hit tunes. <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON>, from the Indian state of <LOCATION> Goa </LOCATION>, a former <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> colony, leads a band which provides a rare opportunity to hear Western music live in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. In live Indian performances, the music imitates the original, but the vocals often have the unmistakable accent of an Indian speaking or singing in English. <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON> concedes his trio, which usually consists of a lead guitarist doubling as the vocalist, a bass guitarist and himself on the drums, can not provide the best quality of music. `` Our equipment is n't that good,'' he said. `` It's also difficult for most people to afford the prices our hotels and clubs charge,'' he said. `` Ultimately, most fans have to be satisfied with their stereos. Live music is expensive and even then it's not too good.'' The cassettes sell for about $ 2.15, and pirated versions go for about two-thirds the price. Records are difficult to come by, and compact discs have not yet made an impact in the country. The recent top sellers, according to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> shop owner <PERSON> Ashok </PERSON> <PERSON> Chehal </PERSON>, are <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON>, <PERSON> Samantha </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>.
