<HEAD>Reagan Asks Allies to Share in Defense Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in a farewell meeting with West European and <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> figures, said today that free nations must work harder to share the cost of defense. In a meeting with officials of 18 European and <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> allies, including <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the president raised anew the question of alliance burden-sharing _ the persistent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plea that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s allies shoulder a larger share of the costs of defending <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. In reply, allied leaders underscored the heavy contributions their governments were making to developing countries, and said this should be considered a significant contribution to the joint objectives of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. `` They spoke in the same general terms as the president, recognizing that everyone must continue to do their share,'' said Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Rozanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridgway </PERSON>. She said that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who leaves office in about four months, told the allied leaders that `` prosperity and security are inextricably linked.'' Winding up two days of meetings with a wide array of world figures, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also restated American condolences over the death of Pakistani President <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> ul <PERSON> Haq </PERSON>. But he told reporters that he did not know the circumstances behind <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>'s death in an airplane crash. `` All I've heard are speculations and so forth,'' the president said during a picture-taking session. `` I have not gotten an official report yet from any of our people.'' On Monday, <PERSON> Reagan