<HEAD>Reagan Signs Interior Department Bill, But Calls It Budget-Buster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed a $ 10.5 billion <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> appropriations bill Tuesday, but warned that it runs the risk of triggering across-the-board budget cuts by exceeding the spending level he proposed. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also said the bill unfairly restricts offshore oil leasing, but said that `` on balance the act merited my approval.'' It was the fifth appropriations bill he has signed, leaving six to come out of 13 that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> annually considers. `` I urge the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to act swiftly to send me the remainder of the fiscal year 1989 appropriations bill _ on time and on budget,'' he said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who was in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for the opening of the new <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> measure exceeds his request by $ 680 million and brings the federal budget closer to sequestration under the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction act. `` This congressional overspending can not continue if the nation is to avoid the uniform, across-the-board cuts that a sequestration inflicts equally on lower priority programs and on the high priority programs upon which many Americans depend,'' he said. Regarding the congressional moratorium on granting oil and gas leases for certain areas of the outer continental shelf, the president said, `` The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> increased the damaging effects of the moratorium by extending it to apply to grants of permits for drilling and exploration activities under leases already granted.'' `` For the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to prohibit the issuance of such permits to those who already had obtained leases is unfair,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. The president also said many provisions of the bill `` reflect a growing and disturbing trend on the part of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to include unconstitutional committee approval or veto requirements in appropriations bills.'' He said the measure would require, for instance, the approval of congressional committees to change <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> regional boundaries, to close <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> regional offices or to reduce personnel in the <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` In granting authority or making appropriations by law, the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> may not reserve to its committees approval or veto power over the exercise of that authority or the expenditure of those appropriations,'' the president said. Since <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> `` has indicated such a special interest'' in these matters, he said, the administration will consult the lawmakers about them.
