<TEXT>
 A six-story apartment house collapsed today and slid down a steep mountainside in a wealthy district of this northern industrial city. Officials said at least two people were killed and others were trapped in the debris. At least two people survived the collapse, but both were injured. The number of people trapped was not known. <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakashima </PERSON>, an investigator with the state judicial police, said the 3-year-old cement building collapsed shortly before 9 a.m. `` One of the neighbors told us that six months ago they told the architect that the building was loosening and and it was leaning,'' he said. Asked if the severe rains brought by <PERSON> Hurricane </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> 11 days ago could have caused the collapse, he said: `` It had to have something to do with it.'' The bodies of a man and a boy were removed from the collapsed building, <PERSON> Nakashima </PERSON> said. The building, which had one apartment to a floor, collapsed like a pancake into a pile about one story high, and part of it slid about 30 feet down the mountain. Mattresses, clothing and furniture were strewn over the area. Perched high in the wealthy district of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pedro </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Garza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Garcia </LOCATION>, it was one of the highest buildings in <LOCATION> Monterrey </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, 27, was sleeping in his second floor apartment when the building collapsed. `` I woke up and the roof was on top of me,'' he said. He said his maid apparently was trapped inside the builidng. His face and pink T-shirt were covered with blood and his chin covered with white gauze bandage. <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Junco </PERSON> said his 19-month-old granddaughter, <PERSON> Ingrid </PERSON> <PERSON> Junco </PERSON>, and a maid were inside his son's third floor apartment at the t