<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Whaling     09-27 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Whaling,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan To Kill Hundreds Of Whales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> plans to kill about 300 whales this winter in a research project aimed at proving there are enough of the mammals to resume commercial hunting, government officials said Tuesday. A similar plan last year was sharply criticized by international environmental groups, which accused <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> of conducting the experiment to circumvent an international ban on commerical whaling. The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> recently submitted the whaling plan to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Whaling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> for review, but decided not to publicize its contents until the evaluation was complete. They said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> planned to catch `` very close'' to 300 minke whales in the <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION> this winter. The species is estimated by the commission to number more than 430,000 worldwide. The Japanese government says research whaling is necessary to assess whale stocks, and such factors as age, sex and health. Japanese officials say they hope the research will prove there are adequate numbers of some whale species, such as the minke, to allow a resumption of limited commercial whaling. Last year, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> told the commission it would kill 875 minke and sperm whales for research purposes, but strong opposition from international environmental groups and other commission members reduced the catch to 273 minke whales, according to officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The officials said this year's research methods will be similar to those practiced last year, when ships sailed along a fixed route and killed only one or two whales in each group sighted. In 1982, the commission passed an international ban on commercial whaling to allow scientists to study whale populations without hunting pressure. The ban went into effect in 1986 and is to be re-evaluated in 1990 on the basis of the research results. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> officially ended its commercial whaling in <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> at the end of the 1986-87 season, when it caught 1,941 of the mammals. The commission's charter allows member nations to conduct research whaling without approval from the 42-member body. Environmentalists have charged that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> _ where whale meat has long been an important protein source _ is using the research provision to maintain its whaling industry. Japanese officials say other commission members have not been serious about conducting research during the moratorium and plan merely to renew the ban in 1990. `` In the <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION>, only <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is conducting research,'' one official said, speaking anonymously. `` The people who are criticizing <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> are not presenting any data of their own.''
