<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some Burmese fleeing to frontier areas claimed Tuesday they saw troops execute anti-government protesters, and a newly formed opposition group accused the military government of torture. Western diplomats in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> say there are increasing reports of executions of lower-level, anti-government leaders but they have yet to be confirmed. The opposition League for Democracy league issued the torture charge in a statement Tuesday, which said: `` It -LRB- the league -RRB- condemns and demands immediate ending of irresponsible and illegal acts of arrests, torture and killings in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> and other towns.'' The statement provided no other details. The coalition also named retired army officer <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON> as its chairman, former defense minister <PERSON> Tin </PERSON> <PERSON> Oo </PERSON> as vice chairman and <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>, daughter of slain independence leader <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON>, as general secretary and spokeswoman. <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON> immediately called for an interim government to replace the military government of Gen. Saw <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>, which took power in a Sept. 18 coup and cracked down on nationwide street demonstrations. The government announced Tuesday that 348 persons had been killed nationwide, 219 others wounded and 1,107 arrested since Sept. 18. But the government has not mentioned actual executions of detainees. The government previously acknowledged more than 250 deaths but has not mentioned executions. Western diplomats believe troops killed up to 400 civilians in the first few days after the coup. In Ghay Baw Bo near the <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> border, some Burmese said the executions took place as people protesting 26 years of authoritarian rule fled to areas of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> controlled by <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> guerrillas. Soe Hlaing, a 36-year-old lawyer from <LOCATION> Pegu </LOCATION>, said he saw nine people executed by soldiers on a bridge in the town of <LOCATION> Tharrawdy </LOCATION> during his flight. `` Each was shot with a gun. One bullet to the heart,'' Soe Hlaing said. A student from the <ORGANIZATION> Rangoon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> said he witnessed the `` sysematic killing'' of 10 people in <LOCATION> Mudon </LOCATION>, south of the coastal city of <LOCATION> Moulmein </LOCATION>. He spoke on condition of anonymity. Most of the alleged killings occurred after <PERSON> Saw </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> sent troops into the streets of <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> and other cities to put down massive anti-government demonstrations. The League for Democracy, formed Saturday, united <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s traditionally fragmented opposition to revitalize the anti-government movement after the military crackdown A league official announced the leadership appointments. Nine of 12 Executive Committee members also were named with the open seats reserved for ethnic minorities also fighting the central government. <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON> said the group believes `` that -LRB- an -RRB- interim government is the only way to solve the present crisis in the country.'' <PERSON> Saw </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> has promised the first multiparty elections since 1960 but has not set a timetable. He has not responded to calls for an interim government. The league also said Tuesday it `` firmly supports the general strike being staged by the government servants and workers, and urges the strikers to continue until the movement for democracy achieves its goal.'' Saw <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> has ordered civil servants, who left their jobs Aug. 8 to protest political repression and economic decline, to returned to work by Monday. Although the government claims some workers are back on the job, business remains crippled.
