<SECOND>PM-Cadets Stricken, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0567,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stricken Cadet Undergoes Liver Transplant as Investigation
Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede SPRINGFIELD, Mass.
^Eds: UPDATES throughout with comments on investigation, deleting
outdated material. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEEDHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A comatose police academy cadet, one of 16 overcome last week by strenuous training, underwent a liver transplant today, but officials said an investigation showed no evidence that he or others had been abused at the academy. At a news conference, the officials said the training was routine for the first day at the academy, including repeated heavy exercise. Dr. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Grady </PERSON>, the chief state epidemiologist, had said earlier that his preliminary examination last week found `` it's very clear the exercise was stressful. But he said today that further investigation found `` at this time that the cause of the illness was a relatively insufficient intake of water relative to the amount of exercise they were doing.'' <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Egan </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Training </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` There was strenuous physical activities, as there always was on that first day ... -LRB- but -RRB- we have found no one that was denied water upon request.'' Asked if his conclusion was that it was the fault of individual cadets that they took ill, <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> said, `` Some of them were unware of the fact that they were doing damage to themselves.'' Earlier, some cadets had said they had been given only a small amount of water the day the cadets had taken ill. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON>, 25, of <LOCATION> Pittsfield </LOCATION>, who has been in a weeklong coma, entered surgery Monday night for a liver transplant at <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>'s Presbyterian Hospital <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Eberts </PERSON>, hospital nursing administrator, would say only that <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON>'s condition was critical this morning. <LOCATION> Pittsfield </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Everest </PERSON> <PERSON> Wojtkowski </PERSON>, who is acting as a spokeswoman for the <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> family, said said the surgery was completed at 5:30 a.m. today and the family was told that <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> came through the operation `` very well.'' <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> was the most seriously ailing cadet after last week's series of illnesses swept the <ORGANIZATION> Edward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Connelly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Training </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Agawam </LOCATION> just south of <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> Several former cadets have suffered similar fatigue-related medical problems at the academy over the past four years, according to former cadets and an <LOCATION> Amherst </LOCATION> physician. Dr. <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> Lentz </PERSON> said she treated between three and eight police recruits from <LOCATION> Holyoke </LOCATION> in 1984 after they were overcome on the first day of training at the academy. Among the 16 cadets who were hospitalized beginning Sept. 19, the first day of classes, ailments ranged from dark urine to exhaustion and dehydration. Although several stricken cadets refused to be interviewed Monday without clearance from superiors, one former trainee said the training routine was severe. `` I've been through basic training in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and it was twice as bad as that,'' said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Purcell </PERSON>, who quit the academy after one day. `` The doctors told me that if I had gone back for a second day, I could have suffered permanent kidney damage.'' After <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> collapsed while running Sept. 19, instructors allowed the recruits to drink two small cups of water, <PERSON> Purcell </PERSON> said. `` Before that, they had lined us up at the bubbler twice during the day and only let us take one cup of water each.'' Six recruits remained hospitalized Monday. Several local officials, including <LOCATION> Wojkowski </LOCATION> and <PERSON> North </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> Mayor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrett </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, asked the state attorney general's office to review the training program. <PERSON> Wojkowski </PERSON> met Monday with <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> and state police Capt. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> of the Agawam academy. `` I was completely dissatisfied with their responses,'' <PERSON> Wojkowcki </PERSON> said. `` I suspect that the incidents are not isolated.'' <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> was in top shape and had worked out more than six months preparing for the academy, said his brother, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> `` He really wanted to be a policeman,'' the brother said. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Grossman </PERSON>, a spokesman for the state office of public safety, said <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON>'s condition may have resulted in part from a `` self-induced, severe diet.'' But <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> said his brother spent the days before reporting to the academy with his family and ate normally.
