<FIRST>r a AM-RiverBlindness     09-27 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-River Blindness,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carter Center Helps Distribute Pill That Prevents River Blindness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A pill that prevents heartworms in <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s bird dogs also halts a parasite that blinds thousands of Third World residents, and the former president is helping to make sure that it reaches them The Task Force for Child Survival, a public health foundation based at the <ORGANIZATION> Carter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, is overseeing a worldwide system to get the drug Mectizan to the 85 million people at risk for the tropical disease. Mectizan is the commercial name for invermectin, used by veterinarians to treat heartworms in dogs and other parasites in cattle and swine. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> discussed his organization's role in the program in a recent telephone interview from his home in Plains. `` I've got two bird dogs and one of my constant problems is that my dogs get heartworms,'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said. `` When a mosquito bites a dog, a little microorganism goes through the body and winds up in the dog's heart and causes heartworms. `` Mectizan is very effective against heartworm not only with dogs but with other animals. And it also proves to be effective against river blindness because river blindness is caused by the sting of a little fly that grows in very rapidly flowing streams,'' said the former president. River blindness, formally known as onchnocerciasis, is caused by a parasitic worm spread by the fly. It has infected 27.5 million people in more than 30 countries, mostly in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>; 350,000 have been blinded. One dose of Mectizan kills the adult worm's millions of tiny offspring and prevents the adult from reproducing for a year. It is the worm's offspring, called microfilaria, that cause the symptoms of the disease, including skin lesions, severe itching and the blinding eye lesions. The medicine halts the progress of the disease but does not reverse damage already caused by microfilaria. A person bitten by the fly who takes Mectizan once a year for the eight-to-12-year life cycle of the adult worm will be free of the disease unless he is reinfected by another fly bite. Mectizan, derived from acids produced by a bacterium found in Japanese soil, is manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Merck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. The <LOCATION> Rahway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, pharmaceutical company began developing the drug for humans in 1980. Another heartworm medicine for dogs, diethylcarbamazine, has been found effective in fighting a parasitic disease called loiasis, prevalent in western and central <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The disease is caused by the loa loa, or African eyeworm, and it is spread by biting flies that feed on human blood. The disease can cause heart and kidney damage. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> has been fighting river blindness for years. WHO and <PERSON> Merck </PERSON> spent seven years on research trials before Mectizan was approved for human use by French drug officials last year, clearing the way for worldwide distribution. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said <PERSON> Merck </PERSON> has volunteered to make the drug available worldwide and free of charge. The company said last year that building a distribution network was its only remaining roadblock. That's where <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s organization comes in. <PERSON> Merck </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> WHO </ORGANIZATION> said they wanted an independent committee of experts to review the organizations set up to distribute the drug, to monitor any adverse reactions and to keep records on the permanent distribution program. The Mectizan Expert Committee is chaired by Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foege </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Carter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and a former director of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>, who was instrumental in organizing the worldwide smallpox eradication program. Next month the committee will begin reviewing the first applications for the program, clearing the way for <PERSON> Merck </PERSON> to start shipping the medicine to high-risk areas.
</TEXT>
