<HEAD>Commitment To 50-State Campaign Appears Not Quite Solid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With six weeks to go to election day, aides to Democratic presidential candidate <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> are scaling back expectations across parts of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> but express continuing hopes for <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and a handful of border states. The <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> states are still viewed as prime battlegrounds, as well, and practically the entire <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Industrial </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> are up for grabs in the view of campaign officials. But one aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the campaign would soon `` begin pulling back budget and pulling back staff'' from some states where chances of victory are dim, and saving them for the more competitive regions. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and his aides have pledged frequently to run a 50-state campaign this fall. `` Watch the schedule'' for clues about which states are regarded as more winnable, said one adviser, also speaking on condition he not be identified by name. In his campaigning since the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has appeared sparingly in the Deep South, with the exception of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, home state to running mate <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' recent trip to <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> were indications of a continued commitment to several border states in what shapes up as a close election, officials said. Publicly, senior advisers say they will not concede any state to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` We are not going to fall into the Republican trap of cutting off parts of the country,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' field director <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, who said that the Democrats have assembled a 50-state field organization for the first time in several elections. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON>, addressing a meeting of Southern governors Tuesday at <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, said, `` We're being realistic, but we're also campaigning here and will continue to do so becuase we think we can be successful in the South.'' Officials hotly dispute that they have reduced efforts in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, with 21 electoral votes, and say they have recently dispatched new aides to the state. They say that talk of scaling back is a Republican-inspired ploy to undermine their chances. But in contrast to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, where the campaign is committed to running television advertisements specially created for the state, no similar decision has been made for <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. And in contrast to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' periodic visits to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> candidate has been to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> only once since the Democratic convention in July, and is not scheduled to return until Oct. 11. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and his advisers have repeatedly pledged their commitment to a 50-state campaign, and at a meeting of campaign officials in July, senior adviser <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Corrigan </PERSON> said he promised the directors of the 50 statewide oranizizations that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would commit the necessary resources in each of them. In states such as <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> in the South and traditional Republican strongholds in the West such as <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, as well as <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, campaign officials concede privately they have little chance for success. Republican vice presidential candidate <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s home state of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> is regarded as an extremely difficult state, as is <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, according to officials. In all, the states involved carry roughly 100 Electoral Votes, out of 270 needed for victory in the race for the White House. The states have voted Republican in most recent elections, and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign officials have said all year they would give the Republicans a solid launching pad for their campaign. `` We are not at a point yet in our views to completely write off any states and it is not our plan to do that,'' said <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, field director for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` But clearly as this thing tightens up in terms of last-minute media buy decisions and last minute scheduling decisions you've got to make some decisions on how you put together an electoral college majority.'' Another aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said it is important to keep states competitive in order to keep the Republicans spending time and resources. `` You see where we are by looking at the schedule but that does n't mean we do n't keep targets of opportunity, either,'' the aide said.
