<HEAD>Star Wars General Retiring From Air Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lt. Gen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrahamson </PERSON>, the first and only director of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s `` Star Wars'' research program, has decided to retire from the military next February, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. The 55-year-old <PERSON> Abrahamson </PERSON>, a three-star <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> general who assumed command of the fledgling <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Initiative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> in April 1984, will be replaced by <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Lt. Gen. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Monahan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s chief spokesman. <PERSON> Monahan </PERSON>'s nomination must be confirmed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Abrahamson </PERSON> will retire Feb. 1 after 33 years of active military service, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. The general has not announced any future plans. According to documents released Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, including a memo from <PERSON> Abrahamson </PERSON> to <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, the Star Wars chief decided on his own early this summer to request retirement. <PERSON> Abrahamson </PERSON> said he had concluded the next president should be allowed to dictate new policies for Star Wars development to a new leadership team. `` I am proud of the people of SDI, who have not indulged themselves with the negative ` it ca n't be done' approach to problems,'' <PERSON> Abrahamson </PERSON> wrote. `` However, a new administration will undoubtedly have different ideas or approaches to SDI. Therefore, I reluctantly have concluded that the program will best be served by allowing new leadership to represent new policy and direction. As you requested, I will serve until a successful transition is well under way.'' The Star Wars program is an effort to develop lasers and other exotic weapons that could be deployed in space and on the ground to automatically shoot down <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear missiles. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> repeatedly has refused in recent years to fund the program at the pace sought by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, but nonetheless has allowed the research to continue. <PERSON> Abrahamson </PERSON>, a former astronaut who never got to fly in space, is credited with putting together a formal organization to oversee the research work _ which is conducted in laboratories around the world _ while serving as an effective `` cheer leader'' to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the business community. Even in his retirement memo to <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, <PERSON> Abrahamson </PERSON> could n't resist praising the program, saying his Star Wars job had been the best of his career and had `` allowed me to appreciate the daring scope of the president's vision and the genius available to the country to solve this and other daunting challenges. `` I have great confidence that this initiative will go forward and will succeed. I will continue to dedicate myself to SDI to my last day of active duty _ and after.'' <PERSON> Abrahamson </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Williston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.D. </LOCATION>, is a Vietnam War combat pilot who trained as an astronaut for the Manned Orbiting Laboratory Program before it was canceled in 1969. In 1981, the general returned to the world of space, serving as the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s associate administrator for the shuttle program. He oversaw the first 10 shuttle launches before returning to the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and assuming command of the Star Wars effort. <PERSON> Monahan </PERSON>, 54, is a native of <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> who is one of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s top procurement officials.
