<HEAD>Senate Report: Pentagon Has Trouble Managing Huge Inventory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite reforms, the Pentagon is still doing a poor job of managing its inventory of millions of stockpiled items ranging from aircraft spare parts to food and clothing, a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> report said Tuesday. The Pentagon should reduce the huge and growing volume of items it has in its inventory, according to the study by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The report was the latest in a series of studies by the Democratic-controlled panel of how the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> manages its huge stockpile. The studies have been critical of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and have recommended management changes. The studies affect so-called `` secondary items,'' which include spares, repair parts, supplies, food and clothing. That stockpile is in contrast to `` principal items'' like tanks, ships, and airplanes. There has been a large increase in the secondary item stockpile, resulting from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s defense build-up. The secondary stockpile, which now contains about 4.6 million different types of items, is worth $ 94 billion, compared to its $ 43 billion value in 1980. `` The enormous, unprecedented, and unsustainable growth in the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s secondary inventory has simply overwhelmed the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s depots, warehouses, and accounting and control systems,'' the report said. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s `` supply system has been unable to cope with the new demands made on it. The management of current inventories has not kept pace with the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s ability to spend money on new goods,'' it said. For example, two years ago, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Missile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> asked <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to return 24 Stinger hand-held missiles for test firing. The Missile Command sought 24 specific missiles, but service officials in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> were able to find only nine by March 1987. Finally, after searching the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s entire European inventory of missiles, service officials were finally able to locate the other 13. Army officials conceded that their policy `` for recording inventory information on small missiles was ambiguous and contained multiple and contradictory control requirements,'' the study said. <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials, asked for comment, did not immediately respond. However, they agreed with the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> last spring when the congressional watchdog agency raised similar criticisms of the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s inventory management. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials conceded they needed to do better. The committee recommended a number of changes, including a halt in the purchase of items not immediately needed and better administrative and internal <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> controls over the vast and widely segmented inventories. One example cited as wasteful spending was the purchase by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Logistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> of metal bars used to mount flashing red lights atop emergency and police vehicles used by the services. Because of an increase in demand, the <ORGANIZATION> DLA </ORGANIZATION> bought 4,297 of the bars in February 1986 but shortly after the purchase, the demand dropped. That means that the <ORGANIZATION> DLA </ORGANIZATION> now has enough of the bars to last for the next six years, and stocks of the bars are now clogging the aisles of a SLA warehouse. The panel also said the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> needs to improve security at sites where weapons and other potentially dangerous items are stored, a complaint raised in previous hearings. For example, the panel said, its investigators found that Stinger missiles were stored at various sites in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in lightweight metal sheds with the word `` Stinger'' stenciled on the shed's side.
</TEXT>
