<HEAD>Couple Who Defected to Soviet Union Then Returned Home Now Jobless
and Broke</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ERI1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A couple who sought a better life in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> following financial setbacks in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are back home, saying they are broke, embittered and have been deceived by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cheryle </PERSON> <PERSON> Branch </PERSON>, who returned to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last week after 10 months in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, were staying Tuesday in a small motel in Erie. They had previously lived in nearby Summit Township. `` By Monday, we will be broke so we are going to move into the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Courthouse to live,'' said Branch, 42, referring to the federal courthouse in <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION>. The Branches said they moved to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> because `` we were so mad at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government, but not at the people.'' `` We're really mad now,'' he said. The couple claimed that after Soviet officials gave them a furnished apartment and jobs at <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, officials at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> there offered them the same benefits plus help resolving their financial troubles if they returned to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. However, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said the Branches were offered only the same loan available to any stranded <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen to finance passage home. `` They made promises there, and now they are backing out,'' Branch claimed. Branch said that after they arrived in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, the Soviets asked them to visit the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy because <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials were worried about them. He said they refused because `` we vowed we would never step inside another federal building. They were n't worried about us there, why would they be worried about us here?'' The Soviets asked them in February to assure the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy that they were not being held against their will. Branch claims that during a subsequent meeting, <PERSON> Jill </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrelly-Byrnes </PERSON>, the embassy's second secretary and vice consul, said, `` Do you need money? We have jobs for you. We have a place for you to live and medical care.'' At an August meeting, the embassy officials said they could not help the Branches solve their problems unless they returned to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Branch </PERSON> said. `` We thought if they were willing to work with us, to make amends, why should we hold a grudge?'' he said. No one greeted them in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> as promised, <PERSON> Branch </PERSON> said. `` I think we have been deceived. We have been stripped of everything,'' said Mrs. Branch, 40. `` It is hard to believe that in a democratic society two people could be in such a predicament.'' The couple want to be reimbursed for the $ 3,000 airfare and the motel room. `` The government is heavily indebted to us and why should n't we feel like this?'' said Mrs. Branch. `` It is supposed to be a great democracy.'' `` We would n't be here looking for a job if they had n't promised us,'' <PERSON> Branch </PERSON> said. He said they might return to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> but are `` tired of moving back and forth across the ocean at somebody's whim.'' The troubles that made the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> look good included the couple's inability to collect $ 10,000 in back wages from <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> despite a federal court judgment in their favor. Land they owned in <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> was declared part of a flood plain by the federal government and is worthless, Mrs. Branch said.
