<HEAD>Hamadi Didn't Kill Navy Diver Aboard Hijacked Jet, Witness Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 2-5 pvs `The attendant...Waldorf, Md.' with 4
grafs to CORRECT spelling of Stethem throughout. PICKS 6th graf pvs
`Ms. Hesp ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A flight attendant testifying at the murder and air piracy trial of <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> said Tuesday that <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>'s accomplice killed a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> diver aboard a hijacked <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> airliner. The attendant, <PERSON> Hazel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hesp </PERSON>, said hijacker <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ezzeddine </PERSON> killed diver <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> after the <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> jet was commandeered June 14, 1985. The testimony contradicted that of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Testrake </PERSON>, the plane's pilot, who told the court he believed <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> was the hijacker who killed <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> Ms. <PERSON> Hesp </PERSON> also testified that <PERSON> Ezzeddine </PERSON> claimed a friend of his had carried out the bombing mission that killed 241 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> in 1983. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, has admitted hijacking the <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> jetliner on the Athens-to-Rome flight and holding 39 Americans hostage for 17 days. But said the other hijacker killed <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Waldorf </LOCATION>, Md. Ms. <PERSON> Hesp </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ezzeddine </PERSON>, who is at large, `` seemed to be giving the orders'' during the hijacking. The 47-year-old Ms. <PERSON> Hesp </PERSON> said `` Said'' was the name <PERSON> Ezzeddine </PERSON> used during the hijacking. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>, she said, called himself `` <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>.'' Ms. <PERSON> Hesp </PERSON> did not name her home or nationality, under guidelines set by the court to protect witnesses in the trial, some of whom have said they feared reprisals. Her speech had a British accent. Outside the courtroom at Preungesheim prison, security remained tight as it has been since the trial began July 5. There were about two dozen policemen near the entrance, and at least three carried machine guns. Asked by the court judge if she knew who killed the 23-year-old <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON>, Ms. <PERSON> Hesp </PERSON> paused, then said: `` Yes. But I did not see the shot, so it is only my opinion. It would be my opinion that it would be Said who shot.'' She added: `` They were both terrifying, of course, but of the two men it is my feeling that <PERSON> Said </PERSON> was the more vicious.'' `` I remember when we first took off from <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> and they punched our heads down and they were running up and down screaming,'' Ms. <PERSON> Hesp </PERSON> said. `` I remember I was always more afraid when I saw the white shoes, because I knew they belonged to Said.'' Other witnesses, including flight engineer <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmermann </PERSON>, have testified <PERSON> Ezzeddine </PERSON> was the more violent of the two hijackers, but that both seemed to have equal authority. When asked to comment, <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>, who sat quietly through much of the testimony with his elbow propped on the table and chin in his left palm, told the court in Arabic through his translator he had nothing to say. Throughout the trial, the court has given <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> the opportunity to comment without having to take the witness stand. Ms. <PERSON> Hesp </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ezzeddine </PERSON> could speak a litte English and told her a friend of his drove a truck laden with explosives into the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> compound in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> in 1983, blowing up the barracks and killing 241 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen. `` He seemed to be very proud of this and told of how he hates Americans, and wondered how non-Americans could work for an American airline,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Hesp </PERSON>. Across the courtroom, facing <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON>, the parents of the slain <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> diver, took notes and listened quietly. In other testimony Tuesday, another flight attendant, <PERSON> Jody </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, 47, described how she and others on the flight were forced to sit for hours with their heads between their knees and hands on the back of their heads. Speaking in an unsteady voice, <PERSON> Ms. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, an American, said she heard the screams of hostages being beaten by the hijackers. `` I saw <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> <PERSON> Suggs </PERSON> with his hands bound, and <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> too. They had cloths tied around their heads as blindfolds,'' Ms. <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Suggs </PERSON> testified Monday he thought he would die next when one of the hijackers said after <PERSON> Stethem </PERSON> was shot, `` One more in five minutes.'' <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON> was arrested at <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> on Jan. 13, 1987, after customs officials discovered liquid explosives in his luggage. In the following week, two West Germans were kidnapped in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. Both men have been freed. <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>'s brother, <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamadi </PERSON>, was convicted by a <LOCATION> Duesseldorf </LOCATION> court of taking part in the kidnappings in a failed effort to pressure <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> into releasing <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>.
