<HEAD>GAO Says Export Promotion Programs In `State Of Disorder'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON> charged Tuesday that export promotion programs run by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> are doing more to confuse <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> businesses seeking to market their products abroad than to help them. <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON>, a Democrat who heads the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> government operations subcommittee on commerce, consumer and monetary affairs, said a <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> study requested by the subcommittee concluded that the department's management of trade shows and trade missions abroad is in `` a state of disorder.'' `` Instead of helping <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> businesses to get into the export business, it seems that the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is doing more to confuse and frustrate anyone who thinks about selling abroad,'' <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON> said. `` This situation must be remedied without delay.'' A draft copy of the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report, released by the subcommittee, said about 55 percent of the major trade events scheduled abroad by the department's <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 were canceled. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said the frequent cancellation of advertised trade shows or missions `` has limited the credibility of the program in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> business community and in some overseas locations.'' <PERSON> Desiree </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> ITA </ORGANIZATION>, said the agency has reviewed the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report and is preparing a written response. Major responsibility for export promotion programs abroad lies with the <ORGANIZATION> ITA </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which has 155 commercial officers in 66 countries. The agency, which also has offices in 48 states, had a $ 68.9 million budget in fiscal 1987, with $ 39.2 million for foreign operations. Two other ITA divisions share the responsibility for export promotion programs, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said, and a lack of coordination among the three units has resulted in poor planning and execution of trade events and a lack of accountability. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> also criticized the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> for failing in three attempts since 1978 to develop a computerized trade information data base that would provide up-to-date international marketing and trade information to government and business officials. A `` very limited'' version of the data base is supposed to be operational by tne end of the year, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. Full implementation is expected to cost $ 39.9 million through 1993, not including the $ 13.4 million spent on the two previous attempts to computerize the trade data.
