<HEAD>U.S. Seeks to Keep Nuclear Arms Out of Troop Reduction Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, in a move bound to reassure <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, said Tuesday that East-West troop reduction talks would not be expanded to cover nuclear weapons. But it still was not clear when the negotiations might begin despite President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s statement that they would open soon and discussions this week at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. The negotiations between the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact are intended to reduce non-nuclear forces, tanks and other mobile weapons in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> and Defense Minister <PERSON> Jean-Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Chevenement </PERSON>, during talks Thursday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, are expected to reject any Soviet attempt to use the forum to promote nuclear weapons reductions. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> agreed to the negotiations only with reluctance. The French are determined to protect their independent nuclear force from cutbacks under joint U.S.-Soviet pressure. In fact, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> is planning to deploy a new tactical missile system. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, at a news conference here, said flatly: `` The talks will not be expanded to include nuclear weapons. They are confined to conventional weaons.'' The start of negotiations has been delayed by a dispute over human rights. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has sought assurances from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> that there would be a simultaneous improvement in human rights conditions in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The issue was discussed at meetings that Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> had in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> last week with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said afterward that the Spviets had promised to release 27 political prisoners and to reform their emigration regulations. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in a speech Monday to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, said the East-West talks would open soon. Both Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrovsky </PERSON> and <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Foreign Secretary <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON>, in separate meetings Tuesday with reporters, said the chances were good the talks would be held this year. Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Rozanne </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridgway </PERSON> said, however, <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s visit to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> `` certainly did not erase all of the differences.'' She said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials reviewed the situation this week with West European allies attending the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> session. `` I think there's a sense here that the last issues have been defined,'' she said. `` But there is nothing that has been done here to specifically _ on a case-by-case basis _ to change the situation.''
