<HEAD>Agency Says Aquaculture Production Is Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Aquaculture production in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which includes fish farming, has grown by 20 percent a year since 1980, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. Production includes food and non-food fish, shellfish and aquatic plants, the department's economic research unit said. `` Domestic production of food fish and shellfish amounted to an estimated 700million pounds in 1987 and was worth almost $ 550 million at the farm gate, compared with 203 million pounds and $ 191 million in 1980,'' the agency said. `` Last year, non-food aquacultural production included, among other items, $ 71.5 million of baitfish and $ 23 million of tropical fish.'' The report by the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> agency was the first in six years. When aquaculture began to move up as an agricultural enterprise, reports were issued in 1980, 1981 and 1982. They were dropped after that as an economy measure. `` During the 1980s, Americans have substantially increased the quantity of fish and shellfish in their diets despite the fact that seafood prices have risen considerably faster than those for some major competing sources of dietary protein,'' the report said. Per capita consumption of all fishery products rose 18 percent to 20.2 pounds in 1987 from an estimated 17.1 pounds in 1980. The largest sources of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fishery products are domestic wild harvests and imports, the report said. Commercial fishermen landed a record 11 billion pounds of fish and shellfish last year, with a wholesale value of $ 3.6 billion, an increase of 1.8 billion pounds and $ 500 million from 1986. Imports were valued at a record $ 8.8 billion in 1987, led by $ 1.7 billion worth of fresh and frozen shrimp. Lobster and tuna were next at $ 600 million and $ 500 million, respectively.
