<HEAD>Man Sues Saudi Government, Claiming 1984 Torture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An American engineer filed a federal damage suit Tuesday against the Saudi Arabian government, claiming Saudi torturers broke his back and legs in 1984 and left him permanently disabled. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, 34, of <PERSON> Davie </PERSON> said he now walks with a cane, has had four knee operations in the past year and was about to enter the <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Durham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, for up to another year of treatment. `` This suit is going to test our laws,'' <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said in a telephone interview Tuesday from an apartment he has taken in <LOCATION> Raleigh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> `` I'm suing them for the damages from the torture I sustained. They broke my back and my legs and never even charged me with a crime.'' <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> and other Americans who said they suffered at the hands of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> authorities testified before a House Foreign Affairs subcommittee in June 1987. In September 1984 <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> was an engineer for <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, monitoring systems at the King Faisal Specialist Hospital in <LOCATION> Riyadh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>. He told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that police picked him up from the hospital security office after he complained about hospital safety problems, but said that to this day Saudi authorities have never explained his detention. `` I have no idea why,'' <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said. `` In four years of trying to find out, nobody has been able to give me an idea.'' <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said he was held incommunicado and tortured for 39 days. `` They have a unique way of torturing people,'' he said. `` They shackle your hands and feet and make you do deep knee bends over a rod until they hear your knees break.'' The torture and repeated beatings left him with a shattered knee, ruptured disks in his back and partial damage to his sciatic nerve, leaving one leg numb. His knee was so badly damaged an artificial one may have to be implanted to save his leg, which suffers from poor circulation. `` I'm walking now, but I have to use a cane,'' he said. `` I'll always have the cane. Saudi authorities eventually released him, telling him his detention had been a mistake, and offering him increasing amounts of money, he said. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> agents later threatened him and his former attorney when he insisted on pursuing the matter with the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The threats are under investigation by the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said he could not comment on any investigation. The suit, filed Tuesday in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> federal court, accused Saudi authorities of negligence, battery, unlawful detainment, wrongful arrest and imprisonment, inhuman torture, disruption of normal family life and mental anguish. It does not specify monetary damages. A spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> Saudi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said she did not have any immediate reaction to the suit. <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>'s attorney, said the case seeks to apply <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> human rights standards and international law to the court suit, something that has rarely been done in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` We expect it to be a ground-breaking suit,'' <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> said. `` Prohibition against torture is fairly accepted worldwide.'' <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> complained that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities were of limited help. He praised <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., who served on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee, but said the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lost his files after he appeared on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> He said the federal suit against a foreign government in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts represents his best chance to get compensation for the torture and damage he suffered.
