<HEAD>Farm Conferees Produce Bill Capping Export Subsidies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farm lawmakers reached a compromise Tuesday on an agricultural money bill that placed a $ 770 million ceiling on the nation's major export subsidy program in the upcoming fiscal year. Lawmakers are still adding up the items in the massive money bill, which covers everything from farm subsidies to food stamps, but the total was between the $ 44.1 billion <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> level and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 47.3 billion. Under the measure, produced by a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION>, spending on the Export Enhancement Program would be capped at $ 770 million in the fiscal year starting Saturday. The administration had requested $ 900 million for the program, under which major grain companies and other exporters are paid with surplus crops to spur exports of American farm products. Established under the wide-ranging 1985 farm law, the program has been responsible for stepped up shipments of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat and feedgrains. Sen. <PERSON> Thad </PERSON> <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>, R-Miss., had pushed for a larger amount but said the level approved would not put too large a crimp in the program `` I think this is a strong signal that we are at level of export assistance that will ensure that we will be able to sell in the international marketplace anything we have available to sell,'' he said. The committee also put a $ 200 million ceiling on expenditures under the Targeted Export Assistance program, which supplies aid for advertising and other promotion of American agricultural products overseas. The program had been scheduled to increase to $ 325 million a year under the 1985 farm program. It has been criticized in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> recently for providing taxpayer aid for the product's of specific companies. The conferees also adopted a compromise with the administration that would defer for one year a cut in the amount that production credit associations would have to pay to bolster the financially wobbly Farm Credit System. Production credit associations are local lending institutions that are part of the massive, borrower-owned system, which represents the nation's largest farm lender. The associations were required to pay assessments under a federal bailout passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1986. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration Monday had called on conferees to drop the provision calling for a lowering of the assessment level, threatening a presidential veto of the entire bill.
