distinction for the first time about his opposition to the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION>, which he uses as a device to attack <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as a liberal because he belongs to the organization. `` I do n't have a quarrel with their work in, you know, helping whatever position they take in terms of defending the right of an individual,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` but I just do n't agree with the major positions that organization has taken'' in terms of legalizing pornography and its opposition to tax exemptions for religious institutions. Meanwhile, a national poll released Tuesday found that perceptions of Sunday's presidential debate as a dead heat have increased, with a plurality of respondents saying there was no clear winner. Forty-two percent in the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> poll conducted Monday night said the debate was a tie or did n't know who won _ more than double the 20 percent who expressed one of those views after the debate Sunday night. The poll of 416 likely voters also found that 34 percent said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> won while 24 percent said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> turned in the best performance. The survey, which included voters who had not seen the debate but had heard or read about it, had a margin of error of plus or minus six percentage points. The two vice presidential candidates are scheduled to debate on Oct. 5 in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, and the jockeying for advantage already was well under way. Democrats have criticized <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> unsparingly during the campaign, but in an apparent bid to raise expectations about the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator's debate performance, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> characterized him as a skillful debater. `` I think <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> is going to do very well in the debate,'' said the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> senator. He said <PERSON> Quayle <