<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police on Tuesday arrested one of the leaders of last year's bloody attempt to topple President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> and said the renegade colonel was recruiting dissident soldiers for a new coup plot. Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Rodolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Biazon </PERSON>, commander of the <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> district, said Lt. Col. <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Matillano </PERSON> was arrested before dawn in a raid on a hotel in <LOCATION> Quezon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> after informants reported seeing him dining there. <PERSON> Biazon </PERSON> said <PERSON> Matillano </PERSON>, former constabulary chief in <LOCATION> Nueva </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ecija </LOCATION> province, was the `` chief recruiter'' of right-wing military dissidents and had been traveling throughout the country seeking to convert soldiers to his cause. <PERSON> Matillano </PERSON> played a major role in the failed coup on Aug. 28, 1987, that was led by former Lt. Col. <PERSON> Gregorio </PERSON> `` Gringo'' <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON>, who remains at large. <PERSON> Matillano </PERSON> led an assault on the government television station and a hotel near armed forces headquarters during the attempt, in which at least 53 people were killed and more than 300 were wounded. He was arrested a short time later and was charged with rebellion, but escaped last April during a visit to a dentist. <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> was arrested last December but fled a prison ship in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, also in April. <PERSON> Biazon </PERSON> said <PERSON> Matillano </PERSON>'s arrest followed the recent capture of 63 followers of deposed President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. He said those arrests were kept secret for security. He said <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON>'s group apparently forged an alliance with other renegade officers linked to <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, adding: `` Matillano's capture severely cripples recent attempts by ultra-rightist elements to destabilize the government.'' Elsewhere, military chief of staff Gen. <PERSON> Renato </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Villa </PERSON> ordered reinforcements sent to southeastern <LOCATION> Luzon </LOCATION> on Tuesday after communist rebels killed 10 soldiers and a civilian in a weekend ambush and captured five sergeants who were carrying a unit payroll worth up to $ 50,000. In another incident, police said Sgt. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Dizon </PERSON> was driving to work in suburban <LOCATION> Malabon </LOCATION> Tuesday when four attackers fired, killing him instantly. Police said the attack was similar to those used by communist rebels, who have killed scores of police and soldiers in the capital this year.
