<HEAD>Stalled Gulf Peace Talks Set To Resume</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign ministers from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> are to resume direct peace talks Saturday in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, an official said, the first meeting between the warring nations since peace talks fell apart in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on Sept. 13. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> and a special mediator plan to meet separately Friday with <PERSON> Tariq </PERSON> <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Guiliani </PERSON>, the secretary-general's spokesman. The two foreign ministers then will have face-to-face negotiations on Saturday with <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> and the mediator, Ambassador <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eliasson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Guiliani </PERSON> said Tuesday. The talks, aimed at ending the 8-year-old <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war, began in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on Aug. 25, five days after a U.N.-sponsored truce took effect. Negotiations bogged down over <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s demand that the <LOCATION> Shaat-al-Arab </LOCATION> waterway, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s only outlet to the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, be cleared of sunken ships and silt as the next step in the peace process. Disputes over navigation rights in the waterway was a main cause of the war. A 1975 treaty puts the border down the middle of the passage, but <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> is seeking control of the entire waterway. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> cease-fire resolution outlining an end to the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war also calls for the sides to withdraw to internationally recognized borders, an exchange of prisoners of war, and a formal determination of who started the conflict. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> initially endorsed the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> cease-fire resolution in July 1987, but <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> did not accept it until a year later, after a series of battlefield defeats.
