<HEAD>Bush Proposes Tax-Deferred Savings for Middle-Income Americans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with Bush ACLU remarks, riverboat ride,
Dukakis comments on savings proposal; EDITS to tighten.
^By TERENCE HUNT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, criticized for advocating tax breaks for the wealthy, proposed a plan Tuesday that would offer tax-deferred interest to low - and middle-income Americans on long-term savings deposits <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said such `` individual savings accounts'' would help the nation `` gain better control over our long-term economic future'' by increasing savings. `` Americans have increasingly gotten away from the sensible frugality that says, ` put some away for a rainy day,''' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. The <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign criticized the proposal as `` pitching pennies'' at the financial struggles of working families because it amounted to a tax break of 40 cents a week. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> unveiled the proposal before the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> Republican state convention on his second visit to <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> in 11 days. The state, offering a prize of 23 electoral votes, is a key battleground in the election fight. In a later appearance across the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> softened his assaults on the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, which have become part of his attack on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` I need to carry <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> to win the presidency of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> declared earlier in the day at a rally before thousands of cheering students at <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. He was headed Wednesday to <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, where he will take a bus tour. As described by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the savings plan would allow interest to accumulate tax deferred for funds put on deposit for at least five years. A maximum of $ 1,000 a year could be deposited. When withdrawn, the interest would be taxed at the saver's tax rate then in effect. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> economist who advises <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign, offered this example: If a person put $ 1,000 into such an account and if it paid about 8 percent annual interest, that would yield about $ 80 in interest income. For those in the 15 percent tax bracket, that would defer some $ 12 in taxes the first year, slightly more in later years. It would cost the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> about $ 70 million in 1989 if that were the first year in effect, growing to $ 550 million by 1993, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign estimated. The full interest deduction would be available only to taxpayers with adjusted gross incomes of less than $ 50,000 a year. Taxpayers with adjusted incomes of $ 60,000 or more would not be eligible for the program. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign staff estimated that more than 8 million Americans would take advantage of the plan. `` They will be helping themselves become better able to afford a home, pay for college or start a business, and they will be helping <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> _ by increasing investment and economic growth,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been repeatedly attacked by <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for advocating a cut in the maximum capital gains tax from its current level of 33 percent down to 15 percent. Most people who pay the tax are charged about 28 percent. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, speaking in a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburb, said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> savings proposal would yield the average family $ 20 a year. `` Twenty bucks a year, who's he kidding?'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` Today, after I pointed that out to him on Sunday night, he discovered the rest of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and he told just what his priorities are,'' he said. `` He wants to give the wealthiest 1 percent of Americans $ 30,000 and the rest of us are going to get twenty bucks. That's a new definition of trickle-down.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaigned later Tuesday at a rally at a riverfront park in <LOCATION> Owensboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, after a brief ride on sightseeing boat on the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. When a reporter tried to ask <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> about the minimal impact of his savings plan, the question was interrupted and drowned out by the blaring noise of the boat's horn. `` Thank you very much,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, turning away with a smile. Speaking before a crowd of several thousand people, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made a distinction for the first time about his opposition to the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION>, which he uses as a device to attack <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as a liberal because he belongs to the organization. `` I do n't have a quarrel with their work in, you know, helping whatever position they take in terms of defending the right of an individual,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` but I just do n't agree with the major positions that organization has taken.'' In his <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> speech, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> avoided any attack on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and tried to set a tone of compassion. `` The answer is up to us,'' he said. `` The answer is in each individual act of kindness multiplied by thousands and tens of thousands. The answer is in a new engagement in the pain of others.'' At <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> entertained the students with a series of barbs aimed at <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. Referring to a television series, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` There's a TV show that reminds me of what interest rates might be if the Democrats get back in again. It's called `` thirtysomething.''
