<HEAD>Reports: Captured Beachfront Must Be Returned To Egypt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An international team of arbitrators has ruled that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> must return a disputed beachfront resort area to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> media reported Tuesday. The ruling, which has been under consideration since May 1987, is to be announced Thursday in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> captured <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION>, a beach resort along the <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war and retained the property when it returned the <LOCATION> Sinai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> in 1982. The dispute over the 250-acre area has been a key sticking point in <LOCATION> Egyptian-Israeli </LOCATION> relations. The two countries signed a U.S.-mediated peace treaty in 1979. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio and newspapers said the arbiters, who have visited the site and studied old maps and thousands of documents from both sides, had decided to return all the property to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. A Foreign Ministry official declined comment on the reports but said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> planned to honor whatever decision the arbiters reached. He noted that if <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION> were returned to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, some compensation would likely have to be made to <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> citizens who own a hotel and a beach resort along the half-mile beachfront. In <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Egyptian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials said President <PERSON> Hosni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON>'s government was so confident the arbiters will decide in <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s favor that the ministry already was preparing a statement to be issued after the announcement. A state-run trave agency in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Misr </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sinai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tourist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, has begun advertising trips to the <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION> area. `` Now <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION> is the talk of the whole world,'' said the advertisement in the English-language Egyptian Gazette. In <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s hardline <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>' left-leaning <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> clashed over <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION>, an issue expected to surface in the elections campaign. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s parliament elections are scheduled for Nov. 1. The <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> said if the decision goes against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, it would be proof of its contention that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> can not expect a fair hearing from an international body and should not agree to an international conference on <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace. `` We should not agree beforehand to the demands of the other side,'' <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> legislator <PERSON> Ronnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Milo </PERSON> said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> army radio. `` I accuse <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> and Labor officials, who threaten that if we do n't accept some demand, everything will collapse.'' <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>, who favors an international conference, said he still believed <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> could sign a peace treaty with neighboring <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> without necessarily returning all the territory it occupies, as was the case with <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. `` I'm also not sure we had to reach such a treaty with <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. But I supported it because it was the only one in the field,'' he said on the radio in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> is scheduled to meet with his Egyptian counterpart, <PERSON> Esmat </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdel-Meguid </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Thursday. The two leaders are expected to work out how to implement the ruling. The five-member <LOCATION> Taba </LOCATION> arbitration team is made up of Swedish chief arbitrator <PERSON> Gunar </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagergren </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Bellet </PERSON> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Schindler </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Sultan </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Lapidot </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> also captured the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> in the 1967 war.
