<HEAD>Disgruntled Diplomats Threatening Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Diplomats at the French Embassy are threatening to strike in a pay dispute, a source told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday. French Foreign Minister <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON> met in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Monday with representatives of French diplomatic missions in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> to see whether he could defuse the problem and dispatched an aide to talk to staff in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said the source, who refused to be identified. The <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> diplomats, who had planned to walk out this week, agreed to delay any protest until after French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> makes a one-day visit to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Thursday. `` It has nothing to do with the visit, and they did n't want to disrupt it,'' said the source who is close to a committee representing staff. <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON> reportedly promised to look into the matter. Some 80 percent of the 250 embassy employees in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, ranging from typists to top diplomats, already staged a walkout on Sept. 9, and other diplomatic missions also have been involved in the dispute, the source said. The protest concerns a decision to cut foreign-living allowances by 20 percent for staffers who live in some 90 countries where compensation is based on the value of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar, which has been rising against the franc this year. There have been protests in other posts in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and elsewhere, the source said. Besides the embassy in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and mission to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the French have 12 consulates in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
