<HEAD>Dukakis Says Bush Might Cut Social Security, Medicare</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with Dukakis stumble in Melrose Park, INSERTING four
grafs after 10th pvs, ``Today, in...trickle-down; EDITING
throughout to tighten.
^By WILLIAM M. WELCH</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, appealing to `` mainstream Americans,'' assailed <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Tuesday as an enemy of Social Security and <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> who might cut both programs. The Democratic presidential nominee traveled to the city that has become a symbol of middle <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to combat his Republican rival's suggestion that he is outside the nation's mainstream. `` If you want to see the difference between <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and me on the things that concern mainstream <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, look at where we stand on Social Security and Medicare,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told a rally outside <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>'s city hall. He said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had called the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> health plan `` socialized medicine'' while running for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> years ago, and that in 1980, while a presidential candidate, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called Social Security `` basically a welfare program.'' `` When it comes to Social Security and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, do n't read his lips, read his record,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said in a remark that turned around <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s `` read my lips'' declaration he would not raise taxes. `` He was wrong then and he's wrong now,'' the Democrat said. Later, during a speech in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Melrose </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> riduled a proposal made Tuesday by <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to allow small savers to sock away up to $ 1,000 a year and defer paying taxes on the interest. `` Twenty bucks a year _ that's Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s solution for average Americans,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said referring to his campaign's calculation of the benefits from the plan, `` He says it will make them, and here I'm quoting, ` better able to afford a home, pay for college, start a business,''' he said. `` Twenty bucks a year, who's he kidding? `` Today, after I pointed that out to him on Sunday night, he discovered the rest of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and he told just what his priorities are. He wants to give the wealthiest 1 percent of Americans $ 30,000 and the rest of us are going to get twenty bucks. That's a new difinition of trickle-down.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> fell on his face when he tripped while climbing stairs to the stage at the Melrose Park event. He got up, showed no sign of being injured or upset, and shrugged it off when asked about it later. `` It happens in every campaign at least once,'' he said. While there he was presented with a shirt bearing the name <ORGANIZATION> Eureka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> school that is President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s alma mater. On the back were the words, `` We like Dutch but we love the Duke.'' Seeking to encourage the notion that he had tightened the presidential race with a strong debate performance two days earlier, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> escalated his assault on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s views on Social Security and <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor repeatedly referred to his debate performance, asking the <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> crowd `` How many of you thought I won?'' and drawing a thunderous cheer. He said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` said our family farms must be doing just fine'' in the debate. `` He must be kidding,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said, saying there were 200,000 family farms and half a million farm-related manufacturing jobs lost in eight years. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said both Social Security and Medicare were likely targets for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to cut to finance additional defense spending and to offset a cut in the tax on capital gains, a tax break <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> contended would primarily benefit the wealthy. He recalled <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s tie-breaking <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote to cut cost-of-living increases for Social Security, and repeated his suggestion that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> might tap the Social Security trust fund. `` Now, if Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wants another tax give-away for the rich, and if he ca n't think of a single weapons system in the budget that he opposes ... and if he says he's going to bring down the deficit, then how's he going to do it without raiding the Social Security trust fund and trying to cut Social Security and Medicare again?'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` My friends,'' he added, `` Social Security is not a ` welfare program.' Social Security is a contract between generations, and ... I will never break that contract.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaigned in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, a tossup industrial state, a day before <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was taking an eight-hour bus trip across the state. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> appeared with former Democratic rival Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, the city recalled in political memory for the <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> administration's reference to it as a barometer of middle <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.
