<HEAD>Law Enforcement Officials To Study Police Academy Training
Routines</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 7th graf `George F.' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
description of training program; INSERTS 2 grafs after 12th pvs,
`But Grady...' to ADD background on council; SUBS 14th graf pvs,
`Several stricken...' to CORRECT from one cup of water to two;
EDITS 15th graf to conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEEDHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials running a police training school Tuesday defended an exercise session that hospitalized 16 cadets, including one who required a liver transplant. The cadets were treated at hospitals beginning Sept. 19, the first day of classes, with ailments ranging from exhaustion and dehydration to kidney failure. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Egan </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Training </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, said no cadet was denied water during the training and that activity on the first day was no more strenuous than any other group's first day at an academy. `` There was strenuous physical activities, as there always was on that first day ... -LRB- but -RRB- we have found no one that was denied water upon request,'' <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> said at a news conference. The most seriously ill cadet, <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON>, 25, a <LOCATION> Pittsfield </LOCATION> police trainee, collapsed while running on the track and has been in a coma for a week. He received a liver transplant early Tuesday at <ORGANIZATION> Presbyterian-University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> and remained in critical condition. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Purcell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Northampton </LOCATION>, who quit the <ORGANIZATION> Edward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Connelly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Training </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> after one day, said recruits were required to exercise vigorously and were kept moving with pushups and laps if they failed to respond quickly to orders. `` We started at 7:30 a.m. with a formation with our gear _ our jackets, boots and other stuff in a duffel bag weighing 50 to 60 pounds _ and we had to walk to classes carrying the duffel bag above our heads with one arm,'' he said. `` We also moved metal lockers and heavy wood furniture from the basement up to either the second or third floor of the building,'' he said. `` Everybody was pushed to the limit before we even got to the physical training part.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grady </PERSON>, the state's chief epidemiologist, said the cadets who became ill at the training facility in <LOCATION> Agawam </LOCATION> suffered from dehydration and exhaustion. Law enforcement officials said they would investigate training routines at <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> police academies. Nearly three dozen police chiefs from western <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> have asked the state attorney general to have an independent agency investigate the academy. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> McHugh </PERSON>, chairman of the training council, said the council, the state attorney's general office and state police would investigate training procedures in the academies. `` Hopefully the council's mission will be to correct this so it wo n't occur in the future,'' <PERSON> McHugh </PERSON> said. But <PERSON> Grady </PERSON> said, `` We feel at this time that the cause of illness was a relatively insufficient intake of water relative to the amount of exercise they were doing.'' The Executive Office of Public Safety oversees the council, which certifies the state's 12 police academies. <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> said that `` stressful situations'' are often introduced as part of the training to see if any of the cadets may react improperly. `` We'd rather have them do it in the academy than out in the streets,'' <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> said. Asked if it was the cadets who were at fault for not drinking enough water, <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> replied, `` Some of them were unaware of the fact that they were doing damage to themselves. They had a chance to go home every night to rehydrate.'' Several stricken cadets told reporters that they could not comment on their experiences at the training facility without permission from their supervisors. But one former cadet said the training routine was severe and that trainees were allowed only two cups of water before <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> collapsed. `` I've been through basic training in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and it was twice as bad as that,'' said <PERSON> Purcell </PERSON>. `` The doctors told me that if I had gone back for a second day, I could have suffered permanent kidney damage.'' A spokesman at the <ORGANIZATION> Baystate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Springfield </ORGANIZATION> hospital said that <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON> also suffered kidney problems and several of the other cadets received kidney dialysis treatment. Six remained hospitalized. After cadets were urged to seek medical examinations, 21 were found to exhibit symptoms from fatigue and nausea to kidney failure. Dr. <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> Lentz </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Amherst </LOCATION> said Tuesday that she treated three to eight <LOCATION> Holyoke </LOCATION> cadets suffering from fatigue and kidney problems after their first day at the academy in 1984. `` I wish in retrospect that I had pushed harder for them to protest the severity of their training,'' she said.
