<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> told <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> business leaders Tuesday that with Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at the helm, the American economy would sail into `` the <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> Triangle of debt, deficit and dependence.'' The Democratic vice presidential candidate said he and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> were tough, experienced economic managers who would tackle <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade and budget deficits and _ unlike <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> _ would strictly enforce the new trade law aimed at opening up foreign markets to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> products. The <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> senator began a four-day campaign swing with a visit to this key industrial state, where public opinion polls have shown a close race between <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> with 20 electoral votes at stake. `` <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and I both have a long record of success when it comes to dealing with the economy,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. `` <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> took a state that was an economic basket case and turned it around. ... As a businessman, as a senator and as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> I have made it a point to look for honest, bipartisan effective answers to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s economic problems.'' He touted <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' call for expanded public-private partnerships and said promised an activist <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> president willing to listen closely to the needs of business and industry. By contrast, he said, the Reagan-Bush administration has stood idly while the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> lost its edge in research and development of new products and deficits piled up, leaving the nation reliant on foreign bankers to finance its debt. From <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> went to <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, where he criticized <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential nominee <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> for leading the unsuccessful opposition to a law giving workers 60 days' notice before they are laid off. `` But <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> lost the fight against plant closing and the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people won,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> told an airport crowd of about 250. `` We're going to open the <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> season a little early this year.'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> also applauded <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' performance in his Sunday debate with <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` He finally got <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> out of that flag factory and talking about the issues,'' he said. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was spending the remainder of night preparing for the debate next week in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, Neb. He had several briefing books with him. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> told the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> business leaders that since President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> took office eight years ago, the federal budget deficit has nearly tripled, the trade defict has grown to nearly a half-trillion dollars and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been transformed from the largest lending nation to the largest debtor nation. `` Those are the facts and as President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has suggested, facts are stubborn things,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said. `` To me and to <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the facts suggest that staying the course, putting this country on automatic pilot, is not an acceptable thing. Not when the course leads to the <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> Triangle of debt, deficit and dependence.'' He said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> has been `` putting out the word that if <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wins this election you wo n't see any change, they're not going to provide rigorous enforcement of that trade bill ...'' <PERSON> Said </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>: `` That would be a disaster for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> _ and no city knows it better than <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>.'' Tailoring part of his speech to blue-collar workers, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said income in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> has grown slower than the national average and domestic car production has fallen during the economic recovery that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> brags about. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> is to visit President <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>'s birthplace at Independence, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, on Wednesday and deliver a speech that aides said would compare his credentials for the vice presidency with those of <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, 41, an <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator.
