<HEAD>Philippines Senator Calls for Slow Down in Investigations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A senator has called on his congressional colleagues to slow down on investigations. The probes, he said, often never end and keep legislators and other officials from more useful work. `` I have nothing against such investigations per se,'' Sen. <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Saguisag </PERSON> said. `` But I do n't think that when we were elected last year, we would be let loose _ we, 200-plus members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> _ to investigate everyone and everybody. ... `` Whatever is in the headlines today, tomorrow it will be investigated.'' He added that the communist insurgency continues and crime increases because generals and police chiefs spend too much time answering questions at congressional hearings. <PERSON> Saguisag </PERSON> made his appeal for a cutback on probes during a television talk show discussion with Sen. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON> <PERSON> Enrile </PERSON>, who took the opposite view. Just hours before the show, <PERSON> Enrile </PERSON> called for yet another investigation, the 73rd pending before the 23-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The bicameral <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> reconvened last year for the first time since it was abolished in 1972 by the now-deposed President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. Since resuming sessions, both houses have initiated scores of probes on controversies chiefly brought out by <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>'s free-wheeling press. The probes involve subjects ranging from the country's $ 28 billion foreign debt and alleged corruption to religious cults and whether gold bullion is buried under an old <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> fort or if two missing bargeloads of rice are really in the bottom of the sea. In early September, when a top player in the <ORGANIZATION> Philippines </ORGANIZATION>' professional basketball league was benched for no specified reason during a championship series, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> launched an investigation In some cases, investigations have made matters worse. After a recent congressional fact-finding trip to the southern <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, Sen. <PERSON> Leticia </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> <PERSON> Shahani </PERSON> openly accused <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> of annexing six Filipino islands. Her accusation led to calls by other legislators and officials for action just short of war. Mrs. <PERSON> Shahani </PERSON> later apologized, however, saying she failed to verify an allegation made by a naval officer, who had misread a navigational chart. <PERSON> Saguisag </PERSON>, a Harvard-trained lawyer, complained that in many cases, the probes fade into oblivion after media interest wanes. Often, investigations would never have been started if congressmen had bothered to think twice about them, he said. `` I'm dumbfounded by the lack of preliminary staff work,'' <PERSON> Saguisag </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Enrile </PERSON>, the lone opposition member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, recently called for investigations into alleged corruption involving relatives of President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> and the sale of a lot in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> last year. Just before the TV show, he asked for an investigation into what a newspaper called a list of `` economic saboteurs'' prepared by <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Vicente </PERSON> <PERSON> Jayme </PERSON>, which included unidentified legislators. <PERSON> Enrile </PERSON> maintained on the show that probes were necessary to help legislators gather information to prepare legislation. In cases of alleged corruption involving presidential relatives, he said, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should investigate because no one else will. <PERSON> Saguisag </PERSON> said that if investigations were unavoidable, congressmen should be `` more restrained'' in what they say in their sessions about other people, who might be slandered and have no means of redress because congressmen enjoy immunity. <PERSON> Saguisag </PERSON> acknowledged, nevertheless, that as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s ethics committee, he himself is conducting several probes. Asked by program host <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Beltran </PERSON> what punishment <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> can give erring congressmen, <PERSON> Saguisag </PERSON> replied that in the 1950s, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> was suspended for 15 months because he made false charges against the president. `` I am willing to be suspended for 15 months,'' <PERSON> Enrile </PERSON> said. `` I can use it for vacation. But if I will get suspended for the error of information I received, I expect that an equal measure will be applied to a senator of the ruling coalition who has brought us to the brink of war.'' That was a reference to Mrs. <PERSON> Shahani </PERSON> and her erroneous charge against <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
