<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Part I: Deliverance</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto, LaserLogo</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 For a decade, in a bucolic corner of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, the Rev. <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON> ran his <ORGANIZATION> Bethel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> for Children. From time to time, tales of abuse circulated, but nothing came of them _ <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> is one of six states where such church homes are unlicensed and rarely scrutinized. But as this summer began, a boy's tale of beatings, neglect and imprisonment brought state authorities to <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>'s door and ignited a conflict fueled by outrage from both sides. `` Gates of Hell'' is the story of these children, who have been given pseudonyms to protect their identities as required by <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> law, of their lives inside <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> and of the emotional struggle over their futures _ and their souls. This is the first installment of three.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` A wise man feareth, and departeth from evil ...'' _ Proverbs 14:16, from a sign on a building at the <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> children's home.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By LISA LEVITT RYCKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUCEDALE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The time had come. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> was ready. He would hide and wait, and when the moment was right, he would blow through the gates of hell and never look back. Quietly now, quietly. He slipped inside the locker and waited, hardly breathing. The other kids at the <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> Home for Children were filing past, on their way to church. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> opened the locker door. To the bicycle by the steps. Carefully now, carefully. If anyone saw, he would be caught, and there'd be more punishment, more pain, more humiliation. No more. He'd had enough for a lifetime.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Prine </PERSON> had just finished stabling her horse when the phone rang Sunday, May 8. It was after 7 p.m.. As a child welfare investigator in <LOCATION> George </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, she was used to calls at all hours, seven days a week It was the sheriff's office: another runaway from <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> That was n't unusual. The Baptist church home's 10-year history was rife with kids trying to escape its rigorous regimen. <PERSON> Prine </PERSON> had dealt with some of <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>'s children but had never seen the operation firsthand. Because the state does not license its church-run boarding homes, and therefore can not regulate them, it rarely ventures in. Among those who have, some call them hospitals for the soul; others consider them spiritual torture chambers. The truth about the <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> Home for Children was a matter of opinion. In 1980, a runaway brought assault charges against <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>'s founder, the Rev <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON>, for a beating he received with a switch _ `` licks,'' Fountain called them. After a hearing, the <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge removed all the children and directed the church to follow certain regulations. But the charges were dropped and the order was never enforced. Many of the children were returned to <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>. Since then, other children had run away, and others told stories of abuse and neglect. But few had been at <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> long enough to be credible witnesses, the kind whose stories would hold up in court. Now there was <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 He had come to <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> in October 1986 at age 13, a sometime truant sent from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> by his mother. Life might have been hard at home, but <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> was like boot camp with a wrathful God as drill sergeant. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>'s description was the same as those of other children and that of <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON> himself. Each day had a schedule: up at 5 a.m., so many minutes in the bathroom, so many minutes to dress, so many to clean the dormitory. There were prayer sessions morning and evening. In the summers, the children picked beans, pulled weeds on the church's 28 acres, dug ditches, picked up trash and cared for <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>'s menagerie of goats, horses, ducks and deer. Sometimes crews of children would tear down abandoned buildings, including some at <ORGANIZATION> Keesler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Biloxi </LOCATION>, and return with what they salvaged to <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>, where it would become part of new structures they built themselves. There was no payment for work, but plenty of punishment for slackers. In the winters, they had Bible memorization and school. Lessons came from religious workbooks. Often, children had to erase other children's answers to fill in their own. Like every new <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> charge, <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> spent his first month `` on watch'' under the eye of more trusted child. Children on watch were allowed to speak only to designated individuals. It was a way to prevent them from planning escapes. Talking on watch meant sure punishment.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
