<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880927-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-27-88 1149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a AM-GatesofHellI ADV02-1stAdd   09-27 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gates of Hell I, ADV 02-1st Add,0739</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LUCEDALE: sure punishment.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 There were no calls to parents for the first two months, and no visits for the first six. Incoming mail was opened and money was removed. Letters home that complained about <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> were ordered rewritten. Telephone calls, when allowed, were monitored. Meals were heavy on oatmeal, grits and rice. At the end of the week, leftovers were mixed together, a meal the kids called `` compost stew.'' Failure to eat everything on the plate brought punishment. No cigarettes, drugs, alcohol or carbonated drinks were allowed. There was no television, no radio, no movies: these worldly media were of the devil. So were newspapers, magazines and most music, except certain religious selections. At night, trusted children guarded the doors against runaways. No one was allowed out. This was the program, steeped in fundamental religion, rooted in biblical principles and imbued, its supporters said, with the Lord's power to change incorrigibles into God-fearing, clean-living Christians. And anyone who deviated from it, in word, deed or spirit, learned a lesson about pain. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> had learned those lessons well.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Maples </PERSON> questioned <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> closely. <PERSON> Maples </PERSON> had been <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> County </PERSON> prosecutor only since January, but he had already interviewed several former <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> children. The 30-year-old <PERSON> Maples </PERSON> had grown up in <LOCATION> George </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, and he knew a little about <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>. In a town the size of <LOCATION> Lucedale </LOCATION>, with 2,500 residents, it was hard to avoid. Some days at lunchtime, <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> preachers stood out on Main Street, hollering about hell and damnation to passersby. That usually prompted stories from the patrons at the nearby Coffee Pot restaurant, but mostly they left the subject alone. After all, they figured, none of the kids out there was local; they probably were bad kids who deserved what they got. Now this boy was telling Maples stories as awful as any he had heard. It would take testimony from those who'd left earlier and knew <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>, and two more who would leave after his escape, to corroborate his treatment from the day he arrived to the day he fled <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 In 1969, <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON> was a heroin addict dabbling in witchcraft. He had forsaken his native Oklahoma for the streets of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>; in three years, he says, he lost his family and his health, ending up in a <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION> hospital with hepatitis from shooting up with a dirty needle. Then he found the Lord. Born again, he won back his family and went off to bible college in <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, later moving to <LOCATION> Corpus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Christi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, to join the ministries of the Rev. <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> Roloff </PERSON>, an evangelist who ran a well-publicized home for troubled children before his death in a 1982 plane crash. Fountain felt the call to begin his own ministry and his own children's home, and in 1978, he, wife <PERSON> Carol </PERSON>, and seven children pulled into <LOCATION> Lucedale </LOCATION>. His Bethel Baptist church and children's home thrived. At one point, as many as 150 children were on campus. Parents who could afford it paid $ 275 a month plus $ 750 for materials and registration. Some paid less. Some paid nothing. It did n't matter to Fountain. The Lord had called him for this work. The state had tried to shut him down in 1980 and failed. Six years later, the welfare department raided the <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION> Home for Girls in <LOCATION> Hattiesburg </LOCATION>, run by his friend, the Rev. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Wills </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Wills </PERSON>' wife, <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Sue </PERSON>. The 113 girls taken from the home spoke of strip-searches, paddlings and starvation diets. One-fourth of the girls reported missing their menstrual periods for two months to a year _ the result, Mrs. <PERSON> Wills </PERSON> forthrightly explained, of stress brought on by much-needed discipline. Discipline. That was the key to a spiritual life, the <PERSON> Willses </PERSON> believed, and <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON> agreed wholeheartedly. Children needed discipline. It said as much in the Bible, and his charges knew Proverbs 23:13 by heart: `` Do not withhold correction from a child, For if you beat him with a rod, he will not die. You shall beat him with a rod And deliver his soul from hell.'' That was Fountain's calling: delivering young souls from hell.
</TEXT>
