<HEAD>Many Bethel Kids Abandoned by Parents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Gates of Hell II</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA LEVITT RYCKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUCEDALE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Many of the children of <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> are human throwaways, tossed out by parents who no longer want to deal with them or no longer know how. Some of the kids have no parents. Others simply feel as if they do n't. `` I would phone,'' said 12-year-old <PERSON> Joshua </PERSON>, clutching his red-leather Bible. `` But they would n't accept my calls.'' The children, whose names have been changed to meet <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> law about juveniles' identities, came from across the nation, with the majority from <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Some had physical or mental disabilities such as hyperactivity or Down's syndrome Some had emotional problems, drug or alcohol habits or had been in trouble with the police. Others were typical teen-agers experiencing the upheaval of adolescence, and all the confusion and rebellion that comes with growing up. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, adopted at age 7 by people who later changed their minds, bounced in and out of foster homes for years. His last family sent him to <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> two years ago. `` My parents had written me after I was there for a while and said the reason I was there was because they did n't have the facilities to handle me and take care of me. `` They wanted someone who would take the responsibility on them of bringing me up right. My parents never really wanted me.'' Freed from <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> by the state, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> earned his GED equivalency certificate -LRB- because the <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> school is unaccredited, its diplomas are not recognized by any state -RRB- and applied for cosmetology school. He began dating <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON>, another former <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> resident, and they plan to marry someday and raise a family. Both say <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> taught them how not to treat children. `` I'm not going to have my kid switched every second he acts up,'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. `` I'm going to make sure I can deal with it.'' `` I'd try to work out any problems with my child,'' said 15-year-old <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON>, who wants to be a teacher. `` If that did n't work, I'd keep on trying I'd never give up. I'd never send them to a place like <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> are in counseling now, as are all the <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> children in state custody. Months and months of being told that the outside world is Satan's playground, that saying, thinking, doing or feeling certain things will send them straight to hell, has left many confused and fearful. But for others, <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> is salvation. Outsiders do n't understand what they were, what they've become, and what they went through along the way. One after the other they will say they deserved the whippings they used to get, but they do n't deserve the bad rap they're getting now. These are Fountain's success stories, followers like <PERSON> Sophia </PERSON>, who call the pastor `` Daddy.'' Arriving at <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> in 1985 was like landing on another planet for the rebellious 16-year-old street veteran from <LOCATION> Boca </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Raton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, a drug abuser and runaway who frequented every tavern's ladies night in town. `` I thought these people were crazy,'' she recalled. `` I got smart to Brother Fountain, and he said, ` I'm going to bust your bottom!' He showed me a switch. I thought, ` A twig! What's that going to do?''' She soon found out. Back talk to the dorm leader ended in a brawl broken up by <PERSON> Brother </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> and his switch. `` He smacked me around,'' <PERSON> Sophia </PERSON> said. `` It's the first spanking I ever got. And whoa! I knew they meant business. I was cussing up a storm.'' The head leader slapped <PERSON> Sophia </PERSON>'s face, and when <PERSON> Brother </PERSON> <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON> came back, he slapped her, too. `` I said, ` Go ahead and kill me.' Everything had been drained out of me,'' she said. `` All that rebellion that I had built up for 16 years of my life was gone. The devil really was beat out of me.'' She spent a week in the revival room, a small, windowless room used to isolate disruptive children, where two girls pointed out the error of her ways. `` They talked to me and they helped me and they showed me the Lord, and I got saved.'' Her eyes opened, she realized she had finally come home. `` You can say, ` Do good, do good. But they lived it. They're really happy,'' <PERSON> Sophia </PERSON> said, and she started to cry `` I came here and they showed me something like a reason to live, a purpose in life.'' Now 20 and married, dandling her baby boy on her lap, <PERSON> Sophia </PERSON> believes she has found the happiness she craved. `` I love this home,'' she said resolutely. `` I ca n't believe what all these ignorant people are doing, saying I'm brainwashed! If I'm brainwashed, I think everybody needs to be.''
