   EDITOR'S NOTE _ The court-ordered removal of children from the
Bethel Home for Children due to suspicion of brutality and neglect
infuriated founder Herman Fountain, who bitterly regretted his
failure to defy authorities in the name of church rights. Before
the battle of Bethel was over, he would have another chance to do
just that. This is the third and concluding installment of ``Gates
of Hell.''
   ___</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LISA LEVITT RYCKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUCEDALE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Friday's raid at the <ORGANIZATION> Bethel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> for Children was followed by Monday's last stand. Over the weekend, word reached Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Oswald </PERSON> that some of the children who had fled police had returned to <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>. He ordered authorities back to the church to retrieve any children they could find. <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> founder <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON>, in <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> awaiting further hearing testimony, caught wind of the action and ordered his staff to ignore the subpoenas that had summoned them and return to <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>. There would be no compromise on this day. Fountain locked the church doors, barricading three dozen parents and children in the church they had built by hand. Dozens of state troopers and sheriff's deputies stood by for more than three hours, while Welfare Commissioner <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> tried to negotiate the childrens' release. Police finally broke in and took the children, while church members recited Bible verse and sang hymns. `` If God be for us who can be against us?'' read the <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> sign by the road. Fountain; his eldest son, <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, nicknamed <PERSON> Bubba </PERSON>, and Brother <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> were among eight people arrested that day. Fountain faces three counts of felonious assault on a police officer and one count of inciting a riot, all scheduled to be presented to the grand jury later this month. Troubles seemed to overrun the pastor like the locusts of Pharaoh's <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. A former <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> resident, <PERSON> Rhonnda </PERSON> <PERSON> Traxler </PERSON>, gathered reporters outside the courthouse and alleged Fountain sexually molested her and another girl while they were at <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>. Fountain denied the accusation and leveled his own: `` You ca n't believe this girl There's no telling how many men she's been with.'' Another former <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> child, <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Friery </PERSON>, filed a $ 1 million federal lawsuit against <ORGANIZATION> Fountain </ORGANIZATION>, alleging assault and battery, abuse, neglect and false imprisonment. Fountain was n't the only one with problems. Many state workers involved in the case received harassing phone calls or believed they were being followed by <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> supporters. <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> sent his 13-year-old daughter out of state after anonymous callers threatened to kidnap her and put her in a church home where she would never be found again.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Before the Youth Court hearings ended, about half of the more than 70 children taken from <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> had testified. Some were too frightened to appear. `` They're really wicked little kids,'' <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON> said in a later interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` I'm talking about homosexuals, I'm talking about lesbians, I'm talking about prostitutes. I'm talking about one boy who raped his 84-year-old grandmother. I'm talking about one who murdered his sister. `` I'm talking habitual runaways, I'm talking car thieves, I'm talking nymphomaniacs. <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> dealt with the same youngsters but saw something different. `` For the most part, they're pretty normal kids who have been battered around by life pretty badly,'' the welfare commissioner said. `` They're children trying to put their lives back together.'' Some parents had despaired of getting help from state agencies; for them, <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> was a last resort. For others, it was a matter of convenience. One child was sent to <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> because he `` took food from the refrigerator,'' <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said. But as the hearing continued after the raid on <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>, some parents sat in the courtroom and wept, overwhelmed by stories of hair-pulling, face-slapping, lap-running and switchings. A 13-year-old girl with Down's syndrome said she ran laps all day long, received frequent spankings and sometimes stood for hours on tiptoe with her chin above a light switch. `` They said she was a little brat and had a demon in her,'' another girl said. `` Parents agreed with it. They said that's what you deserve if you've acted in a wrong way.'' Some parents said they were misled. They did n't know what <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> really was. Other parents knew exactly what <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> was. `` When I went down there, I was totally convinced what had occurred was not morally right, legally right or anyway right,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Birdsboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa </LOCATION>. But his two teen-age sons support Fountain, and they changed his mind.
</TEXT>
