<TEXT>
 `` They love the man tremendously. If my children said to me, ` Dad, that's not the way it was, they were cruel and abused us,' I'd be after Brother Fountain,'' he said. `` But they've solidified my support.'' About 50 of the children were released to their parents, who signed a court agreement not to return them to <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> without the judge's approval. Protecting the children this way was about all the state and Judge <PERSON> Oswald </PERSON> could do since <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> is a private, unregulated facility. Now a dozen parents, including <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON>, are preparing a lawsuit against the state for its action at <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>. `` I look at this much beyond just an incident that occurred in the state of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> said. `` Let's term it religious harassment.'' __ = Life is slow at <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> these days, with so few children around The home remains open, but rows of girls' bunk beds stand empty except for the stuffed bears and rabbits left behind by former occupants. A few new children have come since the hearings. A few former residents have returned. No winner has emerged from the emotional battle over <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>, which begins and ends with a collision of convictions. <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> and his team of investigators, <PERSON> Oswald </PERSON> and prosecutor <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Maples </PERSON> consider it a matter of child protection. <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON>, his faithful flock and other fundamentalists who came to lend support have called it an issue of religious freedom. Conservative religious belief courses through <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s veins and beats fiercely in its heart The perception that the state is venturing into the realm of the church makes blood run hot. But so does the perception that church home operators are using fundamental religion and the Bible as justification to abuse and neglect children. `` I'm a Christian; they're supposed to be Christians,'' said welfare investigator <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Prine </PERSON>, who teaches Sunday school at her Baptist church. `` I believe this is wrong. These kids are being physically abused. These people claim the kids are liars and are not being abused but are being raised by what the Bible says. `` It makes you question your faith and your job. When we went in there, I asked someone, ` Am I hurting the church? Am I hurting God's work by doing this?' I thought about it, and I said, ` No. No, I'm not.''' <PERSON> Oswald </PERSON>, in his order removing the children from <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>, wrote, `` If there is a conflict of interests between religion and the protection of children, this Court's decision must be to protect first the children.'' Fountain sees it another way. `` I dealt with -LRB- <PERSON> Oswald </PERSON> -RRB- in chambers, about his soul. He says, ` The laws of the land are first and that -LRB- the -RRB- Bible's second,''' <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON> said. `` I said, ` That's wrong, that Bible's first and the law of the land is second.' <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, along with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, has no law licensing church-run boarding homes, although some voluntarily apply for licenses. As a result, there is no way to reach many of the children in such homes, many of whom are denied communication with the outside for months at a time, or to ensure that basic educational, sanitation and safety standards are met. `` We've had to wait years to collect information in bits and pieces from runaway children,'' <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> said. `` We have no way of knowing what's going on inside those four walls.'' <PERSON> Maples </PERSON> has filed a court petition to force <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> to comply with state laws governing education, safety standards and child labor laws. The court has yet to act on it. If enforced, such an order could close <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>, because Fountain has said he would never cooperate. For the two years he has been welfare commissioner, <PERSON> Brittain </PERSON> has pushed for a law to open the doors of homes like <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>; Fountain has prayed against one. This might well be the year that the power of prayer is overcome by the power of politics: observers agree that outrage over conditions at <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION> has been so great that the Legislature might be forced to act. Even Fountain agrees, saying, `` It would take an act of God'' to prevent a licensure law from emerging in the next legislative session. At <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>, they will be praying round the clock. `` They're going against God, and that's their problem. That's why we're going to win,'' <PERSON> Fountain </PERSON> said `` The gates of hell ai n't going to prevail against our church.
