</LOCATION> Military Adademy was kindly requested not to fire its touchdown cannon at football games. On Thursday mornings the entire student body gathered in Clothier Memorial for `` collection,'' an assembly dedicated to moral or cultural uplift by friendly persuasion. In World War I, an army training unit was permitted on campus, but the cadets paraded without rifles. British poet W.H. <PERSON> Auden </PERSON> taught composition to a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> V-12 unit in World War II, when the campus was a meld of O.C.'s and C.O.'s: cadet officers and conscientious objectors. After much agonizing, the administration rejected an <ORGANIZATION> ROTC </ORGANIZATION> unit during the Korean War. Two months after arriving on campus, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on Nov. 3, l951, celebrated his 18th birthday by registering for the draft. There were recurrent reminders in the <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> from Gen. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Blaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Hershey </PERSON> that students were not exempt but deferred from the draft if they maintained a C-average. An army recruiter took pains one day to explain that `` in an infantry division of 20,000 men, only 3,000 carried rifles while the great majority were occupied in non-combat units.'' His remarks concluded to polite applause and the release of a dove. `` Many were critical of our involvement in the war,'' <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Stott </PERSON> remembers, `` but the college made it clear this was a moral obligation.'' Actually, fraternities were a bigger issue on campus in the early'50s. <ORGANIZATION> Swarthmore </ORGANIZATION> was and is a dry town, and the five frat houses offered beer along with brotherhood. `` A wild Friday night party might go on until 12:30,'' says <PERSON> Leigh </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitaker </PERSON>, who like <PERSON> Preston </PERSON>, belonged to <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upsilon </ORGANIZATION> when their <LOCATION> Wharton <