<SECOND>BC-APN--Kane's Firsts, ADV 09-2 Takes,0874</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv09</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 9</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&amp;w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 He has written 50 books, a thousand newspaper articles and once had his own wire service. But mostly <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> is a collector of facts about who was the first to do this or that, a debunker of erroneous history. It's been his calling for most of his 89 years.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By KAY BARTLETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> tells a visitor to come to the 27th floor of an upper <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION> building that has only 25 floors. He promises a $ 5 million view with $ 5 worth of furniture. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> will also tell you that the Declaration of Independence was not signed on July 4, 1776, that <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> was not the first president, that <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> did not invent the sewing machine and that <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Duryea </PERSON> really manufactured the first automobile regularly made for sale. The 89-year-old ex-newspaperman and author is serious. <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> is not just the author, but the entire staff of one of the most unusual and most enduring reference books in the world _ `` Famous First Facts: A Record of First Happenings, Discoveries, and Inventions in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' as its first edition was called when it was published in 1933. <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> is now working on the fifth edition _ the fourth came out in 1981 _ as well as four other books he hopes to publish within a year or two. Everything emanates out of this unusual apartment that has more paper, 3-by-5 index cards, reference books and book cases than places to sit down. Except for a few plants and the Dr Pepper he keeps in the half-refrigerator, not much in this oddly shaped oblong room seems to have been purchased in the last half-century. Make that century. <PERSON> Kane </PERSON>, sole inhabitant of this garret for more than 25 years, is not a man who exaggerates. The view from what passes as a kitchen is worth $ 5 million, stretching up the <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, beyond the <LOCATION> George </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION>, down to the World Trade Center and beyond, across into <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. So what if you have to walk up the last two flights because the elevator stops on 25? <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> is author of more than 50 books, some of which he churned out to pay the rent, such as a forgettable volume called `` What Dog Is That?'' describing various breeds of dogs. He also has sold more than 1,000 newspaper articles. He once had his own news service and was an accredited White House correspondent. He has been called a historian, a detective of facts, and a deglorifier of American history. `` History,'' he proclaims, `` is a glorification of fairy tales. There is n't a thing you know that is correct, but still it is better to know something that is wrong than not to know anything.'' It is better, for instance, to think that <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> was the first president than not to have any idea. The truth is <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> was the first president elected under the Constitution, but <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> McKean </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> was the first president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> Assembled under the Articles of Confederation in 1781, eight years before <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> took office. It is also good to know the importance of July 4, 1776. But the accurate version, according to <PERSON> Kane </PERSON>, is that the Declaration of Independence was first ordered `` to be fairly engrossed on parchment'' on July 19, 1776, and was signed in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> on Aug. 2 by 50 members of the original 56 who voted for its adoption. The other six signed at later times, the last being <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> McKean </PERSON>, who was permitted to sign as late as 1781 due to serving in the Army away from <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. `` Over 50 people have told me their father invented the automobile, for example,'' he says. `` When I start verifying claims, I find that someone's father may have invented the fourth knob on the fifth spark plug on the sixth day at 7 o'clock,'' says <PERSON> Kane </PERSON>. `` But he did n't invent the automobile.'' It was <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Duryea </PERSON> who opened the <ORGANIZATION> Duryea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wagon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, in 1895. He began building his automobile in 1891 and first successfully operated it on April 19, 1892. <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> publishes only those facts that can be verified by patent offices, official records in the Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, or other original data. `` I'm stupid enough not to believe anything until I see the proof,'' he says. <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> wrote his first book in 1929. It was n't until four years later, rejected by 11 publishers, that he sold the idea to the H.W. <ORGANIZATION> Wilson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, with a little help from librarians he met as he crisscrossed the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on an 11-month tour. He showed them the local facts, which they knew to be correct, and then beseeched them to write to the California-based company and say they would love to have such a tome in their reference rooms.
</TEXT>
