<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 9</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Newsfeatures Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Curlee </PERSON> and her two sisters used to sing as the <ORGANIZATION> Curlee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sisters </ORGANIZATION>, their mother had dreams of their becoming as famous as <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Welk </PERSON>'s Lennon Sisters. But it was the'60s and girl groups were passe. But one decade's passe is a later decade's nostalgia. Today <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Curlee </PERSON> is one of the four singing actresses appearing in `` The Taffetas,'' an off-Broadway hit at the Cherry Lane Theater. They play four rather naive, singing sisters living in <LOCATION> Muncie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, in the 1950s and making an out-of-town appearance as a group called the Taffetas. `` We're not a slick girls group,'' <PERSON> Curlee </PERSON> says. `` We have n't gotten that far. <PERSON> Curlee </PERSON>, at 34, and her `` sister'' Taffetas are too young to remember when songs like `` Mockin' Bird Hill'' -LRB- <PERSON> Patti </PERSON> <PERSON> Page </PERSON> -RRB-, `` Ricochet'' -LRB- <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Brewer </PERSON> -RRB-, `` Mr. <PERSON> Sandman </PERSON>'' -LRB- Chordettes -RRB-, `` Dedicated to the One I Love'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Shirelles </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, and `` Sincerely'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> McGuire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sisters </ORGANIZATION> cover of a Moonglows hit -RRB-, were on `` The Hit Parade.'' Audiences at the Cherry Lane range from people who do remember those songs with nostalgia to younger listeners curious about what was pop just before rock to girls admiring the Taffetas' prom dresses. The other Taffetas are <PERSON> Tia </PERSON> <PERSON> Speros </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jody </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrahams </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Melanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> has sung in a show set in the 1940s, playing <PERSON> Patti </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> of the Andrews Sisters On TV she has been <PERSON> Angela </PERSON>, a rich girl who got into drugs, on `` Another World'' and <PERSON> Judy </PERSON>, a mean high-school cheerleader, on `` As the World Turns.'' <PERSON> Curlee </PERSON>, from <LOCATION> Fresno </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, became a Taffeta just before the Cherry Lane Theater opening in August, when <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> left to play Grizabella, the `` Memory'' cat, in `` Cats'' in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Curlee </PERSON> had been understudying five cats in `` Cats'' on Broadway for two years. `` The Taffetas'' is the brainchild of <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, who's onstage playing piano at the Cherry Lane with two other musicians. Researching'50s music, he was amazed to find <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON>'s record of `` A Bushel and a Peck.'' `` I thought my mother made that up to put the kids to sleep.'' Now he's working on four-part harmony for `` <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Baby </LOCATION>,'' an <PERSON> Eartha </PERSON> <PERSON> Kitt </PERSON> hit 34 years before <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON> recorded it, to insert into the show before Christmas. He thought of the name, a takeoff on the Chiffons, then the image, the McGuire Sisters. `` They captured what the'50s singing group was like _ gorgeous, great teeth and smiles and they sang incredibly,'' he says. The Taffetas are n't singing note-for-note the'50s arrangements. `` But if you do n't hear something that sounds like what you remember,'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> says, `` you ca n't really remember it.'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> also picked the Taffetas' hometown, <LOCATION> Muncie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, a place none of the quartet ever has been. He visited there, for journalism seminars, from his high school in <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. The Taffetas have been written about recently on Page 1 of the <ORGANIZATION> Muncie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION>, under the headline, `` Natives of a Town They Never Knew.'' `` We're giving everybody from <LOCATION> Muncie </LOCATION> free tickets to see the show, if they can prove it,'' <PERSON> Curlee </PERSON> says. In college, <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> studied music education, then did some acting and musical directing. He moved to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> thinking he'd pursue both. He included on his resume his <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> musical directing credits. He got offered musical directing jobs, often for industrial shows. `` I'd build shows from scratch. They would spend $ 50,000 and it would be performed one night. I did a show that was $ 100,000 a few years ago.'' Trying for a reuseable, cheaper approach, he put together the Taffetas. `` We kept showcasing it for people who book those things. The amount of people we fed and gave booze to over a two-year period _ I'd like to spend that much on parties for my friends sometime. They'd say, ` When you've got reviews, let us know.''' So <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> took the Taffetas into two <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> cabarets, Do n't Tell Mama and Westbeth Cabaret Theater `` I thought we'd put a nice little brochure together. Instead we got fabulous reviews. We were chased by producers wanting us off-Broadway. We made the best choice. We took <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitelaw </PERSON>.'' Since `` The Taffetas'' is an off-Broadway hit, there are offers for industrial shows, conventions and parties. Asked what they think about the 1950s songs they're singing, <PERSON> Speros </PERSON> says, `` They have an underlying sweet, smiling quality.'' <PERSON> Curlee </PERSON> says, `` They sang much slower then. My inner tempo as a 34-year-old woman is to lock in much faster.'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> says, `` Being slower, you can understand the lyrics. Not having angst in the voice makes a more vulnerable, innocent and youthful sound. I think this music grows on you. For me, it does.'' <PERSON> Abrahams </PERSON> says, `` I love the lyrics. I think ` I Cried' -LRB- Patti Page -RRB- is one of the most beautiful songs. It pulls on those heartstrings.'' The Taffetas were photographed with <PERSON> Patti </PERSON> <PERSON> Page </PERSON> when she sang recently at a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> nightspot. `` She does a lot of our songs,'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> says with a smile.
