<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>BANGKOK: Asian country.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Sigur </PERSON> ascribed the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> demonstrations to `` Korean nationalism reacting to the visible presence of another nation's soldiers. This sort of problem is difficult to eradicate entirely.'' However, this very military muscle is welcomed by much of the rest of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, including <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which continues to have shaky relations with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> while building what <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomats call a `` solid, mature, many-sided'' relationship with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is entrenched at <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Cam </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ranh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, its largest military base outside the homeland, and enjoys a close alliance with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has also made political and economic inititatives since 1986 when General Secretary <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> declared in <LOCATION> Vladivostok </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> that the `` <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is also an Asian Pacific country.'' Recently he offered to pull out of <PERSON> Cam </PERSON> <PERSON> Ranh </PERSON> <PERSON> Bay </PERSON> if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> terminated its air and naval stations in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. `` The real, long-term and very difficult obstacle to remove is not the American bases but the Soviet bases and military alliance,'' the head of <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Noordin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sopiee </PERSON>, wrote this year. Asians are also noting that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has become the world's fifth largest spender on defense and is taking a more aggressive role in international politics. In countries like <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, Japanese atrocities in World War II are far from forgotten. `` What kind of a leader is <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> when it worries more about selling transistors than human rights?'' asked an <LOCATION> Indonesian </LOCATION> intellectual, remarking that unlike the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, the Japanese mission in <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION> shuns opposition figures for fear of losing the government's favor _ and business. <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Calder </PERSON> said, `` In comparison with the Japanese juggernaut the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> superpower is more appealing to many Asians... There are a lot of people after <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> who see the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> as more distant, the lesser evil if you will. They balance the generosity of the Americans with the mercantilism, the strategic approach of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>.'' To offset what many Asians call <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s `` economic invasion,'' they urge the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to increase its trade, aid and investment in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. The Japanese have outpaced the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in all three in recent years. Official development assistance by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> countries in 1987 was $ 3.4 billion in contrast to less than $ 900 million from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy makers also say the democratic wave that has in recent years swept the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and now <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>, along with the economic failures of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s communist societies, are in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest. The emerging democracies, they say, are not only closer to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> system and spirit but also eliminate the earlier dilemma of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> propping up right-wing, anti-communist dictators. This had been a source of anti-Americanism in the past.
</TEXT>
