<HEAD>Strasbourg, City of Reconciliation, Awaits Pope John Paul II</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note Oct. 8 date 3rd graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After centuries at the center of a tug-of-war between <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, this city nestled on a tranquil river now harmonizes <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> joie de vivre with German efficiency. `` <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION> is a symbol,'' says Deputy Mayor <PERSON> Germain </PERSON> <PERSON> Muller </PERSON>, who is in charge of the celebrations marking the city's 2,000 th anniversary this year `` <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which often fought over this place, are now the countries leading us toward a united <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.'' Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> will spend four days, beginning Oct. 8, in this city between <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Vosges </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>. He will address the entity that symbolizes <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> unity, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, which meets in the chambers of the Council of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. In coming to <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION>, the pope will not find a better place to illustrate reconciliation _ an appropriate theme at a time when the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in the area is shaken by a traditionalist schism. Memories of the Nazi occupation are fresh enough to cause <PERSON> Strasbourgeois </PERSON>, as the local people are called, to feel passionately French. Taxi drivers boast that the French national anthem, the <PERSON> Marseillaise </PERSON>, was written here. Shopkeepers mention that <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonaparte </PERSON> came here to go to school. The city is still the biggest university town in eastern <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. They mention less often, however, that <PERSON> Goethe </PERSON> studied here, too, or that <PERSON> Johann </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutenberg </PERSON> spent a decade in <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION> inventing the intricate press on which he later produced his Bible, the first book printed with movable type. For centuries <LOCATION> Alsace </LOCATION> and the neighboring region of <PERSON> Lorraine </PERSON> were part of an independent republic bordering the <LOCATION> Rhine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. From 1870 to 1945, the region passed regularly back and forth between German and French hands. The bicultural history is felt today in nearly every aspect of daily life _ from the bildings on the street to the music on the radio. Even the names of city streets reveal <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION>'s seesaw history. In 1871, Avenue <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> became <PERSON> Kaiser </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilhelmstrasse </PERSON>, after the Germans moved in. That was changed to <ORGANIZATION> Boulevard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> la </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republique </ORGANIZATION> after World War I. Then for some years it was known as <ORGANIZATION> Adolf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hitler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strasse </ORGANIZATION> until it was given its current name, Avenue <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaulle </PERSON>, when the French reclaimed the city at the end of World War II. The avenue today is filled with a blitzkrieg of German tourists who arrive by the busload in this city of 400,000, just two miles from the West German border. They are outnumbered only by French sightseers who stroll through the narrow, medieval streets of half-timbered houses, past outdoor cafes and hidden courtyards and over picturesque bridges on the Ill River. Many people speak both German and French, and older people often are fluent in Alsatian, the regional linguistic hybrid. The intertwining of cultures has produced a cuisine that melds German ingredients and French know-how to cook up regional dishes like choucroute _ sauerkraut and smoked meat cooked in wine. Kronenbourg beer is brewed here. Rhine wines, in a dry French style, are produced nearby. Cuisines and languages have blended with ease; the region's two religions have not. Unlike most of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, which is 80 percent <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Alsace-Lorraine </LOCATION> is half <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION>. `` When a <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> girl married a Catholic boy here it used to be considered a disgrace. Except for a very few small villages, it's not that way anymore,'' said City Councilman <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Roos </PERSON>, whose father was a medical officer in the German army in World War I and in the French army in World War II. <PERSON> Roos </PERSON> said the two groups now live in harmony. The discord these days is within the Catholic church itself. In June, a long-brewing dispute between the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> traditionalists culminated in the excommunication of rebel Archbishop <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON>. It was the first schism within the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in more than a century and has led to repeated calls by the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> hierarchy for unity in the face of the challenge posed by <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON> and his flock. As he did on a trip to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> two years ago, Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> is likely to stress loyalty to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> on this visit, which begins at <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION>'s massive cathedral, a dramatic setting for the pope's first speech Built between 1190 and 1489 by master French and Rhineland craftsmen, the pink sandstone cathedral rises 465 feet and was the highest building in the Christian world until a century ago. Inside is an astronomical clock of ingenious works. At 12:30 each afternoon a bell is struck by a figure representing Death, while the 12 Apostles receive the blessing of Christ and a cock, beating its wings, crows three times in memory of <PERSON> Peter </PERSON>'s denial. A perpetual calendar on the clock calculates the phases of the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION>, solar eclipses and rising and setting of the sun. While here, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> also will speak at both the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and Council of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The presence of these two European institutions has stirred the ambitions of some local boosters. `` It is not surprising the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> is coming here,'' said <PERSON> Roos </PERSON>. `` One day we wo n't be just another beautiful city. Someday we will be the capital of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.''
</TEXT>
