<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Broadcast News'' -LRB- CBS-Fox Video; VHS @ Beta, $ 89.98; Rated R -RRB- One advantage in seeing `` Broadcast News'' at home is the opportunity to give the film a more satisfying ending than the feeble conclusion reached by director <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>. Just stop when you've had enough _ at least two good opportunities will arise _ and savor the satisfaction of saving a film in the cutting room. For most of its length, though, `` Broadcast News'' is a witty and often hilarious human comedy set in the high-pressure world of network journalism. This highly praised film inexplicably was snubbed at the Academy Award ceremonies, after winning seven nominations. However, <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> deservedly won best-actress awards from critics in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> play bright, dedicated and tough news professionals who worry about the inroads of fluffy feature stories and blow-dried airheads on the anchor desk. We know they are the very best of journalists because they say so, rather often. Their media <PERSON> Eden </PERSON> is invaded by a blow-dried, airhead snake named <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Grunick </PERSON> -LRB- William Hurt -RRB-. However, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> establishes himself as a sympathetic figure. He's the only character who appears to have any humility, admitting that he's no genius and forthrightly asking help from <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> -LRB- Hunter -RRB-. What he knows is how to look good and sound smart, and he generously offers tips on anchoring to <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON> <PERSON> Altman </PERSON> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Brooks </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ perhaps knowing that the neurotic <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON> is no competition. <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> runs at such a high pitch that she often loses perspective. When her boss sarcastically tells her that it must be great to always be the smartest person in the room, she takes him seriously. `` No, it's awful,'' she sobs. Though <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> and Hurt turn in first-class performances, this is <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>'s movie and it runs on her energy. It's not just the two guys in the film who will fall in love with her. _ By <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Switching Channels'' -LRB- RCA @ <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>; VHS @ Beta, $ 89.95; Rated PG -RRB- `` Switching Channels,'' a film of romantic antics in a satellite TV station, had the bad luck of appearing in movie houses last March several months after `` Broadcast News,'' a far better satire of the TV news business. But let's be fair. Do n't compare `` Switching Channels'' to `` Broadcast News,'' or to classics on the same newsroom theme from which it was derived: `` The Front Page'' and `` His Girl Friday.'' No, `` Switching Channels'' is so silly, predictable, miscast and lost in its lame attempt at broad comedy that a more apt comparison would be to `` Francis the Talking Mule.'' <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> plays an ace reporter at a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> TV station. <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> is her boss and ex-husband. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> takes a vacation and meets <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Reeve </PERSON>, a wealthy <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> manufacturer of sporting goods including, ha ha, jockstraps. They fall in love, and <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> agrees to go East and leave <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> and the news biz behind. Wily <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> is having none of that. He hooks Turner into covering one last big story, the execution of a convicted cop killer, played by <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON>. When it's all over, and <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> must decide between <PERSON> Reeve </PERSON> and <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON>, the only question becomes how could someone supposedly so smart wind up torn between such a pair of shnooks? And do you really care which she choses? Turner does the most with limp material. <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON>, usually very good in such broad comedy, never gets started here. <PERSON> Reeve </PERSON>, who showed flashes of drollery as <PERSON> Superman </PERSON>, is miserably miscast as a foppish, brainless rich boy who's scared of elevators. Director <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Kotcheff </PERSON> seems willing to let the actors drift and mug pretty much as they will. `` Switching Channels'' is rated PG for occasional tart language. _ By <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitgang </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
