<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Chimes of Freedom'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON> This extended play recording was released to coincide with the six-week Human Rights Now! global tour now under way featuring <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON>, Sting, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> and a host of other musicians, with some of the EP's proceeds donated to the human rights group <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>. The disc's four songs were all recorded live during <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON>'s 1988 `` Tunnel of Love'' tour; the opening `` Tougher Than the Rest'' already appears on that album. This live version, recorded at the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sports </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arena </LOCATION>, has a slower, more country-tinged tempo to it, and wraps up nicely with fine harmonica work by <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON>. `` Be True,'' recorded at the <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, is what <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON> fans would call typical `` B Side <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON>.'' The artist has a penchant for putting catchy, danceable tunes on the flip sides of his singles that are n't included on any album. Backed, as always, by the hard-rocking E Street Band, <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON> croons to the fictional heroine, `` You be true to me and I'll be true to you.'' Is n't it kind of tacky for <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON>, whose split with wife <PERSON> Julianne </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> made all the gossip columns during his tour, to include this song here? Incidentally, vocals by back-up singer <PERSON> Patti </PERSON> <PERSON> Scialfa </PERSON>, with whom <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON> is now involved, are far more prominent on this EP than on any previous recording. `` Chimes of Freedom,'' the third song, is alone worth buying this EP for. The <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON> protest song is the perfect anthem for the <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> tour, and <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON>'s rendering, recorded in <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, is faithful to the original. The artist, whose lyrics were often compared to <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON>'s early in his career, proves he can salute his influences and still add something uniquely his own to their songs. By far the most ambitious of the four songs is <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON>'s acoustic version of `` Born to Run,'' also recorded in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> That song was the artist's signature tune before being replaced by `` Born in the <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>,'' and it had the raw power of a motorcycle opened up at full throttle. However, <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON>, who has proven himself an accomplished accoustic artist with `` <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>'' and several cuts on `` Tunnel of Love,'' falls flat here. His vocals meander all over the place like a <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> prose-poem and the impression is one of the motorcycle run out of gas and being pushed along like a scooter. _ By <PERSON> Geneva </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Still Live'' -LRB- ECM -RRB- _ <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarrett </PERSON> <PERSON> Trio </PERSON> <PERSON> Jazz </PERSON> pianist <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarrett </PERSON>, who unlike many of his electronic-minded contemporaries still plays only the piano, has never sounded better than in this two-disc live recording. Communicating intuitively with bassist <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Peacock </PERSON> and drummer <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> DeJohnette </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jarrett </PERSON> combined his signature moody chord voicings with sharp improvising in a collection of jazz standards for a concert audience in <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. He took the songs' familiar melodies and stretched, twisted and bent them in fascinating ways. The listener is never lost, though, and he ends each journey back at the beginning, exhilarated and ready for another. <PERSON> Jarrett </PERSON>'s interpretation of `` My Funny Valentine'' was understated and sensitive, while `` When I Fall in Love'' became a ballad with a bit of an attitude. `` Come Rain or Come Shine'' had just the right bluesy edge. Only `` The Song Is You,'' a Kern-Hammerstein composition, failed to achieve a groove that matched its length, nearly 17 minutes. <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarrett </PERSON> is an intelligent pianist who has done his share of experimenting. `` Still Live,'' with its classic tunes played on acoustic piano, should give purists plenty to cheer about. _ <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Day By Day'' -LRB- EMI-Manhattan -RRB- _ <PERSON> Najee </PERSON> <PERSON> Najee </PERSON> sets a mellow groove on his second LP, `` Day By Day,'' and never strays very far from the course. The album is always tasteful, with the New Yorker's soaring saxophone solos taking center stage and showing his jazz and rhythm and blues influences. Back-up singers dart in and out of the arrangements, keeping things moving along smoothly. But the album tends to be swallowed up by its tastefulness, and often fades into backround music. While this album can be the perfect accompaniment to a romantic dinner, it unfortunately is just as appropriate later on when the dishes are being washed. Only `` <PERSON> Najee </PERSON>'s Nasty Groove,'' a funky track dominated by drums and synthesizer, breaks the mold. Anyone in the market for some easy listening jazz could do worse than this album. But those looking for something more, well, inspiring, would do well to keep on looking. _ By <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
