<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The life's work of sculptor <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> has gone on show in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in a comprehensive way that was never managed while he lived. `` We discussed an exhibition with him in 1984 to mark his 90th birthday this year, but he died in 1986. Now this is his memorial,'' said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Grey </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION>. The venerable academy, which has been presenting art exhibitions since 1768, has done <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> proud, spreading 112 sculptures and 127 drawings by him through its 12 main galleries to show all the stages of his career. There are Giant abstract bronzes and lifesize human figures in stone that had to be lifted in by crane, and little plaster figures smaller than a hand. His famous drawings of restless sleepers who sought refuge in the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> subway to escape bombings in World War II also are shown, along with sketches of coal miners, trees, elephants, sheep, landscapes and ideas for sculpture, often based on bones, stones and bits of wood which he picked up. Dr. <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Compton </PERSON>, a British art historian who organized a popular exhibition of <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Chagall </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION>, spent 15 months arranging the exhibition, which ru a global thing. That's where the ` Small World' concept came from. The album's first single is the brassy `` Perfect World'' written by <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Call </PERSON>, a longtime friend of <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>' who used to be in his old country-rock band Clover. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said the second single will be an edited version of `` Small World -LRB- Part One -RRB-'' and the instrumental `` Small World -LRB- Part Two -RRB-,'' which features a guest appearance by jazz saxophonist <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Getz </PERSON>. `` I once went to a benefit show with my dad, who's a jazz drummer, and <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> came up and introduced himself to me,'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> recalled. `` He said, ` Hey man, why do n't you let me play on some of your stuff? I can play that stuff, too.' Then he gave me a card that said, ` <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Getz </PERSON>: Have Sax, Will Travel.''' Other album cuts are the 1960s-style soul instrumental `` Slammin','' the Cajun-sounding `` Old Antone's'' which features a guest appearance by <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Hornsby </PERSON> on accordion, the reggae-tinged love song `` Better Be True'' and the pure reggae jam `` Bobo Tempo.'' `` ` Bobo Tempo' was written by <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> and myself about 13 years ago when we were both in Clover,'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said. `` It was for a gig we had in <LOCATION> Bolinas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> ` <PERSON> Bobo </PERSON>' is a nickname for <LOCATION> Bolinas </LOCATION>, which is a nutty place. We used to play out there every so often and there would be huge street parties. `` We wrote the song just for that one gig, just for a laugh really,'' he said. `` On the last day of the `` Fore!'' album sessions -LRB- in 1986 -RRB-, we piled into the studio at midnight and cut that song. The track really held up.'' But not the video, which involves a topless girl, a surfer and a horse on a surfboard and probably will never be commercially released. The cleft-chinned <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, born <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Cregg </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, grew up near <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and was known as `` <PERSON> Huey </PERSON> <PERSON> Louie </PERSON>'' when he joined Clover in 1972. He changed his name to <PERSON> Huey </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> when he formed his band in late 1979 with <PERSON> Hopper </PERSON>, 35, <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, 30, and three members of the <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Area </LOCATION> group Soundhole _ <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON>, 36, <PERSON> Cipollina </PERSON>, 33, and <PERSON> Colla </PERSON>, 36. The group originally was called <PERSON> Huey </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>, but the name was quickly altered to avoid an infringment lawsuit. Their self-titled first album in 1980 went nowhere, but the follow-up `` Picture This'' in 1982 had the Top 10 hits `` Workin' for a Livin''' and `` Do You Believe in Love. Next came the landmark `` Sports'' album, which has sold 9 million copies since its September 1983 release and won several Grammy Awards. It spawned five Top 10 singles including `` I Want a New Drug'' and `` Heart of Rock & amp; Roll.'' In 1985, the band had its first No. 1 single with `` Power of Love,'' an Oscar-nominated song recorded for the year's largest-grossing movie, `` Back to the Future. The tour will take <PERSON> Huey </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> and The News well into 1989 and mark their 10th anniversary together. `` I'd be surprised if we're not together another 10 years,'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said. `` But it's funny. I still remember when we got our first paycheck from our manager, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. I remember I told him, ` I got to have $ 150 a week for these guys. Otherwise, that's it.' It does n't seem that long ago.''
