<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Keith Whitley Is Just Getting Started</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rising country music performer <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitley </PERSON> says his career is just getting started even though he's been singing on the road for 18 years The 33-year-old singer hit the top of the country music charts in August with the single `` Do n't Close Your Eyes.'' The album of the same name has been in the Top 10. `` We're at the point where all systems are go,'' said <PERSON> Whitley </PERSON>, whose honky-tonk style of singing is traditional country music with lyrics embracing pain and joy. `` That sounds odd for somebody who's been on the road for -LRB- about -RRB- 20 years. He was only 15 when he and friend <PERSON> Ricky </PERSON> <PERSON> Skaggs </PERSON>, a year older, joined <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Clinch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boys </ORGANIZATION>, a bluegrass band. Like <PERSON> Whitley </PERSON>, <PERSON> Skaggs </PERSON> eventually became a solo country singer. <PERSON> Whitley </PERSON> then survived his remaining, reckless teen-age years and battled a stubborn drinking problem to become one of country music's emerging stars along with <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Travis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoakam </PERSON>. `` I've been in this business for a long, long time,'' he said in an interview. `` But from the musical standpoint and a personal standpoint, we're really just at the beginning of my career.'' As a carefree teen in <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hook </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, he bought bootleg bourbon, poured it down his thirsty throat and then enjoyed challenging the rural roads at breathless speeds deep in <LOCATION> Appalachia </LOCATION>. `` Basically when I was growing up, the only thing we did for pastime was go to bootleggers and get something to drink and ride around and drink it and drive around and see how fast you could take those mountain curves,'' he recalled. At age 17, he was in a car with a companion who attempted to round a curve at 120 mph. The car wrecked, killing his friend. `` The doctor told me I came close to breaking my neck,'' said <PERSON> Whitley </PERSON>, who was cut but not hurt in the accident. At 19, he drove off a 120-foot cliff into a frozen river, escaping with a broken collarbone. `` There were a lot more less serious accidents and brushes with the law,'' he said. But always, he was intrigued by music. He played with <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON>'s band on the weekends as a teen-ager and later was lead singer for <PERSON> J.D </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> and the New South, a country-bluegrass band. After earning the reputation as a fine musician and singer, he moved to <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> in the mid-1980s and landed a recording contract with <ORGANIZATION> RCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION>. His hits besides `` Do n't Close Your Eyes'' include `` Miami My <PERSON> Amy </PERSON>,'' `` Ten Feet Away,'' `` Homecoming'63'' and `` Hard Livin.''' He quit drinking in 1987. `` It was a matter of life and death,'' he said. `` If I had n't stopped drinking, I do n't think I'd be alive today I did so many crazy things while drinking.'' <PERSON> Whitley </PERSON>, who is married to Grand Ole Opry singer <PERSON> Lorrie </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, said his lifestyle intensified his music. `` Not to sound conceited, but I've lived, breathed and cried this music since I was 3 or 4 years old,'' <PERSON> Whitley </PERSON> said. `` I take it very seriously. Most of the things I sing in my songs, I've lived `` I do n't wish the others would have to go through that. But I believe I've got the credentials to sing some of the things I sing about where some others do n't. `` The whole deal with my music has been the emotional quality. Songs I do have to strike an emotional chord the first time I sing them. It's not uncommon for me to get so wrapped up in a song that I cry several times when I sing them. That's the difference between my music and some of the other folks.'' His `` Do n't Close Your Eyes'' is about the desperation of love. `` People identified with it. Women seemed to like it and they are a big part of the record-buying public. At shows, people often come up to me and say they feel like it was written about them. `` The melody is real mournful. You can get lost emotionally singing it.'' One of the songs on the album is `` I Never Go Around Mirrors,'' a hit years ago by the late country star <PERSON> Lefty </PERSON> <PERSON> Frizzell </PERSON>. <PERSON> Whitley </PERSON> had a verse added to the song. A few hours before he recorded it, he visited <PERSON> Frizzell </PERSON>'s grave and wept. `` That sounds weird to people. But his music was very important to me growing up,'' <PERSON> Whitley </PERSON> said. People do n't understand why I did that, but it meant a lot to me.''
