<HEAD>Researchers Disagree Over Reported Genetic Sex Trigger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAR HARBOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Now that scientists have found the gene that makes a man a man, some of them would like to see equal rights for the gene that makes a woman a woman. Last winter, Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Page </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Whitehead </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, announced the discovery of what appears to be the male sex trigger _ a bit of genetic material that separates the boys from the girls. If Page is right, there is one sex switch. Those who get this gene at conception will be boys. Those who do n't will be girls. Page has offered a variety of explanations. But many scientists assume it means there is a gene for masculinity and not for femininity. One researcher who disagrees with this assumption is Dr. <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eicher </PERSON>, a geneticist at the <ORGANIZATION> Jackson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>. She said she has no quarrel with Page, only with how his discovery is interpretted. `` There is sexism in biology,'' <ORGANIZATION> Eicher </ORGANIZATION> said. `` There is no question about it. It influences the way that biologists approach problems, such as sex determination.'' Even the language of genetics, such as `` dominant'' and `` recessive,'' carry subconscious connotations about the roles of men and women, she said. According to her theory _ and she emphasizes it's only that _ the genetic library of the human race contains two sex genes. One contains the instructions for building boys, the other for making girls. She said many experts believe a maleness gene is necessary to make testis and all the internal and external sex organs of manhood. But for making females, only the absence of this gene is necessary. `` When it comes to sex, the active process is testis and the passive or default process is ovary,'' she said. `` I do n't think nature works by doing nothing. There has to be an active pathway'' to womanhood. Dr. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Clinical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Harrow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> agrees. `` It may be simple-minded to think that you have a switch to go down one pathway but nothing to go down the other,'' she said. Everybody is born with two strings of genes, known as sex chromosomes, that are called X and Y. Women have two X chromosomes, but men have an X and a Y. Page found the gene that seems to control maleness on the Y chromosome. But he also found a closely related gene on the X chromosome; nobody knows what that gene does. <ORGANIZATION> Eicher </ORGANIZATION> speculates that this is the female gene. The process might work like this: If an egg is fertilized by a `` male'' sperm, the sex gene on its Y chromosome kicks to life, starting a chain reaction of hormones that eventually direct the fetus to become a boy. Among its jobs is shutting off the female sex gene on the X chromosome. But if there is no Y sex gene, then a few hours later, the X sex gene turns on, starting the process toward womanhood. This is mostly speculation, although <ORGANIZATION> Eicher </ORGANIZATION> said she has found a hint in some strains of mice that something like this could be going on. But at least by challenging people's assumptions, she hopes to eventually get closer to the biological truth. `` We think we know so much,'' she said. `` What I am continually amazed by is that we know almost nothing.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 29</NOTE>
