<NOTE>For release Thursday, Sept. 29, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Much Ballyhooed Alternative to Pesticides Facing Uphill Struggle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennehy </PERSON> gets frustrated about the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>, he starts talking about Oreo cookies and milk. <PERSON> Dennehy </PERSON> says that if he believed Oreos could control insects and he wanted to dangle them in a field, the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> would force him to do a battery of tests to learn if the cookies were an environmental threat. `` At this point, I do n't know if that's an exaggeration,'' says <PERSON> Dennehy </PERSON>, who spent two years getting permits to test pheromones _ chemicals that insects produce to communicate _ as an alternative to pesticides. He and pheromone expert <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> <PERSON> Roelofs </PERSON> have devised a compound simulating the mating scent of female Grape Berry Moths. <PERSON> Dennehy </PERSON> says it is as safe `` as spraying milk'' on crops, can replace up to 12 pounds of insecticides, and does n't even kill the bugs it is meant to control. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Touhey </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> adviser, acknowledges that regulations for toxic pesticides are unnecessarily stringent for such non-toxic alternatives, but is confident that ways can be found to simplify the process. `` Pheromones are in their infancy in terms of practical use,'' says <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridgway </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Insect </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ecology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beltsville </LOCATION>, Md. About 250 pheromones have been identified since their discovery in 1959, and some are being used, <PERSON> Ridgway </PERSON> says, including one to control the cotton boll weevil and another on the Oriental fruit moth on <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> peaches. However, they never lived up to their early promise. Companies ca n't make enough profit because they only work for one species, limiting the market. They are not successful on pests that gather in great numbers, masking the scent. And research and development has run into regulatory roadblocks and apathy. <PERSON> Dennehy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Roelofs </PERSON> spent nearly two years getting a permit for a large-scale test. They had to learn legal jargon to explain what they wanted to do, track down the right forms and present pages of evidence and documentation required by the Federal Insecticide, Fungicide and Rodenticide Act. `` Our problem is that we have a non-toxic chemical being watched over by regulations for toxic chemicals,'' said <PERSON> Roelofs </PERSON>, who works with <PERSON> Dennehy </PERSON> at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Agricultural Experiment Station of <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Touhey </PERSON>, senior agricultural adviser to the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> office of pesticide programs, said, `` It seems the traditional mechanisms that were working in the past to regulate things does n't seem to be working now.'' In <PERSON> Dennehy </PERSON>'s experiment, male moths attracted to clear plastic twist-ties laced with the pheromone have trouble finding fertile females, thus preventing explosive growth of the bugs in the vineyard. He had sought a permit letting him use pheromones _ which have a chemical makeup similar to olive oil _ and sell the grapes. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said OK, but only if he destroyed the grapes, costing him $ 10,000 he might have earned. Then it said he could sell them. <PERSON> Dennehy </PERSON> expects to have results from his tests in 100 acres of grapes across <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> after the harvest. If they are favorable, the next step will be to get the pheromone on the market. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, who grows 275 acres of grapes in <ORGANIZATION> Westfield </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION>, said he would welcome a chance to stop using the pesticide Parathion. `` Any time we can eliminate using something that dangerous, I think it's a good thing.'' Under current rules, however, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> requires a study to determine environmental impact of the `` pesticide.'' That includes feeding it to ducks and shellfish, and could cost millions, <PERSON> Dennehy </PERSON> said. Both <PERSON> Touhey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ridgway </PERSON> believe a compromise can be reached that will make it easier for pheromones to reach farmers and growers. In some cases, tests could be waived, <PERSON> Touhey </PERSON> said. In others, the number of tests could be cut. Meanwhile, he's trying to help pheromone researchers get certain permits and guide them through the regulatory maze. And while theoretically Oreo cookies and milk used to `` control or mitigate'' insects would be pesticides, realistically the morass of regulations includes a waiver of tests, he said. `` But I get the point.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 29</NOTE>
