<HEAD>Heartworm Drug Can Prevent African Parasite Infection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A drug long used to free dogs of heartworms also apparently prevents a serious parasitic disease among visitors to some parts of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. An estimated 13 million people in western and central <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> are infected with loa loa, the African eyeworm, but loiasis, the disease it causes, is usually most severe among outsiders who visit <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The worm is spread by biting flies that feed on human blood, and is parasitic in or just under the skin, often migrating to around the eyes. The heartworm drug, diethylcarbamazine, kills the worm before the body mounts a strong immune response to it. The major consequences of the disease, including possible heart and kidney damage, result from the body's immune reaction to the worm. Doctors from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allergy </ORGANIZATION> and Infectious Diseases tested diethylcarbamazine on <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> volunteers in <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cameroon </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>. Forty-one took weekly doses of the medicine for two years, while 60 others took placebo pills. Six in the placebo group got loiasis, but none of the diethylcarbamazine users got sick. While the drug is considered safe, the doctors said it is not necessary for people who make brief visits to major cities in the region. The research team, headed by Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nutman </PERSON>, reported their findings recently in the New England Journal of Medicine.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Archaeologist Seeks To Market Obsidian, Glass Surgical Blades</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An archaeologist who cut himself 20 years ago on a 3,500-year-old obsidian blade thinks the Mayans had the right idea. Payson Sheets says obsidian blades can be 500 times sharper than steel, resulting in more exact cuts that heal quicker and with less scarring. He and ophthalmologist <PERSON> Firmon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardenbergh </PERSON> are seeking <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> permission to make and sell glass and obsidian surgical blades. Obsidian, formed when lava cools too quickly to crystallize, was traded throughout the <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION> by Indians as tool material. Unlike steel, Sheets says, the black, glassy material can be fractured to a few molecules thick. <PERSON> Hardenbergh </PERSON> uses the blades in cornea transplants and cataract surgery, and the partners have loaned obsidian and glass blades to other surgeons while they await <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> approval, Sheets says. That process could take more than a year. Sheets also is experimenting by mixing a hardening agent into molten glass so blades will hold a tougher and more consistent edge. He pours the molten glass into molds to make blades of different shapes and sizes.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Planned Building Will Display Effects of Wind, Quakes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Anyone nervous about the effects of wind or earthquakes on the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION>'s planned engineering building will have only to go down to the lobby and see what the building says. Instruments planted throughout the building when it is built beginning next summer will measure those forces and display them and the movements of machines and people on a computer-generated graphic display. `` We will put transducers in the beams and columns to measure varying loads and how the building responds to those loads,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, associate professor of civil engineering. `` Instruments that measure wind pressure will be installed so we can determine how the building is affected by wind, and how the real responses compare to the formulas we now use to design buildings. `` It will be a working laboratory. We will be able to make precise measurements of forces that before could only be estimated.'' The building can be used to `` demonstrate engineering mechanics principles, and as a research tool to learn more about design and construction and the long-term behavior of people,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said.
