<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0507</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Economists from major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporations are predicting the economy will slow next year. A panel of 60 economists from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economists </ORGANIZATION> indicated Monday it was bullish about growth this year, predicting an expansion of 3.9 percent as measured by gross national product. That's more optimistic than the administration's forecast of 3.5 percent. However, the median forecast for next year is an anemic 2.3 percent, substantially less than the administration forecast of 3.1 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of existing single-family homes rose a modest 1.1 percent in August to the second-highest level of the year, a real estate trade group says. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that sales of existing homes rose to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.67 million units last month, following a sharp 5.0 percent decline in July. Except for the 3.82 million rate in June, the August pace was the fastest in 15 months.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> says its `` collar'' restraint on computerized program trading will end on the anniversary of the Oct. 19 crash. The collar is to be replaced by previously announced measures designed to quell price volatility and restore investor confidence. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solodar </PERSON>, senior vice president of the nation's largest securities market, mentioned the termination Monday at a briefing aimed at reviewing the exchange's efforts to expand computer capacity and undertake other reforms in the year since the market panic.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's leading securities industry group says individual investors will shun the stock market until they see major reforms. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday in a statement that although the worst fears about the economy never materialized after the Oct. 19 collapse and market conditions have improved in some areas, `` the overall current environment is at best gray.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> have the best track record for creating new jobs and businesses and stimulating growth of young companies in the last four years, according to a new survey. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> magazine's annual report on the states concluded Monday that the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> are thriving, but indicated some industrial states are making a comeback thanks partly to programs that use small amounts of tax dollars to foster private growth.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> have given up on trying to raise the $ 3.35 minimum wage this year, conceding they lacked the 60 votes needed to break a Republican-led filibuster. `` There is no point in our continuing to pound on their door,'' <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said Monday The bill by Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., would have raised the wage floor, which has been stuck at its present level since 1981, to $ 3.75 in January, $ 4.15 in 1990 and $ 4.55 in 1991
</TEXT>
