<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Domtar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> say they will form a new company to recycle plastic bottles. The yet-unnamed 50-50 venture will retrieve from trash polyethylene terephthalate and high-density polyethylene plastics, which make up about 90 percent of the plastics used in bottles for milk, soft drinks, powdered detergents and a variety of other products. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Genson </PERSON>, business director for solid waste solutions for Dow, said Monday the new company would build a pilot plant and then a commercial plant as early as 1990 at a location in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> still to be decided.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The unemployment insurance system has enough reserves to last only five months in a severe recession and would have to borrow billions of dollars from the federal government to keep paying benefits, a congressional watchdog agency says. Because states had to borrow $ 11.8 billion to keep paying benefits during the 1981-82 recession, most have tightened eligibility requirements so much hat only one of every four jobless workers in October of last year received unemployment checks, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> says poor countries have been hurt by the recent rise in world interest rates and is urging stronger steps to ease their staggering foreign debt burdens. The policy-making arm of the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> also on Monday called for indebted countries to pursue policies that will spur growth and help `` restore domestic and foreign confidence.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market fell in a slow session Monday, pushing the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials down 5.51 points to 2,085.17. Bond prices slipped in light trading. The dollar rose against most other currencies in foreign exchange. Soybean futures prices plunged to their lowest close in nearly four months on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Grain futures finished lower, while sugar and cocoa futures fell sharply, livestock and meat futures were sharply higher, energy futures rose and precious metals were mixed.
