<FIRST>r f PM-ArgentinaDebt-Analysis Bjt   09-27 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Argentina Debt-Analysis, Bjt,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Long-Term Conditions Set For Argentinian Loans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new, long-term way of dealing with the Third World's crippling $ 1.2 trillion debt may be foreshadowed by $ 700 million worth of new loans the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> is offering to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. On the surface, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> seems a poor prospect for more loans. It already owes more than $ 49 billion, the biggest debt of any Third World country after <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. It should be paying $ 4.5 billion this year in interest alone, and already is about $ 1 billion behind in its payments. With interest rates rising, the bill may be $ 1 billion higher next year. The financial world is so skeptical about the prospects for repayment that Argentine loans can be bought for less than 22 cents on the dollar. Finance Minister <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sourrouille </PERSON> says he hopes to pay half the interest out of the country's own earnings. The rest he will have to borrow, presumably from many of the same banks that lent the original money. President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>'s government, the first one freely elected after years of military rule, faces an election in 1989. Many of his opponents, who are given an excellent chance to succeed him, are talking about suspending interest payments altogether. Yet the 151 governments in the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> probably will approve the new loans next month. The bank's sister organization, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, has been negotiating all summer with the Argentine government to make another $ 1.2 billion in loans. <PERSON> Sourrouille </PERSON> says negotiations should be completed in a couple of weeks, and he then will know how much to ask from the commercial banks _ probably more than $ 1 billion. Why all this new lending? It has a lot to do with an old banker's saying: `` Lend a man a thousand dollars and he's in your power; lend him a million and you're in his.'' The lenders keep on lending in the hope that <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and the other big debtors will use the money wisely, investing in new factories and farm equipment so they can earn more money from their exports and catch up with their bills. It's called `` growing out of financial difficulties.'' The lenders, all represented at the current fund and bank meetings in <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, see no other choice. The fund says the strategy is working well, and that the debtors' exports are growing faster than their debts. New loans are given under conditions usually tied to economic policies. If the borrower fails to meet them, the disbursements are cut off. Traditionally, the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> has taken the lead in setting the conditions, providing a `` seal of approval'' for other creditors. But the fund was set up originally to deal with short-term currency problems. The <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> is intended to aid long-term development of poor countries. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> is considered a `` middle-income'' country, with individual earnings averaging $ 2,370 a year _ compared with $ 120 in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> and $ 21,250 in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. But <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> has fallen on hard times and incomes have been declining through the 1980s. So the country is considered a candidate for basic improvements. Now, for the first time, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> has taken the lead in setting conditions, and many of them are conditions on long-term policy of a kind that the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> would not require. Sourrouille not only has promised to cut government spending sharply, but also is undertaking other changes basic to his country's economy. He has promised the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> he will strengthen the tax administration, reducing tax evasion and improving collections. He is attempting to improve the bank system, making the major public banks self-sustaining rather than dependent on government subsidies, and has promised new policies on trade and industry. There has been some grumbling. <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, the British chancellor of the exchequer, has warned against easing the conditions for loans. The <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> accord with <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> reportedly made some <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> people furious. But <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Camdessus </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> managing director, welcomed the agreement publicly. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and the fund are expected to agree on further conditions. Commercial banks presumably will come in with their loans, including new money for investment in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. The hope is that the new policies will put the country back on the road to the kind of prosperity it enjoyed before World War II. If they do, the new leadership by the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> may furnish a model for other countries in long-term trouble.
</TEXT>
