<HEAD>Business Economists Predicting Slowdown In 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Economists of major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies are predicting the economy will slow in 1989. A panel of 60 economists from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economists </ORGANIZATION> on Monday made a median forecast of 2.3 percent growth next year, substantially less than the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's forecast of 3.1 percent. Nearly half of the economists _ 47 percent _ said in a survey in late August and early September that they expected the country to topple into a recession by the end of next year. Another 42 percent believe a recession will occur in 1990. Only 11 percent believe the 6-year-old economic expansion will continue into 1991 or later. Separately, a trade group reported that sales of existing single-family homes increased a modest 1.1 percent in August as buyers tried to close purchases before interest rates rose further. Also Monday, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democrats gave up on trying to raise the minimum wage, and their staff issued a report charging the economy was producing mainly low-wage jobs. The home sales report by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said sales of existing homes rose after a sharp 5.0 percent decline in July. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Savacool </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, economic forecasting firm, said buyers completing sales in August probably began looking for homes in May and June. `` That was just after rates started rising,'' he said. The increase `` was a mild panic response to rising rates.'' In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> said a five-day Republican filibuster effectively had killed chances of raising the $ 3.35-an-hour minimum wage this year. `` There is no point in our continuing to pound on their door,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` I'm now conceding that the Republican filibuster was successful The Democratic staff of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said in its wage report that the proportions of both high-paying and low-paying jobs have grown in the 1980s. The report added fuel to an election-year debate over the quality of the 16 million new jobs added since President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> took office in 1981. The report said slightly more than 50 percent of the net increase in new jobs since 1979 paid a year-round, full-time equivalent less than $ 11,611, while 12 percent of them paid more than $ 46,444. Many of the low-wage jobs were held by people who were not the primary wage earners in their families. Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the committee's ranking Republican and former chairman, called the report `` opportunistic and political.''
</TEXT>
