<FIRST>r f PM-Crash-Reforms Bjt   09-27 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Crash-Reforms, Bjt,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>NYSE Seeking SEC Approval of Reforms By Black Monday Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> hopes its post-crash reform package announced earlier this year will receive government approval by the anniversary of the Oct. 19 market rout, but federal regulators are n't making promises. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Solodar </PERSON>, senior vice president of the largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stock market, said Monday the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> actively was reviewing the reform proposals, devised jointly with the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The reforms would supercede the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s temporary `` collar'' restraint on computerized program trading, a six-month experiment approved by the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> last April 20 that was aimed at calming wild price swings. The collar expires Oct. 19, the anniversary of the crash. Speaking to reporters at an <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> briefing about steps taken to improve the climate for stock trading since the crash, <PERSON> Solodar </PERSON> said it was possible the new reforms would not be in place by the anniversary, but `` we believe the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> will approve them.'' In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> officials declined to specify when the reforms would be approved. They were announced in July, but not filed with the regulatory agency until late August. `` The staff is actively reviewing these matters and is trying to expedite its review consistent with the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> request,'' said <PERSON> Brendon </PERSON> <PERSON> Becker </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> associate director of market regulation. Market regulatory officials have said privately that potential complications have arisen because other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> securities markets dislike the proposed reforms. For example, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION>, which supervises over-the-counter trading, has expressed opposition to them. Under the reforms, the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> markets agreed on a one-year pilot program for what they called coordinated `` circuit breakers'' that would halt trading temporarily if price moves exceeded preset limits. The halts would be triggered in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> by a 250-point move in the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks and in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> by a 12-point move in the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 stock-index futures contract. The reforms also call for tighter communication between the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> exchanges and a common policy on `` intermarket front-running,'' an abuse in which traders are able to take a profitable position in one market based on what they know will happen in another market. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> also has prepared what it calls an `` <ORGANIZATION> Individual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delivery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>,'' which will provide transmission priority to individual investor orders when the Dow average moves 25 points from its previous close. This reform was designed to reassure investors that their orders will receive equal treatment with those from large institutional investors. On Black Monday, many individuals complained they could not sell their stock because larger investors were served first. <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> officials conceded at the Monday briefing that individual investors remain unwilling to re-enter the stock market, which has failed to recoup much of the loss from the crash and has been plagued by low trading volume. Asked to speculate when individuals would regain the confidence to invest in stocks, <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Grasso </PERSON> said: `` That is beyond my crystal ball at the moment.'' A bleak assessment of when individual investor confidence also was offered Monday in a post-crash review by <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assocation </ORGANIZATION>, a leading Wall Street trade group. <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said in a statement that although the worst fears about the economy never materialized after the collapse and market conditions have improved in some areas, `` the overall current environment is at best gray.'' He said the <ORGANIZATION> SIA </ORGANIZATION> `` believes the near-term outlook is n't likely to improve substantially until full investor confidence is restored in both the integrity of the marketplace and the strength of the economy.'' <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> also said there have been a few steps to correct problems exposed as a result of the crash, `` but major regulatory reform has n't taken place.''
