<HEAD>Industry Survey Finds 40 Percent Pay Bank Credit Cards In Full
Each Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> says changing tax laws are prompting more consumers to pay their credit card balances in full each month. A new survey by the industry trade group indicates 40 percent of consumers pay their monthly card bills in full, up from about 33 percent last year. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, vice chairman of <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Retail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Card </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION>, said the increase stemmed from the federal tax law, which is phasing out credit card interest deductions over a four-year period ending in 1991. The study, released Monday, also found that overall growth in the bank credit card business had slowed because of stiff competition from other issuers, such as <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>. `` The survey results reflect the fierce competition among bank card issuers,'' said <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>. `` The range of prices and card features gives consumers a virtually unlimited number of options.'' The number of Visa and <ORGANIZATION> MasterCard </ORGANIZATION> cardholders grew by about 9 percent last year, a slowdown in the rate of previous years, according to <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>. Visa and <ORGANIZATION> MasterCard </ORGANIZATION>, both bank-owned credit card associations, represent 60 percent of the bank credit card market. `` We've seen the entrance of significant new competition over the last couple of years,'' said <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, who also is executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Signet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION>. The report found consumers charged more than $ 165 billion on their bank cards last year, an increase of 18.8 percent for <ORGANIZATION> Mastercard </ORGANIZATION> and 12.3 percent for Visa. The <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> report was based on a survey of 1,444 card-issuing banks selected from a national sample based on asset size and includes 1987 and first quarter 1988 data on bank card interest rates, fees, marketing and operations. The number of banks charging the maximum interest rate allowed in their states declined to less than one-fourth, according to <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, who attributed the drop to increased market competition. Banks that charged the maximum rate included 18 percent of banks with assets under $ 300 million and 27 percent of large banks with assets above $ 1 billion, the report said. In comparison, last year's report found that 35 percent of the large banks, with assets above $ 1 billion, charged the maximum rate. That report also showed that about 26 percent of banks with assets below $ 500 million charged the highest rate allowed in their states. The <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> is the national trade and professional association for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> full service banks of all sizes. The bank card conference runs through Wednesday.
