<TEXT>
 Finance Minister <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuo </PERSON> said Tuesday the reimposition of a capital-gains tax on stock profits next year is meant to maintain a fair taxation system despite investors' worries the levy would trigger a market slump `` It is not government intervention. We merely want to make it fair to all taxpayers,'' <PERSON> Kuo </PERSON> told a news conference. On Saturday, <PERSON> Kuo </PERSON> announced the government would reimpose the tax on stock profits next year after a 12-year freeze. Individual investors who sell stocks worth more than 3 million <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> dollars, or $ 103,448, should include the stock income when filing their annual income tax, she said. Observers said the surprise move, timed before the four-day, Mid-Autumn Festival holiday, was designed to cool down the stock market. `` There will surely be heavy selling pressure when it re-opens Thursday,'' said <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd </ORGANIZATION>.
