<SECOND>PM-Merc Rules,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Pact For Innovative Margin Rules Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and the nation's largest options clearing house have reached an agreement on new rules to ease the strain on the system caused by heavy trading, officials said The agreement between the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> and Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Options </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clearing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, announced Monday calls for cross-margining on certain stock index futures and options accounts. Margins are deposits paid by traders to cover the risk of daily losses. Cross margining allows traders to have credit for trading positions that reduce their risk of loss. Under the plan, traders who have protected their positions by hedging in both markets would have to put up less money for their margins. The practice was recommended by a presidential commission that investigated last October's stock market crash and must be approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Commodities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Officials from the <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and Options Clearing, the nation's largest options clearing house, have been working on the cross-margining program for about a year. Had cross-margining been permitted during the huge decline in the stock market on Oct. 19, it would have reduced the strain on the nation's financial system and eased demands for cash on several major banks that ran into billions of dollars a day.
</TEXT>
