`` A penny a day so that working parents wo n't lose their jobs when they care for a newborn ... when they must care for a seriously ill child,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. `` I put the choice to the opponents of this bill _ can you spare a penny a day for these children? Or is this economic expansion so fragile that a penny a day will do us in?'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said he had received three veto letters from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration on the family leave bill. <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> appealed Monday for bipartisan support from his colleagues and from Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the Republican presidential nominee. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the Democratic presidential nominee, already has endorsed the Dodd approach. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said women should n't have to worry about getting their jobs back after a maternity leave but has not issued a detailed proposal. He is said to favor a voluntary approach involving tax breaks for businesses that offer job-protected leaves. Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, R-Ind., the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential nominee, opposed the Dodd bill in committee <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> work on the parental leave bill came as the chamber's <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leaders on Monday gave up all hope of passing legislation to increase the minimum wage this year, conceding defeat to a Republican filibuster
