<FIRST>r f BC-ForkliftDumping     09-27 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Forklift Dumping,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Alleges Japan Trying To Evade Duties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Hyster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> contends that its Japanese competitors now are `` dumping'' forklift parts in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in an effort to evade new <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> customs duties imposed on them for selling complete forklifts below cost. After a yearlong battle by <PERSON> Hyster </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government decided last spring to impose customs duties ranging as high as 50 percent on the imports. The company now alleges that the Japanese are trying to circumvent those duties by importing the vehicles in pieces and assembling them in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Hyster officials say they have collected data that show imports of forklift parts have nearly doubled this year compared to last year. In a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> administrators, Hyster notes <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> statistics list truck part imports at $ 16.7 million in the first six months of 1987. This year those imports jumped to $ 34.9 million. The company asks the government to determine whether trucks assembled in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> also should be subject to the duties. Hyster notes in its letter that the new trade law allows federal officials to assess duties against companies that simply switch from dumping finished products to dumping parts, which then are assembled in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or in a third country. In a similar case involving dumping televisions in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION>, the government decided imported parts that were assembled in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> also were subject to dumping duties.
