<HEAD>Data General Consolidates Various Functions to Save $50 Million
Annually</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTBORO, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> announced Tuesday that it will take a charge of about $ 45 million against operations in its fourth quarter and consolidate various functions to save the company $ 50 million annually and cut 800 jobs. The new job cuts bring to about 4,000 the number of jobs cut since 1985. `` The company is committed to being a highly efficient, low-cost producer and because of advances in technology and productivity, that means fewer people in manufacturing,'' said <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Skates </PERSON>, executive vice-president and chief operating officer. `` We see ongoing and tough cost management as a way of life for Data General.'' The company said it has made arrangements for outplacement services and pay and benefits continuation based on years of service of affected employees. The company employs more than 15,000 people world-wide. The current fourth-quarter earnings report is not yet available, the company said. For the first nine months ending June 25, earnings were $ 31.5 million, or $ 1.06 per share, on revenues of $ 1.02 billion. For the comparable 1987 period, the company reported a loss of $ 104.4 million on revenues of $ 942.1 million.
