<HEAD>Coffee Futures Surge On Signs Of International Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Coffee futures prices surged Tuesday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on indications that a new coffee price-support agreement was near. On other markets, sugar futures soared; energy futures retreated; copper and precious metals advanced; frozen pork bellies plunged; livestock were mixed; grains and soybeans were mixed; and stock-index futures retreated. News arrived in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> at midday from the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>'s meeting in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> that <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, respectively the world's No. 1 and No. 2 coffee producers, had proposed an initial global export quota of 54 million bags for the 1988-89 marketing year. The reports sparked high-volume buying of coffee futures by roasters and speculators on ideas that the proposal could become the cornerstone of a new ICO agreement for stabilizing coffee prices in the upcoming marketing year, which begins Oct. 1. `` This was significant not only in that these two countries have agreed on something but in that it sets the tone for the conference as a whole,'' said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON>, coffee market analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` It indicates the meeting is progressing harmoniously.'' Under the proposal, coffee producers would limit sales to <ORGANIZATION> ICO </ORGANIZATION> consumers to 54 million bags during the marketing year, compared with this year's initial quota of 58 million bags. The ICO can adjust the quota upward or downward during the year, depending on market conditions, to keep prices stable. Global coffee consumption is declining, but demand for higher-priced `` mild'' coffees _ as opposed to the more plentiful `` robusta'' coffees _ is on the rise. <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON> said consumer nations might agree to the lower quota, which would tend to support prices, if producers agree to increase the percentage of milds in the export mix. Coffee settled 2.15 to 2.83 cents higher with the contract for delivery in December at $ 1.2924 a pound. Sugar futures recovered nearly all of Monday's sharp losses on buying inspired by technical factors and rumors of physical sugar purchases by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON> said. Sugar settled .37 cent to .69 cent higher with October at 9.86 cents a pound. Crude oil futures dipped to 2-year lows below $ 14 a barrel early in the session on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> but recovered to finish only slightly lower than Monday's final prices. Analysts linked the early weakness to reports of continued discount sales of crude by <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and pessimism about <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s search for a solution to the overproduction that has been blamed for the persistent weakness of crude oil prices West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 6 cents to 15 cents lower with November at $ 14.14 a barrel; heating oil was .55 cent to .72 cent lower with October at 39.51 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .45 cent lower to .34 cent higher with October at 45.59 cents a gallon. Copper futures posted new contract highs in most delivery months for the fourth straight day on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on continuing concern about tight supplies and rising demand. Copper settled 1.20 cents to 1.80 cents higher with September at $ 1.214 a pound. Precious metals futures also advanced on the Comex, buoyed by the stability in the oil market, analysts said. Gold settled $ 2.10 to $ 3 higher with October at $ 397.90 a troy ounce; silver was 5.5 cents to 6 cents higher with September at $ 6.166 a troy ounce. Frozen pork bellies for February and May delivery settled down the allowable daily limit of 2 cents a pound on a technically-inspired selloff on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, analysts said. Hog futures retreated on position-evening ahead of Friday's quarterly hogs-and-pigs report from the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, while cattle finishednarrowly mixed Live cattle were .20 cent lower to .38 cent higher with October at 70.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .37 cent lower to .15 cent higher with September at 79.80 cents a pound; hogs were .38 cent to .63 cent lower with October at 39.92 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.10 cents to 2 cents lower with February at 50.10 cents a pound. Most corn futures finished moderately to sharply higher in a late rally on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> after an expected increase in farmer selling of newly harvested corn failed to emerge. Soybean futures advanced with the corn market, but wheat moved slightly lower amid slack export demand, analysts said. Wheat settled -LCB- cent to 1 cent lower with December at $ 4.21 -RCB- a bushel; corn was -RCB- cent lower to 5 -RCB- cents higher with December at $ 2.86 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 1 -LCB- cents lower to 2 -LCB- cents higher with December 